rification is mandated where applicable, and manual PAN entry must be validated before onboarding proceeds. This identity validation process is explicitly described in onboarding journeys that support minor onboarding and PAN verification workflows. \n- Documentation artifacts involved: identity documents, PAN where applicable, and guardian PAN details for minors. In practice, certain onboarding flows require PAN verification to be completed before the customer card can be progressed. \n\n## 2) KYC / AML risk assessment\n- Ensure KYC status is in an actionable state (e.g., KYC Registered or Under Process) before onboarding; other statuses typically block onboarding (hard stop in practice). The KYC status field and its possible values are captured in onboarding profiles. \n- Conduct AML risk screening as part of regulatory validations, typically via an AML screening service integration (e.g., Trinity AMLA). This forms the core of risk and compliance checks during onboarding. \n- Documentation: KYC/identity documentation, and KYC status history; AML screening results and log of risk assessment outcomes. \n\n## 3) Sanctions screening and risk-mitigation checks\n- Sanctions/AML screening is encompassed within the broader AML risk and regulatory validation workflow and is supported by AML screening integrations referenced in onboarding flows. Ensure sanctions-related flags or hits trigger escalation and holds as part of the risk engine gating. \n- Documentation: AML screening results, any corresponding adverse alerts, and remediation actions taken. \n\n## 4) Source of funds / Source of wealth (SoW)\n- Capture and validate the source of wealth to support risk profiling and regulatory compliance. SoW data is collected as part of the onboarding profile and is used to assess risk and determine suitability. \n- Documentation: SoW declarations and any corroborating supporting documents as required by the risk policy. \n\n## 5) Document validation and upload\n- Document upload is mandatory; onboarding flows enforce mandatory document submission (e.g., identity proofs, photographs, signatures). Validation ensures all required fields/files are provided before proceeding. \n- Specific document capture controls include mandatory photo and signature uploads, with explicit checks for required fields. \n- Documentation: identity documents, address proofs, photos, signatures, and any other regulatory documents required by the identity/KYC program. \n\n## 6) Data accuracy and field validations\n- Enforce mandatory field verification to ensure all required fields are completed (e.g., on onboarding forms). This includes validation of formats (e.g., identification numbers, dates) and consistency across related fields (e.g., guardian details for minors when applicable). \n- Maintain accurate and current KYC status and profile attributes (e.g., tax status, AML status, source of wealth) as part of the onboarding data model. \n\n## 7) Consent capture\n- While not always spelled out explicitly in the cited documents, consent capture is a standard prerequisite in compliant onboarding processes (data usage, communications, and AML/KYC disclosures). Align onboarding flows to record explicit consent where required by policy and regulation. [Documentation in the provided materials focuses on data collection and risk flags; ensure policy-based consent is implemented in your platform and captured in the onboarding record.] \n\n## 8) Approvals and governance\n- Supervisor approval or supervisory-level assessment is an established governance control in onboarding workflows, with self-assessment and supervisor-review patterns described in governance/approval journey documents. Ensure that onboarding records route to the appropriate approver and that approvals are logged. \n\n## 9) Module mapping (generic, platform-agnostic)\n- Onboarding module: orchestrates the end-to-end process and gates progression on the validations above. Supports mandatory-field checks, identity capture, KYC status gating, and document upload enforcement.\n- Identity verification service: dedicated subsystem that performs identity proofing, PAN verification, and guardian-relationship checks for minors where applicable (e.g., guardian PAN checks and age validation). \n- Risk engine / AML service: handles KYC risk scoring, AML screening, sanctions screening, and source-of-wealth validation as part of the risk and compliance workflow. \n- Documentation management: stores and validates required documents (photos, signatures, identity proofs, SoW proofs). \n\n## 10) Required documentation checklist (illustrative)\n- Identity documents (government ID, PAN where applicable) and guardian details for minors (if relevant). \n- Proof of address and date of birth, as required by the KYC program. \n- Source of wealth / wealth declaration documents. \n- Photographs and signatures (for onboarding records). \n- KYC-related status history and AML screening results. \n\nNotes and care points:\n- The onboarding flow commonly uses a hard gating rule around KYC status (e.g., only proceed if KYC is Registered or Under Process); ensure you enforce this gating in the onboarding logic. \n- Minor onboarding requires guardian details, and guardian PAN validation; guardian must be an existing wealth customer with primary status. \n- Regulatory validations and AML screening are integrated via AML screening services (e.g., Trinity AMLA) as part of the risk checks during onboarding. \n- Document upload and mandatory-field validations are enforced as part of the onboarding data capture to prevent incomplete submissions. 	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Identity","KYC Compliance information","KYC status validation","System would validate if KYC status in Customer Profile Details is other than “KYC REGISTERED” or “UNDER PROCESS” there would be a hard stop","document upload is mandatory","Supervisor Approval","KYC UPDATION OVERDUE IN ACCO