586,-0.03984154,-0.022014312,0.04672583,0.028898602,-0.0069549303,-0.023131726,0.001703412,-0.015258462,0.029540794,-0.01619606,0.004720105,-0.018212542,0.022515222,0.011283299,-0.019342797,0.0020020308,0.010865875,0.008046655,-0.016504312,-0.0069356645,0.016183218,-0.0145135205,-0.006659522,0.008663159,0.0052659675,-0.011553019,-0.018572168,-0.016440094,0.01252915,-0.008541143,0.019715268,-0.024236294,0.03002886,-0.010576888,0.0107759675,-0.029155478,0.024364732,0.017917134,0.004154977,-0.026894966,0.018340979,-0.0041581877,0.12494471,-0.010698904,-0.0046655186,0.013473171,-0.018893264,-8.749854e-05,0.0028577507,0.00013686699,0.04343781,-0.0077448254,-0.01773732,0.0074429954,-0.0023809236,0.039661724,0.013049324,0.026381213,0.021795968,0.007629231,-0.034010444,0.0013775,-0.0068521798,0.023619791,0.025572052,0.027999535,-0.00017710427,-0.0015035301,0.021924406,0.029412355,0.0075778556,-0.023568416,-0.019060234,-0.013049324,0.004935239,0.01925289,0.0064154896,0.026381213,-0.016504312,0.013550233,-0.027100466,-0.008611783,0.02039599,0.00078989513,-0.040021352,-0.009350304,-0.020267554,-0.006698054,0.016029092,0.003769662,0.004768269,-0.0065086074,0.025340863,-0.03282881,-0.031518742,-0.011944756,0.012400711,0.01162366,0.024518859,-0.011867693,0.023273008,-0.011719989,-0.030850863,1.1564458e-05,0.0027437618,0.026638089,0.009151224]	deep	# Business Requirements Document (BRD)  \n**Module:** Retirement Planning  \n**Application:** Wealth Management Platform  \n\n---\n\n## 1. Purpose, Scope, and Objectives\n\n### 1.1 Purpose\nDefine the business and system requirements for a new Retirement Planning module that allows clients and advisors to create, implement, and monitor retirement plans within the wealth management application.\n\n### 1.2 Scope\nIn scope:\n\n- Retirement goal definition and planning\n- Projection of retirement corpus and income\n- Scenario analysis and plan refinement\n- Contribution and withdrawal strategy modeling\n- Investment allocation recommendations\n- Integration with existing client data, holdings, and order execution\n- Ongoing monitoring, alerts, and reporting\n- Compliance, audit, and regulatory support\n\nOut of scope (for this BRD):\n\n- Detailed design of third‑party planning engines (if any)\n- Non‑retirement goal planning (education, housing, etc.) beyond reusability considerations\n\n### 1.3 Business Objectives\n\n- Enable clients and advisors to determine required savings and investment strategies to achieve a target retirement income or corpus.\n- Leverage existing client data (demographics, holdings, income, risk profile) to streamline planning.\n- Ensure plans are aligned with risk tolerance, time horizon, and regulatory constraints.\n- Increase client engagement and AUM through actionable, trackable retirement plans.\n- Provide robust auditability and compliance with applicable financial and data protection regulations.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Stakeholders\n\n- **Clients / End Users**  \n  Use the module to set retirement goals, view projections, and track progress.\n\n- **Relationship Managers / Advisors**  \n  Create, adjust, and review retirement plans for clients; initiate implementation and monitor plans.\n\n- **Product / Portfolio Managers**  \n  Define model portfolios, asset allocation models, and capital market assumptions used in planning.\n\n- **Compliance & Risk Officers**  \n  Ensure suitability, regulatory compliance, proper disclosures, and record‑keeping.\n\n- **IT / System Administrators / Operations**  \n  Manage configuration, integrations, performance, security, and operational monitoring.\n\n- **Management / Business Owners**  \n  Track adoption, business impact, and ensure alignment with strategic objectives.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Data Requirements\n\nThe module must consume and maintain the following data:\n\n### 3.1 Client Demographics\n\n- Date of birth / current age\n- Planned retirement age\n- Life expectancy (defaulted or configurable)\n- Marital status, dependents (for needs estimation)\n\n### 3.2 Financial Profile\n\n- Current income and expected income growth (optional)\n- Current savings and investment balances (including retirement accounts)\n- Existing pensions / social security / employer retirement benefits (if available)\n- Current and estimated retirement expenses (or target retirement income)\n\n### 3.3 Retirement Goal Details\n\n- Goal type: Retirement\n- Target retirement age or year\n- Target retirement income (per month/year) and/or target corpus\n- Desired lifestyle or specific sub‑goals (e.g., travel fund) – optional\n\n### 3.4 Risk Profile\n\n- Current risk rating / score\n- Date of last risk assessment; flag if outdated\n- Risk profile questionnaire results (for audit)\n\n### 3.5 Market & Economic Assumptions\n\n- Inflation rate assumptions\n- Expected returns by asset class / model portfolio\n- Volatility assumptions (for advanced analysis, if applicable)\n- Tax rate assumptions (income, capital gains, retirement account rules)\n\n### 3.6 Regulatory / Tax Data\n\n- Contribution limits for tax‑advantaged accounts\n- Tax treatment of contributions, growth, and withdrawals\n- Jurisdiction‑specific projection or disclosure rules (configurable)\n\n### 3.7 Investment Models\n\n- Model portfolios / asset allocation models by:\n  - Risk profile\n  - Time to retirement\n  - Goal type (retirement)\n- Approved product universe (funds, ETFs, etc.) with constraints (min amounts, eligibility)\n\n### 3.8 Existing Holdings & Transactions\n\n- Account and holdings data from custodians / portfolio system\n- Historical and ongoing contributions and withdrawals relevant to retirement\n\n---\n\n## 4. Functional Requirements\n\n### 4.1 Retirement Goal Setup\n\n- Allow creation of a new “Retirement” goal for a client.\n- Pre‑fill demographic and financial data from client profile and holdings.\n- Validate key inputs (e.g., retirement age > current age; numeric ranges).\n- Support multiple retirement goals per client only if business policy allows (e.g., separate goals for spouses); otherwise enforce single primary retirement goal.\n\n### 4.2 Projection Calculations\n\n- Calculate required retirement corpus to support target income, considering:\n  - Inflation\n  - Retirement duration (based on life expectancy)\n- Calculate required periodic contributions (monthly/quarterly/annual) to reach corpus, considering:\n  - Current savings\n  - Expected returns based on chosen allocation\n- Provide transparent assumptions and formulas (documented and visible to users).\n\n### 4.3 Scenario Planning\n\n- Allow users to create and compare multiple scenarios by varying:\n  - Retirement age\n  - Contribution amount and frequency\n  - Target income / corpus\n  - Return assumptions (within compliance‑approved ranges)\n- Display scenario outcomes side‑by‑side (corpus at retirement, probability of success if applicable, surplus/shortfall).\n\n### 4.4 Contribution Planning\n\n- Support:\n  - Lump‑sum contributions\n  - Systematic Investment Plans (SIPs) with configurable frequency\n  - Contribution escalation (e.g., X% per year)\n- Enforce regulatory and product‑specific contribution limits; warn or block when exceeded.\n- Display contribution schedule and cumulative contributions over time.\n\n### 4.5 Withdrawal Strategy Modeling\n\n- Model post‑retirement drawdown strategies, including:\n  - Fixed periodic withdrawals (SWP)\n  - Percentage‑of‑portfolio withdrawals\n  - Annuity purchase (if supported by product set)\n- Show sustainability of desired income over retirement horizon under chosen strategy.\n- Consider post‑retirement investment growth and inflation.\n\n### 4.6 Tax Considerations\n\n- Apply tax rules to:\n  - Contributions (deductibility, caps)\n  - Investment growth (tax‑deferred, tax‑free, taxable)\n  - Withdrawals (taxable vs non‑taxable portions)\n- Support jurisdiction‑specific and account‑type‑specific rules via configurable logic or integration with a tax engine.\n- Present net (after‑tax) income projections where applicable.\n\n### 4.7 Investment Allocation Recommendations\n\n- Recommend asset allocation based on:\n  - Risk profile\n  - Time to retirement\n  - Firm‑defined models for retirement goals\n- Map allocation to approved products or model portfolios.\n- Allow limited user/advisor adjustments within risk and compliance constraints.\n- Recalculate projections when allocation is changed.\n\n### 4.8 Plan Review and Adjustment\n\n- Allow editing of existing plans:\n  - Update income, contributions, retirement age, assumptions, allocation.\n- Maintain version history:\n  - Who changed what, when, and why (optional comment).\n- Optionally require approvals for material changes (see 4.11).\n\n### 4.9 Progress Tracking\n\n- Track:\n  - Actual contributions vs planned contributions\n  - Current portfolio value vs projected value\n- Show status indicators (e.g., On Track / Slightly Off Track / Off Track).\n- Suggest remedial actions (e.g., increase contributions, adjust retirement age) when off track.\n\n### 4.10 Alerts and Reminders\n\n- Generate alerts for:\n  - Missed or delayed contributions (if not automated)\n  - Significant deviation from expected portfolio performance\n  - Upcoming plan review dates\n  - Approaching retirement date\n- Deliver via in‑app notifications and, where configured, email/SMS.\n\n### 4.11 Approval Workflow\n\n- Support plan statuses: Draft, Pending Approval, Approved, Active, In Retirement, Closed.\n- Configurable rules for when approvals are required, e.g.:\n  - Risk profile overrides\n  - Use of non‑standard assumptions\n  - Large deviations from model portfolios\n- Notify relevant parties (client, advisor, supervisor) at each workflow step.\n\n### 4.12 Integration with Order Execution\n\n- From an approved plan, allow:\n  - Creation of SIP orders aligned with contribution plan.\n  - Creation of SWP or redemption instructions for drawdown phase.\n- Pass plan identifier to OMS / RTA for traceability.\n- Receive and store order references and status updates.\n- Support modification/cancellation of orders when plan parameters change.\n\n### 4.13 Documentation and Reports\n\n- Generate client‑facing “Retirement Plan Summary” (PDF or equivalent) including:\n  - Inputs and assumptions\n  - Projections and charts\n  - Recommended contributions and allocation\n  - Disclaimers and methodology notes\n- Support draft and final versions (e.g., watermark “Draft” where applicable).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Non‑Functional Requirements\n\n### 5.1 Security & Privacy\n\n- Encrypt data at rest and in transit.\n- Enforce role‑based access control:\n  - Clients see only their own plans.\n  - Advisors see only assigned clients.\n- Log access to sensitive data and report downloads.\n- Comply with applicable data protection laws (e.g., GDPR) and internal policies.\n\n### 5.2 Performance\n\n- Typical plan calculation and scenario updates should complete within ~2 seconds under normal load.\n- System must support concurrent use by advisors and clients at expected peak loads (to be defined by capacity planning).\n\n### 5.3 Availability & Reliability\n\n- High availability for core planning and calculation services.\n- Graceful degradation if non‑critical integrations (e.g., real‑time market data) are temporarily unavailable (e.g., use last known values with clear indication).\n\n### 5.4 Auditability\n\n- Maintain detailed audit logs for:\n  - Plan creation, updates, approvals, and closures\n  - Changes to assumptions and risk overrides\n  - Orders initiated from plans\n- Logs must be queryable by compliance and retained per regulatory requirements.\n\n### 5.5 Regulatory Compliance\n\n- Support jurisdiction‑specific rules on:\n  - Projection assumptions and ranges\n  - Disclosure and disclaimers\n  - Suitability and risk profiling\n- Prevent bypass of mandatory risk profiling and required disclosures.\n\n### 5.6 Usability & Accessibility\n\n- Intuitive, guided workflows (wizard‑style) for data entry and scenario analysis.\n- Clear visualizations (charts, progress bars) with plain‑language explanations.\n- Comply with WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility standards where feasible.\n\n### 5.7 Scalability\n\n- Architecture must support:\n  - Growth in number of users and plans\n  - Potential reuse of planning engine for other goal types\n- Efficient storage and archiving strategy for historical plan versions and projections.\n\n### 5.8 Maintainability & Extensibility\n\n- Modular design:\n  - Separate calculation engine, UI, integration layer, and configuration.\n- Business rules and assumptions configurable without code changes where possible.\n- Clear documentation of formulas, rules, and data structures.\n\n---\n\n## 6. End‑to‑End Workflows\n\n### 6.1 New Plan Creation\n\n1. **Initiate**  \n   User selects “Add Goal” → “Retirement” from Goals/Planning section.\n2. **Prerequisite Checks**  \n   System verifies presence and freshness of risk profile and basic client data; prompts completion if missing.\n3. **Data Entry (Wizard)**  \n   - Step 1: Confirm personal details (age, marital status, dependents).  \n   - Step 2: Set retirement age and target income/corpus.  \n   - Step 3: Confirm current savings and contributions (pre‑filled from holdings; user can adjust).  \n   - Step 4: Confirm risk profile and investment preferences (if applicable).\n4. **Validation**  \n   System validates inputs and displays any warnings (e.g., aggressive targets).\n5. **Calculation**  \n   System fetches assumptions and runs projection engine.\n6. **Results Display**  \n   Show required corpus, required contributions, charts, and recommended allocation.\n7. **Scenario Refinement**  \n   User adjusts key parameters and compares scenarios.\n8. **Finalization**  \n   User selects preferred scenario, confirms disclosures, and saves plan (Draft/Pending Approval/Active as per workflow).\n9. **Implementation Prompt**  \n   System offers to set up SIPs or other orders aligned with the plan.\n\n### 6.2 Implementation of Investments\n\n1. User chooses to implement plan.\n2. System proposes specific products and contribution splits based on recommended allocation.\n3. User confirms funding source and schedule.\n4. System sends orders to OMS/RTA and stores order references.\n5. Plan status updated to “Active – Implemented”.\n\n### 6.3 Monitoring and Review\n\n1. Periodic updates of holdings and valuations from portfolio system.\n2. System recalculates projected outcomes vs original plan.\n3. Dashboard shows status (On Track / Off Track) and key metrics.\n4. Alerts generated for review triggers (e.g., off‑track, annual review).\n5. Advisor/client initiates review, edits plan, and (if needed) adjusts orders.\n\n### 6.4 Retirement and Drawdown\n\n1. As retirement approaches, system notifies advisor/client.\n2. User configures withdrawal strategy (SWP, annuity, etc.).\n3. System sets up corresponding orders and transitions plan to “In Retirement”.\n4. Ongoing monitoring of withdrawals, portfolio value, and sustainability.\n\n### 6.5 Plan Completion\n\n- Plan is marked “Closed” when:\n  - Client passes away, funds exhausted, or goal terminated.\n- Final summary generated and archived.\n\n---\n\n## 7. User Interface & User Journey (High‑Level)\n\n### 7.1 Entry Points\n\n- Clients: “Goals” / “Planning” menu → “Retirement Planner”.\n- Advisors: From client profile → “Financial Planning” → “Retirement”.\n\n### 7.2 Data Input\n\n- Multi‑step wizard with:\n  - Progress indicator\n  - Contextual help / tooltips\n  - Pre‑filled fields where possible\n\n### 7.3 Plan Summary & Visualization\n\n- Key metrics:\n  - Target corpus\n  - Required contribution\n  - Projected retirement income\n- Charts:\n  - Accumulation curve (contributions vs growth)\n  - Drawdown curve (portfolio balance over retirement)\n- Asset allocation pie chart and product list.\n\n### 7.4 Scenario Tools\n\n- Inline controls (sliders/fields) for:\n  - Retirement age\n  - Contribution amount\n  - Target income\n- Option to save and compare multiple scenarios.\n\n### 7.5 Plan Detail View (Ongoing)\n\n- Snapshot: time to retirement, status, progress bar.\n- Original vs current projection overlay.\n- “Edit Plan”, “Download Report”, “View Linked Orders” actions.\n\n### 7.6 Error Handling & Help\n\n- Clear, user‑friendly error messages.\n- Links to FAQs / help content on:\n  - How projections are calculated\n  - Meaning of “on track”\n  - Key assumptions\n\n---\n\n## 8. Data Flows and Integrations\n\n### 8.1 Client Profile / CRM\n\n- Read:\n  - Demographics\n  - Risk profile\n  - Advisor–client relationships\n- Update:\n  - Flags indicating presence of a retirement plan (for CRM views).\n\n### 8.2 Portfolio / Holdings\n\n- Read:\n  - Accounts and balances\n  - Transaction history relevant to retirement contributions\n- Ongoing:\n  - Daily or near‑real‑time valuations for progress tracking.\n\n### 8.3 Market Data & Assumptions\n\n- Read:\n  - Capital market assumptions (returns, volatility)\n  - Inflation assumptions\n- Admin interface or service to maintain and update assumptions.\n\n### 8.4 Product Catalog & Model Portfolios\n\n- Read:\n  - Approved products and constraints\n  - Model portfolios for retirement by risk/time horizon.\n\n### 8.5 Order Management System (OMS) / RTA\n\n- Create:\n  - SIP/SWP/lump‑sum orders with plan ID.\n- Read:\n  - Order status and execution results.\n- Update:\n  - Modify/cancel orders when plan changes.\n\n### 8.6 Payment / Mandate Systems\n\n- Verify:\n  - Availability of valid payment mandates for SIP/SWP.\n- Prompt user if mandate setup is required (if integrated).\n\n### 8.7 Notifications / CRM Tasks\n\n- Create:\n  - Alerts and reminders (e.g., review due, off‑track).\n- Log:\n  - Communications for audit and CRM history.\n\n### 8.8 Audit & Logging\n\n- Send:\n  - Plan lifecycle events and key changes to central audit log.\n\n### 8.9 Data Warehouse / BI\n\n- Export:\n  - Plan metadata, projections, and status for management and compliance reporting.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Reporting and Dashboards\n\n### 9.1 Client‑Facing Plan Report\n\n- Contents:\n  - Client and goal summary\n  - Inputs and assumptions\n  - Projections (tables and charts)\n  - Recommended contributions and allocation\n  - Disclaimers and methodology\n- Format:\n  - Branded PDF or equivalent, downloadable and storable.\n\n### 9.2 Advisor Dashboard\n\n- View of all clients with retirement plans:\n  - Key columns: target income, contribution, status, last review date, retirement year.\n- Filters:\n  - Off‑track plans\n  - Plans nearing retirement\n  - Plans without recent review.\n\n### 9.3 Management & Compliance Reporting\n\n- Metrics:\n  - Number of active plans\n  - AUM linked to retirement plans\n  - Distribution of retirement ages and success rates\n  - Exceptions (e.g., risk overrides, high return assumptions)\n- Export to BI tools or standard reports.\n\n### 9.4 Client Progress Reports (Optional)\n\n- Periodic (e.g., annual) summary:\n  - Contributions made\n  - Portfolio performance\n  - Updated on‑track status.\n\n### 9.5 Audit Trail Access\n\n- Ability (via UI or queries) to:\n  - Retrieve historical versions of a plan\n  - View change timeline and responsible users.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Testing and Quality Assurance\n\n### 10.1 Unit Testing\n\n- Coverage of:\n  - Projection formulas\n  - Tax calculations\n  - Edge cases (zero contributions, extreme ages, etc.).\n\n### 10.2 Integration Testing\n\n- End‑to‑end flows:\n  - Plan creation → order placement → status updates.\n- Failure scenarios:\n  - Downstream services unavailable, timeouts, partial failures.\n\n### 10.3 Functional / System Testing\n\n- Validate:\n  - All UI flows and validations\n  - Role‑based access\n  - Report generation.\n\n### 10.4 Performance Testing\n\n- Load tests for concurrent calculations and dashboard queries.\n- Long‑running usage and data volume tests.\n\n### 10.5 Security Testing\n\n- Penetration tests and code review.\n- Authorization checks (no cross‑client data access).\n- Input validation and XSS/CSRF checks.\n\n### 10.6 User Acceptance Testing (UAT)\n\n- Advisors and selected clients validate:\n  - Usability\n  - Financial reasonableness of outputs\n  - Fit with advisory workflows.\n\n### 10.7 Regulatory / Compliance Testing\n\n- Compliance review of:\n  - Assumptions and ranges\n  - Disclaimers and report content\n  - Record‑keeping and audit logs.\n\n### 10.8 Regression Testing\n\n- Ensure no adverse impact on existing modules (trading, holdings, CRM, etc.).\n\n---\n\n## 11. Deployment and Migration\n\n### 11.1 Environment Readiness\n\n- Deploy new services and DB schema to dev/QA/stage.\n- Configure integrations to test endpoints.\n- Set initial assumptions and model portfolios.\n\n### 11.2 Data Migration / Seeding\n\n- Seed:\n  - Default economic assumptions\n  - Model portfolios and product mappings.\n- Optional: import existing high‑level retirement goal data from CRM as draft plans.\n\n### 11.3 Feature Toggles & Phased Rollout\n\n- Use feature flags to:\n  - Enable for internal users first\n  - Pilot with selected advisors\n  - Gradually roll out to all advisors and then clients (if applicable).\n\n### 11.4 Training & Documentation\n\n- Advisor training:\n  - How to use the tool and explain outputs.\n- Support documentation:\n  - FAQs, troubleshooting guides.\n- Client‑facing help content.\n\n### 11.5 Go‑Live Checklist\n\n- Backups, schema migrations, code deployment.\n- Smoke tests:\n  - Access, basic calculation, report generation, visibility controls.\n\n### 11.6 Post‑Deployment Monitoring\n\n- Monitor:\n  - Errors, performance, integration failures.\n  - Order flows originating from plans.\n- Rapid rollback or feature disable capability if critical issues arise.\n\n### 11.7 Feedback & Iteration\n\n- Collect feedback from pilot users and early adopters.\n- Plan minor releases for usability and defect fixes.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Regulatory Considerations and Controls\n\n### 12.1 Suitability & Fiduciary Duty\n\n- Enforce use of current