 % gain/loss)\n    - Relative return vs benchmark\n    - Money‑weighted return / IRR (accounts for cash flows)\n    - Time‑weighted return (isolates investment performance from cash flows)\n\n- **Risk‑adjusted performance**\n  - Sharpe ratio (return per unit of volatility)\n  - Jensen’s alpha (excess return vs what CAPM predicts)\n  - Treynor ratio (return per unit of systematic risk)\n  - Information ratio (excess return vs benchmark per unit of tracking error)\n\nThese metrics help determine whether the portfolio is meeting its objectives efficiently, not just whether it is up or down.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Risk Analytics\n\n**Purpose:** Understand the risk profile and downside characteristics of the portfolio.\n\n**Key metrics:**\n\n- **Volatility:** Standard deviation of returns over a chosen period.\n- **Beta:** Sensitivity to market or benchmark movements.\n- **Value at Risk (VaR):** Estimated maximum loss over a given horizon at a specified confidence level (e.g., 95% 1‑day VaR).\n- **Maximum drawdown:** Largest peak‑to‑trough decline over the analysis period.\n- **Risk ratios:**\n  - Sharpe, Treynor, information ratio (also used in performance context).\n- **Risk attribution (where available):**\n  - Which holdings, sectors, or asset classes contribute most to overall volatility or VaR.\n\nThese analytics are used to check alignment with the client’s risk profile and to identify concentrations of risk.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Portfolio Composition and Exposures\n\n**Purpose:** Show what the client owns and where the portfolio is exposed.\n\n**Core breakdowns:**\n\n- **Asset allocation**\n  - Equity, fixed income, cash, alternatives, real estate, etc.\n- **Sector allocation**\n  - Technology, healthcare, financials, industrials, etc.\n- **Geographic allocation**\n  - Domestic vs international, regions, countries (where supported).\n- **Currency exposure**\n  - Base currency vs foreign currency exposures.\n\n**Holdings and concentration:**\n\n- Top holdings by weight and market value.\n- Issuer‑level exposure (e.g., total exposure to a single corporate issuer).\n- Concentration flags (e.g., >X% in one stock, sector, or country).\n\n**Look‑through analysis (for funds/ETFs):**\n\n- Aggregates underlying holdings of mutual funds, ETFs, and other pooled vehicles.\n- Shows total exposure to individual securities, sectors, or regions across both direct and indirect holdings.\n- Helps identify hidden concentration risk (e.g., multiple funds holding the same stock).\n\n**Actual vs target allocation:**\n\n- Comparison of current allocation vs:\n  - Model portfolio\n  - IPS‑defined target ranges\n- Highlights overweights/underweights and drift from target.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Contribution and Attribution Analysis\n\n**Purpose:** Explain *why* the portfolio performed as it did.\n\n**Performance contribution:**\n\n- By asset class (equity vs fixed income vs alternatives).\n- By sector (e.g., tech vs healthcare).\n- By individual security.\n- Shows positive and negative contributors over a selected period.\n\n**Performance attribution (where supported):**\n\n- Breaks performance into:\n  - Asset allocation effect (over/underweighting asset classes or sectors)\n  - Security selection effect (stock picking within sectors/asset classes)\n  - Interaction effects\n- Can be done vs a benchmark or model portfolio.\n\n**Risk attribution:**\n\n- Which holdings, sectors, or asset classes contribute most to:\n  - Portfolio volatility\n  - VaR or other risk measures\n\nThese tools support client explanations (“Outperformance came mainly from stock selection in technology”) and internal review of investment decisions.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Trend, Scenario, and Forecast Analysis\n\n**Historical trend analysis:**\n\n- Portfolio market value over time.\n- Historical asset allocation and risk metrics (e.g., how volatility or drawdown evolved).\n- Impact of past market events on the portfolio.\n- Interactive charts with zoom and custom date ranges.\n\n**Scenario analysis (“what‑if”):**\n\n- Hypothetical shocks:\n  - Equity market drop (e.g., –10%)\n  - Interest rate shifts (e.g., +100 bps)\n  - FX moves or sector‑specific shocks\n- Estimates impact on:\n  - Portfolio value\n  - Key risk and performance metrics\n\n**Forward‑looking projections (where available):**\n\n- Monte Carlo simulations or other models to:\n  - Project potential future portfolio values over time.\n  - Show probability ranges (e.g., 5th/50th/95th percentile outcomes).\n- Used in financial planning (e.g., likelihood of reaching retirement or education funding goals).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Benchmarking and Comparison\n\n**Purpose:** Put performance and risk in context.\n\n**Benchmarking:**\n\n- Comparison vs:\n  - Single index (e.g., equity index)\n  - Blended benchmark (matching portfolio asset mix)\n- Analytics:\n  - Excess return (alpha)\n  - Tracking error (volatility of excess return)\n  - Relative volatility, beta vs benchmark\n\n**Peer and model comparisons (where supported):**\n\n- Comparison vs:\n  - Firm’s model portfolios for similar risk profiles\n  - Peer groups or category averages\n- Helps demonstrate value added and identify underperformance.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Compliance and Audit Analytics\n\n**Purpose:** Ensure portfolios adhere to mandates, policies, and regulations.\n\n**Compliance checks:**\n\n- Investment guidelines:\n  - Concentration limits (e.g., max % in one stock/sector/issuer).\n  - Asset class ranges (e.g., equity 40–60%).\n  - Credit quality limits for fixed income.\n  - Prohibited securities or sectors.\n- Risk profile alignment:\n  - Check that volatility, beta, or VaR remain within profile‑specific thresholds.\n- Automated alerts:\n  - Breaches of guidelines or drift outside target ranges.\n  - Rating downgrades or other events affecting eligibility.\n\n**Audit trail:**\n\n- Logging of:\n  - Data feeds (prices, holdings, benchmarks).\n  - Calculation methods and parameter changes.\n  - Advisor actions (e.g., report generation, overrides).\n- Supports internal and regulatory audits and ensures consistency across reports.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Data Sources and Inputs\n\n**Core data feeding the analytics engine:**\n\n- **Market/pricing data**\n  - End‑of‑day prices, intraday quotes (if supported), NAVs for funds.\n- **Holdings and positions**\n  - Daily (or more frequent) feeds from custodians/back‑office systems for each account/folio.\n- **Transactions**\n  - Buys, sells, corporate actions, income, and cash flows for accurate performance and IRR.\n- **Fund and ETF holdings**\n  - For look‑through exposure analysis.\n- **Benchmarks and indices**\n  - Levels and returns for comparison and attribution.\n- **Reference and risk factor data**\n  - Security master, classifications (sector, region, currency), ratings, duration, etc.\n- **Fees and charges**\n  - Advisory and product fees to show gross vs net performance.\n\nData is typically updated on scheduled cycles (e.g., end‑of‑day), with quality checks and exception handling.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Visualization and Reporting\n\n**Dashboards:**\n\n- Client portfolio dashboard with:\n  - Total portfolio value and daily change.\n  - Performance summary over key periods.\n  - Asset/sector allocation charts.\n  - Key risk metrics and alerts.\n- Drill‑down views:\n  - Performance detail\n  - Exposures and holdings\n  - Risk analytics\n  - Contribution/attribution\n\n**Visual tools:**\n\n- Line charts for performance and value over time.\n- Pie and bar charts for allocation and contributions.\n- Interactive elements (hover for details, filter by date range, zoom, etc.).\n\n**Reports:**\n\n- On‑demand and scheduled reports (e.g., monthly, quarterly):\n  - Performance summaries\n  - Risk and allocation details\n  - Holdings and transaction listings\n- Export options (PDF, Excel, CSV) for further analysis or client distribution.\n- White‑labeling for client‑facing documents.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Integration with Portfolio Management Workflows\n\n**Advisor and portfolio manager usage:**\n\n- Filter views by:\n  - Individual account/folio\n  - Household or relationship group\n  - Advisor’s book of business\n- Role‑based access:\n  - Advisors see their clients; clients see only their own accounts.\n\n**Actionable analytics:**\n\n- Use analytics to:\n  - Identify need for rebalancing (drift vs target).\n  - Adjust risk exposures.\n  - Propose changes in line with client objectives.\n- Integration with order management:\n  - Generate trade tickets or rebalance orders directly from analytics screens (where supported).\n- Consistency:\n  - Same data and calculations feed:\n    - On‑screen dashboards\n    - Client statements\n    - Regulatory and internal reports\n\n---\n\nIn summary, portfolio analytics in wealth management span performance, risk, exposures, attribution, scenarios, benchmarking, compliance, and reporting. Together, they give advisors and clients a clear, auditable, and actionable view of each customer portfolio.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Provide a comprehensive overview of the analytics features available for client investment portfolios in a wealth management platform.",\n  "expanded_question": "What analytics capabilities does a wealth management platform offer for client portfolios, including performance metrics (returns, risk, attribution), risk analytics (e.g. volatility, VaR), portfolio breakdowns (asset and sector exposure), contribution analysis, trend and scenario analysis, benchmarking against indices, compliance checks, data sources, visualization options, and how portfolio managers/advisors use these tools?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Customer Dashboard",\n    "Folio",\n    "Exposures",\n    "Start Date",\n    "Date Ranges"\n  ],\n  "answer": "# Portfolio Analytics in Wealth Management Platforms\\n\\n**Overview:** Modern wealth-management platforms provide comprehensive analytics on client portfolios to help advisors and investors understand performance, risk, and holdings. These analytics tools aggregate portfolio data and present insights through interactive dashboards and reports. The goal is to offer transparency into how the portfolio is performing, what it contains, and what risks or opportunities it faces, enabling informed decision-making and effective client communication.\\n\\n## Performance Measurement\\nPlatforms offer robust **performance metrics** to evaluate how a portfolio is doing over various time frames. Users can view **returns** over standard periods (e.g. 1 month, 3 months, YTD, 1 year, or custom date ranges) as well as since inception. Performance is often shown as **time-series charts** plotting the portfolio’s value or return over time, with options to select a **start date** or specific date range for analysis. The system may calculate both **absolute returns** (total growth of the portfolio) and **relative returns** versus a benchmark. For deeper insight, **risk-adjusted return** measures are provided – for example, **Sharpe ratio** (return vs volatility) or **Jensen’s alpha** (return above what the market would predict) – to gauge how efficiently the portfolio is generating returns given its risk. In some cases, **internal rate of return (IRR)** or **money-weighted returns** are available to account for cash flows. All these metrics help in assessing whether the portfolio is meeting its investment objectives.\\n\\n## Risk Analytics\\nBeyond returns, analytics modules focus on the **risk profile** of the portfolio. Key **risk metrics** are calculated to understand volatility and potential downsides. For instance, the platform will show **volatility** (often as standard deviation of returns) indicating how much the portfolio’s value fluctuates. It may provide **beta** (how sensitive the portfolio is to market movements) to show market correlation. **Value at Risk (VaR)** is commonly included to quantify potential losses in extreme scenarios (e.g. “the portfolio has a 95% chance of not losing more than X in a day”). Other analytics can include **max drawdown** (the largest peak-to-trough decline experienced) to highlight worst-case historical losses. Risk analytics often encompass **risk ratios** like Sharpe, **Treynor ratio** (returns vs systematic risk), or **information ratio** (performance against benchmark volatility) to evaluate performance in risk terms. These measures help advisors ensure the portfolio’s risk is in line with the client’s risk appetite and highlight any areas of concern.\\n\\n## Portfolio Composition & Exposures\\nAnalytics tools break down the **portfolio holdings** to show exactly what the client owns and how those holdings are allocated. Users can see **asset allocation** across major asset classes (for example, what percentage is in equities, fixed income, cash, etc.) as well as **sector allocation** within equity holdings (such as exposure to technology, healthcare, finance sectors, etc.). Often this is presented in charts like **pie charts or bar graphs**, along with tables of holdings. The platform highlights **exposures** to individual securities or issuers – identifying the largest holdings and their weight in the portfolio. For clients holding mutual funds or ETFs, modern systems perform a *look-through analysis*: they fetch data from sources (like fund holdings feeds) to show the portfolio’s *underlying* exposure. This means the advisor and client can see the combined exposure to a given stock or bond across all the funds and direct investments in the portfolio. For example, if multiple mutual funds all invest in the same company, the system will aggregate that to show the client’s total exposure to that company. This helps in spotting **concentration risk** (over-exposure to a single asset or sector).\\n\\nIn addition, many platforms allow comparing the current **portfolio allocation vs. a target model**. If the firm uses model portfolios or target allocations tied to the client’s risk profile, the analytics can display **actual vs. model asset allocation**, highlighting deviations. For instance, an advisor can quickly see if the portfolio is overweight in equities relative to the model, or if any asset class is outside its recommended range. This exposure analysis ensures the portfolio stays balanced and aligned with the client’s goals.\\n\\n## Contribution & Attribution Analysis\\nFor a detailed understanding of performance, portfolio analytics often include **performance attribution** or contribution analysis. This breaks down the portfolio’s return to show **which holdings or sectors contributed most** to the performance. Advisors can see, for example, how much of the year’s return came from equities versus bonds, or which specific stocks were the top contributors (positive or negative) to the portfolio’s gains. Contribution analysis might also be done at the asset-class level (e.g. equity vs fixed income contribution) or sector level (e.g. technology stocks contributed X% to the total return). By attributing performance to various factors – asset allocation, security selection, sector bets – the platform helps identify the sources of outperformance or underperformance. This is critical for explaining results to clients (“Your portfolio beat the market mainly due to our stock selection in tech”) and for making strategy adjustments. Some systems also offer **risk attribution**, showing which investments are contributing the most to overall portfolio volatility or VaR, helping in risk management.\\n\\n## Trend Analysis and Forecasting\\nAnalytics capabilities include studying historical **trends** and performing forward-looking **scenario analysis**. Historical trend analysis lets users examine how the portfolio has evolved: for example, tracking the portfolio’s market value or asset allocation over time. The platform might display **growth charts** that show how an initial investment grew over the years, or how the portfolio’s risk level changed in response to market events. There are often interactive features (e.g. the ability to select custom date ranges or zoom into specific periods) so that one can analyze performance before and after a particular event.\\n\\nFor looking ahead, **scenario testing** tools allow advisors to model “what-if” situations. Users can apply hypothetical scenarios to the current portfolio, such as “What if equity markets drop 10%?” or “What if interest rates rise by 1%?” The system will estimate the impact on the portfolio value and key metrics, helping to gauge potential risks. Advanced platforms also provide **forecast projections** using techniques like Monte Carlo simulation. These projections generate a range of possible future outcomes for the portfolio based on volatility and historical correlations. For example, an advisor could show a client the probabilistic range of portfolio values in 5 years – illustrating best-case, worst-case, and median scenarios given the current portfolio composition and market behavior. Such forward-looking analytics help in **financial planning** (e.g. determining the likelihood of reaching a target investment goal under various market conditions) and in setting realistic expectations with clients.\\n\\n## Benchmarking and Comparison\\nA core part of portfolio analytics is comparing the portfolio’s performance against relevant **benchmarks** or peers. The platform will typically allow the selection of one or more benchmark indices (for instance, an equity index or a blended index matching the portfolio’s asset mix) to evaluate how the portfolio is doing relative to the market. Performance charts often overlay the portfolio return line with a **benchmark index** line for the same period, so one can see if the portfolio is outperforming or lagging. The system might also show **excess return** (alpha) over the benchmark and track **tracking error** (the volatility of the performance difference). Beyond returns, risk metrics can be benchmarked too – e.g. comparing the portfolio’s volatility to that of the benchmark or checking if the portfolio’s beta is close to 1 against the chosen index.\\n\\nIn some cases, the platform supports **peer comparisons** or model portfolio comparisons. An advisor could compare a client’s portfolio to an industry peer group or to the firm’s model portfolio for that risk category. This helps put the performance in context – for example, showing a client that while their portfolio returned 8%, the benchmark returned 6%, indicating value added. Benchmarking ensures accountability and helps in discussing portfolio strategy (if underperforming, the advisor might adjust the portfolio; if outperforming, they can explain what decisions led to the added value).\\n\\n## Compliance and Audit Considerations\\nWealth platforms also integrate analytics with **compliance checks** to ensure portfolios adhere to investment guidelines and regulatory requirements. For example, the analytics system can monitor if a portfolio exceeds certain concentration limits (like no more than 10% in a single stock or 	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765568429501_mpzyw2ngv","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_08d98dcfb0d0cec600693c6fac637081a2846d5842bf2e9098"}	resp_08d98dcfb0d0cec600693c6fac637081a2846d5842bf2e9098	t	2025-12-12 19:47:59.206	2025-12-12 19:47:59.206	1	f	\N
