may hold up or outperform, reducing portfolio volatility.\n- Scope of diversification:\n  - Across asset classes (e.g., equities, fixed income, cash, real assets, alternatives) to capture different sources of return and risk.\n  - Across geographies (domestic and international markets) to diversify country-specific and currency risks.\n  - Across sectors (e.g., technology, healthcare, finance) to avoid concentration in any single industry.\n  - Across investment instruments (mutual funds, exchange-traded funds, direct securities, bonds, alternatives) to blend different risk/return profiles and liquidity characteristics.\n\nHow diversification reduces risk\n\n- Correlation and risk reduction: Combining assets with low or negative correlations lowers portfolio variance. When one asset class falls, others may hold or increase in value, reducing drawdowns.\n- Risk types addressed: Systematic risk (market-wide) cannot be eliminated, but unsystematic risk (company or sector-specific) can be mitigated through broad exposure and caps on concentration.\n- Balance of sources of return: A diversified mix provides multiple return drivers, which can improve resilience in varying market environments.\n\nMeasurement and monitoring approaches\n\n- Allocation tracking: Monitor asset class, geography, sector, and instrument allocations against target weights.\n- Risk metrics: Use portfolio standard deviation, beta, and drawdown analysis; employ correlation matrices and scenario/stress tests to assess potential impacts under different markets.\n- Diversification indicators: Count of distinct holdings, concentration measures (e.g., Herfindahl index), and coverage across factors (asset classes, geographies, sectors).\n- Rebalancing discipline: Establish triggers or time-based schedules to rebalance back to target allocations as markets move.\n\nPractical guidelines for constructing diversified portfolios\n\n- Clarify constraints: Start with risk tolerance, time horizon, liquidity needs, tax considerations, and regulatory limits.\n- Define strategic asset allocation: Establish target weights across broad asset classes and geographies aligned with objectives.\n- Select instruments thoughtfully: Use a mix of instruments (mutual funds/ETFs, direct securities, bonds, allocations to cash or cash equivalents) to achieve desired exposure with appropriate liquidity.\n- Avoid concentration risk: Limit exposure to any single security, sector, or geography; prefer broad-market or multi-asset vehicles when appropriate.\n- Incorporate costs and taxes: Consider expense ratios, trading costs, and tax efficiency when constructing the mix.\n- Use modular building blocks: Combine core holdings (broad-market funds, high-quality bonds) with satellite positions (tilts to themes or sectors) to maintain diversification while pursuing outcomes.\n- Monitor and adapt: Regularly review risk, returns, and correlations; rebalance as needed to maintain diversification in light of evolving client circumstances.\n- Compliance and constraints: Ensure adherence to regulatory requirements and firm guidelines when designing and adjusting allocations.\n\nIllustrative diversified portfolio examples (generic)\n\n- Conservative profile: 40% fixed income, 40% broad domestic equities, 15% international equities, 5% cash or cash equivalents.\n- Balanced profile: 60% equities (split across domestic and international), 35% fixed income, 5% alternatives/cash.\n- Growth profile: 70% equities (global exposure, with sector diversification), 20% fixed income, 10% alternatives/cash.\n\nLimitations and important considerations\n\n- Diversification cannot eliminate systemic market risk entirely; markets can move in the same direction across many assets.\n- Correlations evolve; regular reviews are essential to ensure the portfolio remains aligned with objectives.\n- Liquidity, tax, and regulatory factors may constrain diversification choices and require tailored adjustments.\n	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"