filing configuration**\n  - **Risk profile questionnaire maintenance**: The library of questions, answer options, and scoring rules is defined in advance. \n  - **Risk appetite mapping**: Ranges of risk scores are mapped to standard risk profiles (e.g., Conservative, Moderate, Aggressive). \n\n- **Downstream configuration dependencies**\n  - Model portfolios and product hierarchies are defined with reference to the risk profiles, so that once a client’s profile is known, appropriate model portfolios and products can be suggested or restricted. \n\nThese prerequisites ensure that when a client is profiled, the system can both compute a result and consistently apply it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Data collection and questionnaire structure\n\nThe platform uses configurable questionnaires as the primary mechanism for assessing risk:\n\n- **Questionnaire parts / types**\n  - Non‑scorable sections (e.g., financial profiling, investment knowledge) that capture qualitative inputs and understanding. \n  - Scorable sections where each response contributes to a numeric risk score.\n\n- **Question attributes**\n  - Each question is configured with:\n    - Description text\n    - Mandatory flag\n    - Single‑ or multi‑select behavior\n    - Scoring type (e.g., none, range) and computation type, which define how responses convert into points. \n\n- **Client‑level capture**\n  - When profiling is initiated for a client, the system presents the active questionnaire version, records responses, and validates that all mandatory questions are answered.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Scoring model and risk appetite mapping\n\nOnce responses are captured, the system calculates a **risk score** and maps it to a **risk category**:\n\n- **Score computation**\n  - Response‑level points are aggregated as per the configured computation logic to derive a single numeric risk score for the client.\n\n- **Risk appetite mapping**\n  - In a dedicated maintenance screen, administrators define score bands (e.g., 0–20, 21–40, etc.) and link each band to a risk profile label. \n  - When a client’s score falls into a band, the corresponding risk profile (e.g., “Balanced”) is assigned.\n\n- **Profile history and metadata**\n  - The system maintains a **risk profile history** including:\n    - Historical risk scores\n    - Historical risk categories\n    - Suitability Assessment Form (SAF) signed date and expiry date\n    - Maker details of the user who performed profiling \n\nThis ensures a full audit trail of changes in a client’s risk standing over time.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Use of external ratings (e.g., CRISIL)\n\nExternal ratings such as CRISIL are used at the **product level** rather than to compute client risk directly:\n\n- For mutual funds, the system can display CRISIL consistency ratings (e.g., 1–5) alongside each fund in product selection. \n- These ratings are part of the data points used when evaluating whether a given security is aligned to a client’s risk profile and when presenting product information for informed decision‑making.\n\nWhile the risk score mapping is primarily questionnaire‑driven, these external metrics support suitability checks and portfolio construction by classifying product risk.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Risk segmentation and outputs\n\nThe direct outputs of the profiling process are:\n\n- **Risk score**: A numeric value derived from questionnaire responses.\n- **Risk category / profile**: A standardized label determined by the risk appetite mapping.\n- **Suitability metadata**:\n  - SAF signed and expiry dates for evidencing client consent and periodic review. \n  - Maker details and timestamps for governance and audit.\n\nThese outputs are attached to the client/investor record and are available to all downstream journeys that require risk information.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Integration with onboarding and ongoing journeys\n\nRisk profiling is embedded within other key journeys rather than being a standalone artifact:\n\n- **At onboarding / profile completion**\n  - When a new client is being onboarded or their profile is being updated, the user can trigger the risk profiling flow from within the client context so that risk category is established early and stored with the client record.\n\n- **At order placement and product selection**\n  - During order placement and product selection, the system checks for the presence and validity of the client’s risk profile:\n    - If a client has **no risk profile** or the profile has **expired**, the system prompts the client to either accept restrictions or to perform/refresh risk profiling before proceeding. Only limited transactions (e.g., redemptions) may be allowed until profiling is completed. \n    - If a selected security’s risk rating is **higher than the client’s risk profile**, the system displays a **deviation alert** and asks for explicit confirmation before proceeding. \n    - If the security’s risk level is **two or more categories above** the client’s risk profile, the system enforces a **hard stop** and blocks the transaction. \n\n- **Model portfolio and recommendation alignment**\n  - Model portfolios are pre‑defined against each risk profile; when advising or constructing portfolios, only the model(s) aligned to the client’s risk category are suggested. \n\nThis ensures that risk profiling is consistently enforced across channels and transaction types.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Governance, controls, and lifecycle\n\nRisk profiling is governed through a combination of configuration control, entitlements, and periodic review:\n\n- **Configuration governance**\n  - Only entitled users can create or modify questions, scoring rules, or risk appetite mappings, ensuring changes are controlled and traceable. \n\n- **Auditability**\n  - Risk profile history captures all past scores and categories along with maker details, enabling full audit and supervisory review. \n\n- **Validity and renewal**\n  - SAF expiry dates and system prompts at order placement enforce that risk profiling is refreshed periodically and not used beyond its defined validity.  \n\nThrough these mechanisms, the system ensures that client risk assessments are current, consistently applied, and demonstrably governed across the investment lifecycle.	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","Customer Risk profile","Product risk profile","INVESTOR","RM","Risk Appetite Mapping","Switch In Fund Risk Profile","Intellect","PMS application","Model Portfolio Maintenance"],"seed_node_ids":["aum:customer_risk_profile","aum:switch_fund_risk_profile","dataentity:switch","dataentity:risk_profiling","datastore:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:investor","dataentity:customer","system:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","dataentity:rm","system:pms_app","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:product_risk_profile","system:rmws","system:intellect","aum:risk_profiling","system:risk_appetite_mapping"],"expanded_nodes":77,"expanded_edges":178,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser's Question: How does risk profiling work in the system?","Explain how the platform builds, executes, and governs client risk profiling for suitability and recommendations within the wealth-management system.","Provide a concise, business-focused explanation of how the system performs risk profiling for clients, including inputs (client risk tolerance, investment horizon, constraints), data collection, scoring model, risk segmentation, outputs (risk category, suitability assessment, recommendati