figurations; questionnaires can be extended with additional questions and scoring types (e.g., None/Range) as part of maintenance. \n- The risk profile is maintained and configured via dedicated risk profiling questionnaire maintenance and risk appetite mapping processes. On onboarding and during ongoing servicing, risk appetite mappings connect observed scores to defined risk categories. \n- In addition to questionnaire data, ongoing risk assessment flows may consider existing client data and approvals to determine suitability and profiling status. On some journeys, risk profile views may be surfaced as part of the client’s risk profile or recommended risk profile screens. \n- Data surfaces used in risk context include client risk profile screens, risk-based asset composition views, and historical risk profile records. \n\n## Scoring methodology and risk tiers\n- A risk score is derived from the risk profile questionnaire and related inputs, which is then mapped to a risk category via a Risk Appetite Mapping framework (e.g., Very Conservative, Conservative, Moderate, Aggressive, Very Aggressive). The mapping defines the risk profile that corresponds to the numeric score range. \n- The questionnaire design supports diverse scoring treatments (scorable vs. non-scorable components) and explicit computation types to drive the overall risk score. \n\n## Data sources and privacy considerations\n- Core inputs come from risk profiling questionnaires and risk appetite mappings, with governance around how responses are used to determine risk category. (Questionnaire maintenance and risk appetite configuration are controlled in the system.) \n- Sensitive data used for profiling is stored and surfaced within client-facing screens, with audit and validation controls governing how risk data is accessed and modified. See governance and audit references below. \n\n## Cadence, triggers, and updates\n- Risk profiles have a defined date and expiry lifecycle; reassessment can be triggered or prompted as needed, and profiles may expire requiring reassessment to proceed with certain actions. \n- On ordering journeys, if a risk profile is missing or expired, the system prompts action (e.g., risk profiling) and may restrict certain operations until profiling is completed. This gating logic helps ensure alignment before product allocations or purchases. \n- When evaluating transactions, the system compares Product Risk Profile against Customer Risk Profile, and may issue warnings or hard stops depending on the deviation (e.g., up to CRR+2 can generate advisory prompts; CRR+2 or more can trigger hard stops or required approvals). \n\n## Storage and surface of risk profiles\n- The risk profile is stored as part of the client profile and is surfaced on dedicated risk profile screens, including risk profile history and risk-based asset composition views. This supports ongoing monitoring and review. \n- Historical risk profile data enables traceability and governance over profiling decisions and changes over time. \n\n## How risk profiling drives portfolio construction and advisory workflow\n- The risk category directly informs asset allocation and model portfolio construction through the Risk Appetite Mapping framework, which translates risk scores into recommended risk profiles and permissible investment choices. \n- Suitability and supervision checks are guided by the alignment between the customer’s risk profile and product risk profiles; deviations are surfaced to advisors and may trigger warnings, escalation, or hard stops depending on the severity of the mismatch. \n- When a product’s risk profile exceeds the customer’s risk profile by a specified margin (e.g., PRR > CRR + 2), the system blocks transactions or requires higher-level approvals, enforcing risk discipline in advisory workflows. \n\n## Governance, audit trails, and configurability\n- Audit trails capture risk-related actions (including risk profile maintenance, risk appetite mapping, and related questionnaire governance) to support compliance and traceability. \n- Advisors and operations can configure risk profiling controls through Risk Appetite Mapping maintenance, enabling adjustments to mapping grids, thresholds, and permissible risk settings as part of governance. \n\n## What this means in practice\n- On onboarding and during servicing, clients are profiled via a structured risk questionnaire, scored, and mapped to a risk category. This category informs asset allocation guidance, product recommendations, and the permissible range of investments for the client. The system continuously validates profiling status, surfaces risk-profile information on client screens, and enforces controls during order placement to maintain risk-aligned execution. Deviations trigger warnings or hard stops, with governance and audit trails ensuring accountability and traceability of risk decisions. 	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","Customer Risk profile","Product risk profile","INVESTOR","RM","Order","Intellect","Risk Profile Deviation alert","Field Level Details","Risk Appetite Mapping"],"seed_node_ids":["aum:customer_risk_profile","dataentity:risk_profiling","dataentity:investor","report:field_level_details","dataentity:customer","report:risk_profile_deviation_alert","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","dataentity:rm","dataentity:order","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:product_risk_profile","system:rmws","dataentity:field_level_details","system:intellect","aum:risk_profiling","system:risk_appetite_mapping"],"expanded_nodes":46,"expanded_edges":81,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concis