Very Conservative, Conservative, Moderate, Aggressive) and may also link those bands to target asset allocations. \n- **Asset Allocation / Model definitions** – For each risk band, the system maintains indicative asset allocation models (e.g., equity/debt/cash splits) that can be used for recommendations. \n- **User, role, and entitlement setup** – RMs, operations users, and supervisors are configured with entitlements to create/modify questionnaires, perform risk assessments, and approve recommended profiles.  \n\nThese prerequisites must be in place for risk profiling to function consistently in onboarding and transaction workflows. \n\n---\n\n## 2. Risk Profiling Process for a Customer\n\n### 2.1 Initiation\n\n- Risk profiling is triggered when:\n  - A new customer is being onboarded or their profile is being edited; or\n  - The customer attempts a transaction and **no valid risk profile exists or the existing profile has expired**. In such cases, the system prompts the user/customer to perform risk profiling before proceeding with non‑redemption transactions.  \n\n### 2.2 Administering the Questionnaire\n\n1. The user (RM or customer, depending on channel) navigates to the **Risk Profile Questionnaire** for the relevant customer.\n2. The system presents the active questionnaire version applicable to that customer type/category and date.\n3. The user answers all mandatory questions; some questions may be informational / non‑scorable, while others carry scores used for risk tolerance assessment.  \n\n### 2.3 Scoring and Risk Band Determination\n\n- As responses are captured, the system **calculates a total risk score** based on the scoring rules configured in questionnaire maintenance. \n- This score is then passed through the **Risk Appetite Mapping**, which maps score ranges to a discrete **recommended risk profile** (e.g., Very Conservative, Conservative, Balanced, Aggressive). \n- The system can also derive associated expectations such as **expected return and standard deviation** for that risk band, which are later shown on the risk profile screen. \n\n### 2.4 Recommended Risk Profile and Approval\n\n- The system generates a **Recommended Risk Profile** for the customer based on the mapped risk band.  \n- In many setups, this recommendation requires **supervisory approval** before becoming active:\n  - RM performs the questionnaire and submits the recommended profile.\n  - Supervisor reviews the responses, score, and proposed risk band, then approves/rejects it.\n- Once approved, the risk profile is stored against the customer with:\n  - Risk band/category\n  - Risk score\n  - Date and **expiry date** (validity period), as configured in the questionnaire.  \n\n---\n\n## 3. Data Storage and Access\n\n- The **customer record** stores the latest active risk profile along with its score, effective date, expiry date, and related statistics (e.g., expected return, standard deviation). \n- The system maintains **risk profile history**, allowing users to view previous assessments and how the customer’s profile has evolved over time. \n- Risk profile data is read by downstream processes, especially order capture and suitability checks, via the customer card or equivalent profile object. \n\n---\n\n## 4. Use of Risk Profile in Order and Advisory Workflows\n\n### 4.1 Pre‑trade Checks and Deviation Handling\n\nDuring order capture (purchase, SIP, STP, switch, etc.), the system compares **Customer Risk Profile (CRR)** with **Product Risk Profile (PRR)** for each selected security:\n\n- If **PRR ≤ CRR**: No warning; the order can proceed normally.  \n- If **PRR = CRR + 1** (one level above customer risk):\n  - The system shows a **warning/confirmation pop‑up** listing all securities where PRR exceeds CRR.\n  - The user (RM or customer) must explicitly confirm to proceed.  \n- If **PRR ≥ CRR + 2** (two or more levels above customer risk):\n  - The system applies a **hard stop**; those securities cannot be transacted in that journey.\n  - This applies across relevant transaction types (purchase, SIP, STP, switch) and may consider all holders in joint accounts, using the lowest applicable customer risk profile.   \n\nThis behaviour is surfaced to users through **Risk Profile Deviation alerts** and similar warning messages in the order journey UI. \n\n### 4.2 Handling Missing or Expired Profiles\n\n- If a customer **does not have a risk profile** or if their profile has **expired**, the system:\n  - Prompts the user/customer to either perform risk profiling or, in some channels, proceed with only redemption transactions.\n  - Blocks or restricts new investment transactions (e.g., subscription, purchase, switch‑in) until a valid risk profile is captured.  \n\n### 4.3 Advisor View and Client Reporting\n\n- Advisors and customers can access a **Risk Profile screen or widget** that displays:\n  - Current risk profile band.\n  - Risk score.\n  - Expected return and standard deviation metrics linked to that band.\n  - Risk profile date, expiry date.\n  - Options to download/email the risk profile and view history. \n\nThis makes the risk profile directly usable in advisory discussions and suitability documentation.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Governance and Validation\n\n- **Validation rules** in the risk assessment journey ensure all mandatory questions are answered and that effective dates and validity periods are consistent.  \n- **Actor/entitlement controls** restrict who can:\n  - Define/modify questionnaires and risk appetite mappings.\n  - Perform risk assessments.\n  - Approve recommended risk profiles.  \n- In some implementations, orders with risk deviations may require **additional supervisory approval** in the order workflow when soft warnings are overridden. \n\n---\n\n## 6. Summary\n\nIn summary, risk profiling works as a controlled, configuration‑driven process where:\n\n1. Questionnaires and mappings are centrally maintained.\n2. Customers are periodically assessed via a structured questionnaire.\n3. Scores are mapped to risk bands and, optionally, model asset allocations.\n4. Recommended profiles are approved and stored with validity.\n5. Orders are checked against the stored profile, with warnings or hard stops where product risk is higher than allowed.\n6. Advisors and customers can view and evidence the risk profile throughout onboarding, advisory, and ongoing transaction journeys.	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Customer Risk profile","Switch In Fund Risk Profile","Product risk profile","INVESTOR","RM","Risk Appetite Mapping","Model asset allocation","asset class exposure"],"seed_node_ids":["aum:customer_risk_profile","aum:switch_fund_risk_profile","dataentity:switch","dataentity:risk_profiling","dataentity:investor","dataentity:model_asset_allocation","dataentity:customer","dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","report:risk_profile_questionnaire","dataentity:rm","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:product_risk_profile","system:rmws","aum:risk_profiling","system:risk_appetite_mapping","dataentity:asset_class_exposure"],"expanded_nodes":79,"expanded_edges":181,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser's Question: How does risk profiling work in the system?\\n","What is the general, business-focused approach used by the wealth-management system to determine a client's risk profile, and how is it utilized in onboarding and advisory workflows?","Describe the end-to-end risk profiling workflow in the wealt