 goal type, the engine typically works with the same base inputs and formulas; what changes are the assumptions and configuration:\n\n- **Target value / corpus at goal date** (future cost of the goal)\n- **Time horizon**: years/months until the goal start date\n- **Inflation assumption** for the goal (price growth of the target expense)\n- **Expected portfolio return** for the investments mapped to the goal\n- **Funding structure**:\n  - Lump-sum now\n  - Recurring contributions (SIP-style)\n  - Combination of both\n- **Success check**: comparison of projected portfolio values vs. required goal corpus over time.\n\nThe engine typically uses time-value-of-money annuity and compounding formulas to compute one of:\n- Required **lump-sum** now, given the target corpus, horizon, inflation and return\n- Required **periodic contribution** (SIP) given the same\n- Or **funding status** given current investments (surplus/shortfall).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Calculation differences by goal type\n\n### 3.1 Emergency / Contingency goal\n\n**Objective**  \nBuild a liquid safety buffer (e.g., 3–12 months of expenses).\n\n**Typical assumptions and calculations**\n- **Target corpus**: Derived from current (or projected) monthly expenses × chosen multiple (e.g., 6 months). Often **low or zero explicit inflation** assumption, as it is a near-to-medium-term buffer.\n- **Time horizon**: Usually **shorter or flexible** (e.g., 1–3 years to build the corpus); the goal may be ongoing and not tied to a fixed event date.\n- **Return assumption**: Conservative, based on low-risk, high-liquidity instruments.\n- **Contribution pattern**:\n  - Often SIP-style monthly contribution until target corpus is reached.\n  - Required SIP is calculated so that projected value (at conservative return) equals target corpus in the chosen horizon.\n- **Liquidity emphasis**:\n  - No structured withdrawals; the goal assumes the corpus stays available.\n  - Success metric focuses on **achieving and maintaining the corpus**, not on income replacement.\n\n**How this differs vs. others**\n- Lower expected return and risk; shorter horizon; target is a **multiple of expenses**, not a one-time future purchase or long-term income stream.\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Retirement goal\n\n**Objective**  \nProvide income replacement during retirement over a long post-retirement horizon.\n\n**Typical assumptions and calculations**\n- **Two phases**: \n  1. **Accumulation**: from today to retirement date.  \n  2. **Decumulation**: from retirement to assumed life expectancy.\n- **Target corpus at retirement**:\n  - Based on desired **retirement income** (often a % of pre-retirement expenses or income), \n  - Adjusted for **inflation** from today to retirement start, and again through the retirement period.\n- **Accumulation calculation**:\n  - Future corpus needed at retirement is computed using inflation and desired income stream (present value of an annuity at retirement date).\n  - Required **lump-sum today** or **SIP amount** is calculated using expected pre-retirement return.\n- **Decumulation check**:\n  - Tests if the corpus, invested at assumed post-retirement return, can sustain the inflation-adjusted withdrawals over the retirement years.\n- **Return & risk assumptions**:\n  - Often **higher pre-retirement** (growth-oriented allocation) and **lower post-retirement** (balanced/conservative).\n\n**How this differs vs. others**\n- Explicit **two-phase modelling (accumulation + decumulation)**.  \n- Success is defined as **sustainability of income over a long horizon**, not just reaching a one-time amount.\n\n---\n\n### 3.3 Education goal\n\n**Objective**  \nAccumulate a corpus to fund education costs (tuition, living expenses) starting at a specific future year, often with multi-year outflows.\n\n**Typical assumptions and calculations**\n- **Target corpus**:\n  - Either as a single amount at course start or a **series of yearly cash flows** (e.g., 4 years of fees and living costs),\n  - Inflated using a **higher education-specific inflation rate** (often higher than general CPI).\n- **Time horizon**: From current date to start of education.\n- **Return assumption**: Moderate growth allocation, as horizon is usually medium-to-long but finite.\n- **Contribution pattern**:\n  - Required lump-sum or periodic SIP calculated so that projected portfolio value at education start meets or exceeds target corpus.\n- **Withdrawal structure**:\n  - If modeled as multiple outflows, the plan checks whether the portfolio can fund each year’s cost while remaining invested.\n\n**How this differs vs. others**\n- Typically uses **higher inflation** than generic costs.  \n- Often treats goal as **one main start date with potential staged withdrawals**, rather than a long replacement-income stream like retirement.\n\n---\n\n### 3.4 Wealth / general investment goal\n\n**Objective**  \nBuild wealth without a strict consumption event (e.g., “grow wealth to X by Y date” or “maximize wealth subject to risk profile”).\n\n**Typical assumptions and calculations**\n- **Target** may be:\n  - A specified corpus by a date (e.g., achieve 10 million in 15 years), or\n  - Open-ended / aspirational, where the tool projects likely outcomes for given contributions.\n- **Time horizon**: User-defined; can be short, medium, or long, but **no specific liability date**.\n- **Return assumption**: Based on chosen risk profile’s model portfolio.\n- **Contribution structure**:\n  - Can handle both lump-sum and SIP; calculations compute future value of contributions.\n- **Success definition**:\n  - If a numeric target is given, checks sufficiency vs. that target.  \n  - If not, simply shows projected wealth trajectory.\n\n**How this differs vs. others**\n- No fixed “real-world liability”; goal success is **reaching a corpus target**, not funding a defined expense pattern.\n- Inflation may be applied for real-wealth comparison but is less central than for education or retirement.\n\n---\n\n### 3.5 Other / custom goals (e.g., house, wedding, travel, car)\n\n**Objective**  \nAccumulate a corpus for a specified life event or purchase at (or over) a known future date.\n\n**Typical assumptions and calculations**\n- **Target corpus**:\n  - Starts from today’s cost of the purchase/event and applies **goal-specific inflation** to the target date.\n- **Time horizon**: Single-phase, from now until the event date.\n- **Return assumption**: Depends on time horizon and risk profile:\n  - Shorter horizons → more conservative returns/asset mix.\n  - Longer horizons → more growth-oriented.\n- **Contribution pattern**:\n  - Standard lump-sum / SIP / combination calculations, same as wealth goals but **always tied to a concrete liability date**.\n- **Withdrawal structure**:\n  - Typically a one-time withdrawal at goal date; thereafter the goal is considered met.\n\n**How this differs vs. others**\n- Similar computation framework to education, but generally **single payout** at goal date (no prolonged income stream or multi-stage education fees).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Cross-goal calculation nuances\n\nAcross these goal types, several dimensions differ in configuration even though the underlying math is similar:\n\n1. **Inflation rate**\n   - Emergency: low/near-term, sometimes flat.  \n   - Retirement: long-term general inflation for expenses.  \n   - Education: often higher, education-specific inflation.  \n   - Wealth / Other: general inflation; may be used mainly to show real vs nominal values.\n\n2. **Return and risk assumptions**\n   - Derived from model portfolios or risk profiles, which may vary by goal type and time horizon (e.g., more conservative for short-dated or capital-protection goals, more aggressive for long-dated growth goals).\n\n3. **Time horizon treatment**\n   - Retirement: split into **pre- and post-retirement phases**.  \n   - Education / Other: usually **single accumulation phase** to a known date; education may also include a multi-year payout phase.  \n   - Emergency / Wealth: can be ongoing or flexible, not always tied to a single event date.\n\n4. **Cash-flow pattern**\n   - Retirement: long series of inflation-linked withdrawals.  \n   - Education: finite series of withdrawals (e.g., annual fees).  \n   - Other: single withdrawal at goal date.  \n   - Emergency: no scheduled withdrawals (buffer concept).  \n   - Wealth: usually no defined liability; main focus is accumulation.\n\n5. **Success / sufficiency metrics**\n   - All goals: compare **projected portfolio value** with **required corpus or cash flows**.  \n   - Retirement/Education: often highlight **probability of shortfall** over multiple years.  \n   - Emergency/Other: binary sufficiency at or before target date.  \n   - Wealth: gap vs target corpus if specified.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Summary\n\n- The platform supports multiple goal types such as **emergency, retirement, education, wealth accumulation, and other custom life goals**.\n- All goals share a common engine based on future value/annuity calculations using **time horizon, inflation and expected return** assumptions.\n- The main differences between goal types arise from:\n  - How the **target corpus** is defined (income replacement vs. one-off purchase vs. safety buffer),\n  - The **cash-flow pattern** (single payout, multi-year fees, or long-term income stream),\n  - The **inflation and return assumptions** applied, and\n  - The **risk and liquidity posture** appropriate to each goal.\n\nThese configuration differences drive how required contributions, projected values and sufficiency checks are calculated for each goal type.	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Primary goal of the Model","Projections","Annexure","Benchmark","Key metrics","performance","Volatility","risk profiling","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Customer Risk profile"],"seed_node_ids":["report:view_performance_graph","report:annexure","dataentity:volatility","aum:performance","compliance:risk_profiling","aum:r