gous lists exist (customers), the default user‑triggered sort is by **name, ascending or descending**; for activities, by **status or date**.   \n  - It is therefore reasonable to infer that, **unless your implementation has a custom BRD**, an RM list on such a view would typically default to either:\n    - Alphabetical by RM name, or\n    - A simple metric such as total leads or AUM, if configured locally.\n  - However, **this is not codified in the shared documents**, so any concrete metric‑based ordering must come from project‑specific configuration, not the generic standard.\n\n- **Tie‑break logic (e.g., conversion rate, pipeline value, recency):**\n  - No tie‑breaker hierarchy is specified anywhere for a list of RMs (e.g., "if conversion rate is equal, then sort by total pipeline, then by name").\n\n- **Configurability of sorting (user vs admin):**\n  - Related widgets (customers, To‑Dos, notes) allow the **end user to pick the sort criterion** (e.g., status vs date, ascending vs descending, by name).   \n  - There is **no explicit configuration section** describing admin‑level controls to define or lock the default RM ranking logic for lead performance.\n\n- **Influence of filters (region, time window, etc.):**\n  - Filters on dashboards (HNW, AUM, product type, RM/Agent name) clearly **constrain which customers or records are displayed**, but do **not alter the underlying sort rule**; sort and filter are independent actions in the described screens.  \n  - By analogy, regional or time‑window filters on an RM lead‑performance view would typically **change the dataset (which RMs or which leads are counted)**, while the ranking rule (whatever is configured) remains the same.\n\n- **Data sources for any RM performance ranking:**\n  - The broader ecosystem uses **leads, opportunities, activities, and customer holdings** as sources for RM‑level metrics (e.g., opportunities from call reports, alerts, AUM and product composition on dashboards).  \n  - However, the documents stop short of stating a specific formula for a composite "lead performance" score or its direct use in sorting RMs.\n\n### 4. Practical conclusion\nGiven the current documentation set:\n\n- **There is no standard, documented system logic that definitively states how RMs are sorted in a dedicated “lead‑performance” RM list (no fixed primary metric, direction, or tie‑breakers).**\n- Existing patterns show:\n  - **Simple, single‑field sorts** (mostly by name, date, or status), chosen by the user in each widget.   \n  - **Filters** that affect what records appear, but not the sort mechanism itself.\n- Therefore, if your environment shows a ranked list of RMs by lead performance, the ordering is most likely **defined in a project‑specific BRD or configuration (e.g., custom KPI weighting or supervisor‑view logic)** rather than in the base product specification.\n\nFor an accurate answer in your specific instance, you would need to refer to your implementation’s BRD/FRD or configuration notes that define:\n- Which KPI (or composite score) is used as the primary sort, and\n- Any secondary metrics or name‑based tie‑break rules applied on that screen.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n[1] JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf  \n[2] SAAB-Journey of Self_Assessment and Supervisor Assessment_Customer Dashboard_V13_CCV10docx.pdf  \n[3] Maybank_Journey of Self-Assessment and Supervisor Assessment-Customer Dashboard_V12_CCV_V10docx.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["RM","Lead","Relationship","Portfolio Performance Report","Customer Dashboard","Risk Profile Deviation alert"],"seed_node_ids":["report:customer_dashboard","dataentity:relationship","report:pf_performance_report","system:rmws","report:risk_profile_deviation_alert","dataentity:lead","dataentity:rm"],"expanded_nodes":39,"expanded_edges":1180,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\