\n2. **Analysis of needs and risk**  \n   - Using the client profile and risk questionnaire, the platform determines the client’s **risk profile** and **risk appetite mapping**, which will later govern which products and transactions are considered suitable.  \n   - Planning logic (outside what is explicitly documented here) typically projects goals, cash flows, and asset allocations into a recommended strategy, often via a **model portfolio**.\n\n3. **Product selection and carting of recommendations**  \n   - From the client **Customer Card / Dashboard**, the RM or advisor initiates a transact journey and is taken to a **Product Selection Screen** where eligible products are displayed based on licenses, risk constraints, and other entitlements .  \n   - The advisor chooses the appropriate **securities** (e.g., mutual funds) for implementation of the financial plan. These may be drawn from existing holdings or new products .\n\n4. **Definition of transaction instructions**  \n   - For each chosen security, the user defines **transaction details** such as purchase, switch, redemption, or **Systematic Investment Plan (SIP)**, including amount, frequency, and start dates .  \n   - These instructions are aggregated into an **order** that operationalizes the financial plan.\n\n5. **Validation, disclosures, and order capture**  \n   - Before order confirmation, the platform applies a series of **general and instrument-specific validations**, and ensures the correct **disclaimers** are displayed/accepted.  \n   - Once validated and accepted (including acknowledgments of disclaimers), the **order** is placed and downstream trade processing and settlement journeys take over .\n\n6. **Execution, settlement, and post-trade view**  \n   - Orders flow through trade processing, execution, and settlement journeys, updating **transactions** and holdings .  \n   - The **Customer Dashboard** then reflects updated holdings, transactions, and product cart information, supporting ongoing monitoring and review of the financial plan .\n\n---\n\n## 2. Role of the Product Selection Summary section in financial planning\n\nOnce products are chosen for implementing the plan, the **Product Selection Summary section** acts as the bridge between planning and order capture:\n\n- **Aggregation of chosen securities**  \n  - After selections from Existing Holdings or Other Funds, the user proceeds to the **Product Selection Summary screen**, which shows all **securities** selected for the client .  \n  - This provides a consolidated view of the instruments that will implement the plan (e.g., multiple mutual funds aligned with the client’s target allocation).\n\n- **Configuration of transaction details per security**  \n  - For each security, the user chooses the required **transaction type** from a dropdown (e.g., SIP) and enters parameters like SIP amount .  \n  - This step concretely converts the financial plan recommendations into executable transactions for each product.\n\n- **Comparisons and additional details**  \n  - The section can surface **product comparison** and **additional product details** (explained in the purchase section of the same journey) to support suitability and informed decision-making at the point of implementing the plan .\n\n- **Gateway to order confirmation**  \n  - Once all details are confirmed on the Product Selection Summary, the user proceeds to the next step for validations, disclaimers, and final order capture. In effect, it is the last structured checkpoint where the consistency of the financial plan implementation (amounts, schemes, SIP settings) can be reviewed and adjusted before committing.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Role of General Validation in financial planning\n\n**General Validation** (together with other validation components) ensures that the recommended and selected investments remain compliant, suitable, and technically correct before orders are accepted:\n\n- **Pre-requisite configuration and governance**  \n  - The platform requires maintenance of risk profile questionnaires, risk appetite mappings, model portfolios, security master, and disclaimers as prerequisites for order journeys .  \n  - These configurations define the rules that General Validation will apply (e.g., product eligibility given a risk profile).\n\n- **Suitability and eligibility checks**  \n  - General Validation typically ensures that:\n    - Chosen products fit the client’s **risk profile** and **risk appetite mapping**.  \n    - Regulatory and internal policy constraints (e.g., KYC status, license-based entitlements, product eligibility for client type) are respected, as seen where the system only allows order placement if KYC status is in an allowed state and displays eligible securities based on user license .\n\n- **Technical and completeness checks**  \n  - General Validation also ensures mandatory fields are populated (e.g., SIP amount, start date), transaction values are within permitted ranges, and that there are no internal inconsistencies in the planned transactions.\n\n- **Interaction with more granular validations**  \n  - In addition to general rules, the platform invokes **Validations and Warnings** that validate specific entities such as **securities**, **mutual funds**, and **model portfolio maintenance** for setup consistency and trading eligibility .  \n  - Together, this layered validation framework underpins the integrity of financial plan execution.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Role of Disclaimer Maintenance in financial planning\n\n**Disclaimer Maintenance** is a core governance component that ensures appropriate legal and risk disclosures are consistently embedded into the planning and order process:\n\n- **Centralized definition of disclaimers**  \n  - Disclaimers (e.g., product risk warnings, suitability caveats, regulatory disclosures) are maintained centrally in **Disclaimer Maintenance**, which is identified as a prerequisite for order placement journeys .\n\n- **Binding disclaimers to products and journeys**  \n  - Specific disclaimers can be mapped to product categories (e.g., mutual funds, SIPs) or journeys (e.g., financial planning, order placement).  \n  - When the advisor implements a financial plan and reaches Product Selection Summary or later confirmation screens, the relevant disclaimers are displayed to the user and/or client for acknowledgement, ensuring informed consent.\n\n- **Regulatory and audit support**  \n  - Central maintenance supports traceability and versioning of disclaimers. This ensures that when financial planning recommendations are executed as transactions, the platform can demonstrate that appropriate disclosures were presented at the time of advice and order capture.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Role of transactions in financial planning\n\nIn the platform, **transactions** represent the concrete actions that give effect to the financial plan:\n\n- **From plan to order to transaction**  \n  - The advisor’s selections and SIP setups in the Product Selection Summary are consolidated into **orders**.  \n  - As orders flow through trade processing, they generate **transactions**—purchase, switch, redemption, SIP installments, etc.—which update the client’s holdings and cash .\n\n- **Lifecycle and status management**  \n  - Transactions pass through multiple states (initiated, matched, executed, settled, reversed, or rejected). For example, executed units are processed as settled as per settlement date, while unexecuted units are rejected and holdings released .  \n  - Reversals (e.g., for SWP/SIP or switch transactions) are handled via reversal orders and corresponding reversal transactions, ensuring the plan can be adjusted over time .\n\n- **Visibility on the customer dashboard**  \n  - The **Customer Dashboard** provides a **Transactions** view where all completed and in-flight transactions are listed, giving transparency on how the financial plan is being executed and updated .\n\n- **Input for ongoing planning**  \n  - Transaction history (contributions, withdrawals, switches) informs periodic plan reviews and re-planning, as advisors can see actual implementation versus original recommendations.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Role of securities in financial planning\n\n**Securities** are the building blocks used to implement the financial plan’s asset allocation and strategy:\n\n- **Security maintenance as a prerequisite**  \n  - **Security Maintenance** is called out as a prerequisite for order capture and settlement journeys, ensuring that all tradable instruments (mutual funds, etc.) are properly defined before they are used in planning or transactions .\n\n- **Selection in planning journeys**  \n  - In the Product Selection and Product Selection Summary steps, the advisor chooses the specific **securities** (e.g., schemes from existing holdings or other funds) that will implement the client’s strategy and enters transaction details for each .\n\n- **Validation and constraints**  \n  - The platform’s **Validations and Warnings** validate securities to ensure they meet eligibility rules and configuration standards before they can be ordered (for example, checking that the scheme is active, tradable, and allowed for that client type) .\n\n- **Composition and exposure data**  \n  - For instruments like mutual funds, the system holds **asset and sector exposure details**, allowing planners to assess how a set of selected funds aligns with the client’s risk profile and diversification needs.\n\n---\n\n## 7. How these components work together in financial planning\n\nPutting it together, financial planning in the platform is performed as follows:\n\n1. Maintain foundational data and governance: client profile and KYC, risk profile configuration, model portfolio, security master, and disclaimers.  \n2. Use planning tools and dashboards to understand client goals and risk appetite, and determine an appropriate allocation and product strategy.  \n3. Move to Product Selection, choose eligible securities, and proceed to the **Product Selection Summary** to review and parameterize transactions (e.g., SIP).  \n4. Run **General Validation** and detailed **Validations and Warnings** to ensure suitability, regulatory compliance, and technical correctness.  \n5. Present and enforce **Disclaimer Maintenance** output (relevant disclosures) at confirmation points.  \n6. Capture and submit orders, which generate **transactions** in the chosen **securities**, thereby implementing the financial plan.  \n7. Use the Customer Dashboard’s holdings, transactions, and product cart views to monitor, review, and periodically adjust the plan as client circumstances or market conditions change.\n\nThis integrated flow ensures that financial planning is not just a one-time recommendation, but a governed, validated, and fully executable process from advice through to trade settlement and ongoing oversight.	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["investments","Risk Appetite Mapping","Model Portfolio Maintenance","Disclaimer Maintenance","products","mutual fund holdings","approved funds","Risk Rating","Return","AMC"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:approved_funds","system:disclaimer_maintenance","dataentity:mutual_fund_holdings","dataentity:return","dataentity:disclaimer_maintenance","dataentity:model_pf_maintenance","system:risk_appetite_mapping","datastore:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:risk_rating","report:disclaimer_maintenance","dataentity:investments","dataentity:amc","aum:return","system:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","dataentity:products"],"expanded_nodes":42,"expanded_edges":1230,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise wh