ionnaire to collect the necessary inputs. - The questionnaires’ questions are fetched from questionnaire maintenance, ensuring consistent structure and governance for risk assessment. # 2) Goals and planning context - Planning activities are framed around financial goals. The planning journey explicitly references “Planning for Financial Goals and Making Investments,” underscoring goal-setting as a foundational input to the plan. Users can view and manage a summary of goals within the client journey. - Goals are also surfaced in goal-related dashboards, where a summary of the customer’s goals is accessible as part of the planning process. # 3) Wealth planning constructs (plan type and objectives) - The wealth planning component provides distinct plan types (e.g., Wealth Planning, Retirement Planning, Education Planning, Protection Planning, Tax Planning, Execution Planning), which define the overarching planning domain and objectives. This framing guides what investments or products are eligible within a plan. - Within a plan, plan objectives articulate concrete aims (e.g., Grow Wealth, Preserve Wealth) and align with the chosen plan type (e.g., Retirement). This clarifies the intended outcome of the plan. # 4) Plan generation and recommendations - Plan generation occurs inside the wealth-planning context, leveraging the selected plan type and objectives to generate a structured plan and associated investment recommendations. The explicit linkage between plan types/objectives and planning activity is illustrated by the wealth-planning constructs described in the planning journey documents. # 5) Execution and translation into actions - When plan recommendations involve investment transactions (e.g., mutual funds), the system supports order capture, authorization, and routing as part of the investment workflow. These steps form the bridge from planning to execution, ensuring proper approvals and traceability before settlements. # 6) Documentation and compliance - Actions and data changes—especially around risk profiling, planning inputs, and investments—are captured in audit trails, enabling traceability and compliance review. The audit-trail literature lists plan-related and risk-profile activities as tracked entities. # 7) Review, approvals, and ongoing monitoring - Where deviations or escalations occur (e.g., risk-deviation scenarios), these may be routed for escalation as part of the governance process, aligning with risk-management workflows. - Ongoing monitoring and governance are supported by the integrated risk and planning questionnaires and governance mechanisms described in the planning and risk-profiling journeys. # Data entities and system components involved - Data entities: Risk Profile Questionnaire; Financial Profiling; Investment Knowledge Profiling; Risk Profiling; Goals; Customer; (plan-related constructs) Wealth Planning; Plan Type; Plan Objective; Audit Trail; Compliance; Documentation. These data elements underpin the end-to-end flow from data collection to plan execution and governance. - System components: Questionnaires and questionnaire maintenance for risk profiling; Wealth Planning modules (supporting plan type/objective definitions); Planning-to-execution linkage (order capture, authorization, and routing for investments); Audit trails for compliance and governance; Planning-related user journeys and dashboards that expose goals and plan status. These are referenced across the planning and risk-profiling journeys.	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Risk Profile Questionnaire","Portfolio Performance Report","Customer Dashboard","Portfolio View","Flow Diagram","Prerequisite","INVESTOR","List of Risk profiles","PRODUCT SELECTION SCREEN","Model Portfolio – Order Placement"],"seed_node_ids":["report:pf_view","dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","report:product_selection_screen","report:pf_performance_report","report:customer_dashboard","dataentity:list_ris