 opportunity/lead summary, customer composition, revenue, and prospect-to-client conversions, analogous to the RM dashboard widgets (AUM, Opportunity Summary, Customer Composition, Revenue under Management, Prospects to Clients) used for individual RMs .\n\n3. **Drill from team-level widgets to RM breakdown**  \n   - Each summary widget (e.g., **Lead / Opportunity Summary**, **Prospects to Clients**, **Asset Under Management**) supports a **Level 2 view** where data is broken down **by RM** or **by lead status**. For example, separate design artefacts specify Level 2 "Lead status by RM" to see how each RM is performing on lead stages .\n   - The drill interaction is typically via clicking on the widget bar/pie segment or a “View Details / Level 2” link.\n\n4. **Open RM-level dashboard for a specific RM**  \n   - From the RM breakdown grid, supervisor chooses a specific RM row (e.g., via hyperlink on RM name) to open that **RM’s Dashboard** view.\n   - The RM Dashboard shows that RM’s AUM, opportunity summary, customer composition, gain/loss by customers, revenue under management, and prospects-to-clients widgets at an individual level .\n\n5. **Drill from RM dashboard to underlying customers / leads**  \n   - Further drill-downs allow navigation from each widget to **customer or lead lists** mapped to that RM. For example, clicking prospects-to-clients or opportunity widgets can open a **Lead/Prospect workspace filtered by that RM**, time frame, and status (New, In-Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected, etc.) .\n\nThis path gives a simple mental model: **Supervisor Dashboard → Level 2 (by RM or lead status) → Individual RM Dashboard → Detailed lead/prospect/customer lists.**\n\n---\n\n## 2. Required data fields on the drill path\n\nEach drill level should expose only the fields relevant to its purpose while enabling consistent filtering.\n\n### 2.1 Supervisor Dashboard (team-level)\nKey data elements:\n- **RM Identifier**: RM ID, RM name.\n- **Team/Hierarchy context**: branch, region, segment, wealth hub where applicable .\n- **Aggregate KPIs per RM (summed or averaged)**:\n  - Total AUM and Wealth AUM (sum of holdings across customers mapped to the RM) .\n  - Total customers with wealth products mapped to each RM .\n  - Total revenue generated by customers mapped to each RM .\n  - Net new money (inflows – outflows) per RM .\n  - Lead funnel metrics per RM – counts by lead status (New, Ready for Follow-Up, In Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected) .\n\n### 2.2 Level 2: Lead / Opportunity status by RM\nFields in the Level 2 grid or chart should typically include:\n- RM Name / RM ID.\n- Lead count by status (New, Ready for Follow-Up, In Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected) .\n- Percentage distribution of leads by status (for comparison).\n- Conversion metrics (e.g., number and rate of "Client Accepted").\n- Average conversion time (Lead Created Date to Client Accepted Date).\n\nA separate **Lead Status by RM** view is explicitly referenced as a Level 2 reporting artefact, indicating this breakdown is standard in the design .\n\n### 2.3 RM Dashboard (individual RM view)\nFor each RM, the RM Dashboard should display:\n- **Asset under Management** (AUM) and **Revenue under Management** widgets .\n- **Opportunity / Lead Summary**: opportunities and leads assigned to that RM, with counts by stage.\n- **Prospects to Clients**: conversions from prospect to customer for that RM .\n- **Customer Composition**: segmentation of customers mapped to that RM.\n- **Peer-to-Peer benchmarking** (optional): comparison of RM vs peers on AUM, customers with wealth products, revenue and net new money .\n\n### 2.4 Lead / Prospect Workspaces (detailed lists)\nWhen the supervisor drills into the underlying lead lists for a given RM:\n- Lead/Prospect ID and name.\n- Customer ID / CIF where applicable.\n- RM assigned.\n- Branch / region.\n- Lead type – Lead vs CIF (existing wealth customer) .\n- Lead status (New, Ready for Follow-Up, In Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected) .\n- Key dates:\n  - Lead creation date.\n  - Last activity date.\n  - Prospect conversion date.\n  - Customer onboarding date.\n- Product interest / opportunity value (to support pipeline value calculations).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Filters and slicing dimensions\n\nAcross Supervisor Dashboard, Level 2 views and RM dashboards, the following filters should be supported:\n\n- **Time frame**: As-on date / period (e.g., today, MTD, QTD, YTD, custom range). Many dashboards explicitly display data "as on current date" in peer benchmarking and dashboard widgets .\n- **Region / Branch / Wealth Hub**: Filter to show only RMs under particular branches or wealth hubs, which are maintained through branch/segment/wealth hub attributes on the customer and RM mappings .\n- **Team / Supervisor hierarchy**: For supervisors managing multiple teams.\n- **RM Name or ID**: Search/filter RMs for targeted analysis.\n- **Lead/Prospect Status**: For the drilled lead lists (New, Ready for Follow-Up, etc.) .\n- **Client Type (Wealth vs Non-wealth)**: Dashboards should **exclude non-wealth customers**, implemented by defaulting non-wealth customers’ RM to a dummy "Vacant" that is not present in user hierarchy so that non-wealth records are not picked up in RM/Supervisor dashboards .\n\n---\n\n## 4. Core KPIs for RM performance\n\nFrom a business perspective, the drill-down should surface the following KPIs at RM and team level (computed using underlying lead, prospect and customer data):\n\n1. **Lead-to-client conversion rate**  \n   - Numerator: Leads assigned to the RM that reach "Client Accepted" / converted to customer.  \n   - Denominator: Total leads assigned to RM in the selected period.  \n   - Supported by explicit lead statuses including Client Accepted and Client Rejected .\n\n2. **Average conversion time**  \n   - Average days from lead creation to client acceptance or customer onboarding, computed from captured lead creation and conversion dates.\n\n3. **Pipeline value (opportunity value)**  \n   - Sum of expected AUM or revenue for open leads/opportunities assigned to RM.\n\n4. **AUM and Wealth AUM**  \n   - Total holdings value of all investment and insurance products held by customers mapped to the RM, and optionally total AUM including CASA/FD per RM  .\n\n5. **Revenue under management**  \n   - Revenue or commission generated by all mapped customers for the selected time frame .\n\n6. **Net new money**  \n   - Net inflows minus outflows for customers mapped to each RM .\n\n7. **Number of active clients and client growth**  \n   - Count of wealth customers (Client Type = Primary) mapped to the RM, along with new-to-wealth and existing-to-wealth classifications where needed  .\n\n8. **Lead activity efficiency**  \n   - Average number of follow-ups per conversion, response time to new leads, etc., drawing on lead activity logs.\n\nThese KPIs mirror existing RM dashboard and peer benchmarking capabilities, simply re-aggregated at supervisor level and broken down per RM  .\n\n---\n\n## 5. Data-model relationships\n\nThe drill-down relies on clean relationships across leads, prospects, customers and RM assignments:\n\n1. **Lead → RM**  \n   - Each lead stores **Assigned RM** (RM ID) and **Branch/Region**, enabling filtering and counts per RM and the "Lead status by RM" view  .\n\n2. **Lead → Prospect → Customer**  \n   - Journey is explicitly defined: lead → qualified to prospect → onboarded customer .\n   - Lead and prospect records maintain references to the resulting customer/CIF ID when converted, enabling conversion rate/time calculations.\n\n3. **Customer → RM mapping**  \n   - Each customer has a **primary RM** and optionally secondary RM, as well as Client Type (Primary/Secondary) and other attributes like Client Category, Wealth Hub and Segment  .\n   - Dashboards and RM crediting are **always based on primary RM mapping**: revenues and dashboard credit accrue to primary RM even if a secondary RM executes an order .\n   - Non-wealth customers (Client Type = Secondary) have RM defaulted to "Vacant" and are excluded from RM/Supervisor dashboards .\n\n4. **Customer / Account → AUM & Revenue**  \n   - Investment, insurance, CASA/FD accounts are tied to customer records, and aggregation logic rolls them up by primary RM to compute AUM and revenue widgets .\n\n5. **User hierarchy → Supervisor**  \n   - Supervisors see dashboards for RMs **within their user hierarchy**; the dummy "Vacant" RM is intentionally excluded from hierarchy so related customers do not appear in RM/Supervisor views .\n\nThese relationships ensure that any drill from a team widget to RM, then to customer or lead records, is consistent and traceable.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Screens and reports involved\n\nIn a typical implementation, the following screens/reports participate in the drill-down journey:\n\n1. **RM Office / Dashboard Landing**  \n   - Entry point from which both RM and Supervisor dashboards are accessed .\n\n2. **Supervisor Dashboard (Summary view)**  \n   - Team-level widgets for AUM, Revenue, Prospects to Clients, Lead/Opportunity Summary and Customer Composition \n   - Clickable widgets for Level 2 drill-down (by RM / by lead status)  .\n\n3. **Level 2 – Lead / Status by RM report**  \n   - Tabular view presenting lead counts and conversion metrics per RM across statuses .\n\n4. **RM Dashboard (individual RM)**  \n   - Same widget set as above but scoped to a single RM, plus peer benchmarking views  .\n\n5. **Lead / Prospect Workspace & My Leads**  \n   - Lists of leads and prospects with search and filter by RM, Branch, Status, Type (Lead vs CIF) .\n\n6. **Customer Dashboard / Customer Workspace**  \n   - For detailed review of individual customers mapped to an RM, including holdings and transactions; accessible based on RM mapping and user hierarchy rules  .\n\n---\n\n## 7. Permissions and entitlement checks\n\nTo ensure supervisors see only authorised data and that KPIs are attributed correctly, implement these key rules:\n\n1. **Hierarchy-based access**  \n   - Supervisor Dashboard should only show RMs (and their customers/leads) that fall under the supervisor’s **user hierarchy**. Dummy RMs such as "Vacant" are excluded from the hierarchy to prevent non-wealth customers from appearing in RM dashboards .\n\n2. **Customer card access**  \n   - An RM can access a customer card via search only if they are mapped as **Primary or Secondary RM**; broader RM Workspace users with elevated roles may access additional cards, but standard RMs are limited to mapped customers .\n\n3. **Wealth vs non-wealth visibility**  \n   - Dashboards must exclude non-wealth customers based on Client Type and RM mapping logic, ensuring regulatory and reporting consistency .\n\n4. **Role-based dashboard access**  \n   - RM roles access RM Dashboard and self-assessment features; supervisors and managers gain access to Supervisor Dashboard and Level 2 team views, but not necessarily to each RM’s detailed customer-level data unless hierarchy allows it .\n\n---\n\n## 8. Audit and logging considerations\n\nFor a robust supervisory drill-down capability, the system should log:\n\n- **Dashboard access events**: user, role, timestamp, and which dashboard or RM they viewed (Supervisor Dashboard, specific RM Dashboard, Level 2 views).\n- **Filter selections**: date ranges, branches/regions, RM selections, client type filters, so that reproduced views can be reconstructed in audits.\n- **Record-level access**: when a supervisor or RM opens a particular Lead, Prospect or Customer card, log user ID, record ID, time, and action (view/edit) for compliance and internal audit.\n- **Attribution checks**: ensure that revenue, AUM and conversion KPIs remain tied to primary RM mappings even when secondary RMs or other roles execute transactions, aligned with the rule that credit goes to primary RM .\n\n---\n\n## 9. Business summary\n\nBy structuring the journey around a clear hierarchy of **Supervisor Dashboard → Level 2 (Lead/Status by RM) → RM Dashboard → Lead/Customer Workspaces**, tied together via consistent RM and customer mappings, supervisors gain a concise, actionable view of team performance. Embedded filters, permission controls, and detailed audits ensure that insights are reliable, compliant, and aligned with the underlying lead-to-customer data model.\n\n\n### Sources\n[1] SBI_Journey of Lead to Prospect to Customer_V10_CCV13.pdf  \n[2] SBI International-Journey of Self_Assessment and Supervisor Assessment_RM Dashboard_V12_CCV10docx.pdf  \n[3] IIFL_Journey of Self-Assessment and Supervisor Assessment-RM Dashboard_CCV13.pdf  \n[4] 360One_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf  \n[5] SBI_Journey of Assesing Risk_DC3_Lead status by RM.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["NAV of the security","Market Value (INR)","Switch-Out NAV","Current Market Value","RM","Order Book Report","Customer Dashboard","Risk Rating","Product risk profile","Portfolio Performance Report"],"seed_node_ids":["report:customer_dashboard","dataentity:transaction","dataentity:product_risk_profile","dataentity:market_value_inr","report:pf_performance_report","aum:market_value_inr","report:order_book_report","system:rmws","dataentity:risk_rating","dataentity:switch","aum:current_market_value","aum:switch_out_nav","dataentity:rm","aum:nav_security"],"expanded_nodes":76,"expanded_edges":138,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: resp_0222c44ba345f6d90069413bf8b854819ca3169ebb71f3c5e4\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Inter