ly for each risk profile via Model Portfolio Maintenance. This enables a consistent, risk-profile–driven mix across clients and supports uniform implementation of model updates and rebalances [2].\n- Model portfolios commonly capture asset allocations, sub-asset allocations, and security portfolios, which can be linked to security-level portfolios and then to client holdings as part of the model portfolio workflow [6].\n- The same model portfolio design supports the decomposition of a model into underlying security orders for bulk execution, ensuring consistency of advice and scaling across portfolios [3].\n\n2) Drift detection and visibility\n- Rebalancing relies on monitoring the model asset allocation against the actual holdings of a client’s portfolio. Views such as Deviation, Actual, and Selected exposures show how the model compares to current holdings and the impact of chosen securities. Asset Class exposure and Sector exposure widgets provide visibility into where drift is occurring and how it affects composition [4].\n- Model compositions and asset allocations can be viewed and analyzed at the model level and across asset classes to inform rebalancing decisions [6].\n\n3) Triggers for rebalancing (time-based vs event-based)\n- Rebalancing can be system-initiated (auto trigger) or advisor-initiated (manual). Clients may opt into auto-rebalance enrolment or RM-driven execution, enabling either periodic or event-driven rebalancing based on the model configuration and client preferences [1].\n- Time-based triggers are encompassed by configurable rebalancing frequencies and schedules (e.g., daily/weekly/monthly) tied to the model’s governance and client preferences, while event-based triggers arise from model updates, risk changes, or explicit RM actions [3].\n\n4) Drift thresholds and discipline (gap controls)\n- Drift controls are enforced through validations and cut-off behaviors (e.g., soft vs. hard stops around NAV cut-offs) to ensure orderly rebalance execution and to manage deviations at the security level during rebalancing cycles [1].\n- Deviation and exposure analyses, including model vs. actual vs. selected portfolios, provide a practical mechanism to assess when drift crosses thresholds that warrant a rebalance [4].\n\n5) Cash flows and transaction types\n- Rebalancing interacts with the broader cash-flow framework, including lump-sum purchases and systematic investments (SIP), which feed into model-based orders. The model order journey captures how model orders are initiated, detailed, paid, and routed for execution, with downstream settlement and funding considerations. This is described in model-order journeys and the broader mutual-fund/order-journey workflows [3], [5].\n\n6) Execution workflow within the PM system (Model Portfolio, Order Placement, Reporting)\n- Model Portfolio Maintenance defines the modeled asset mix; this is carried into a model order placement journey that transforms a single model decision into a fleet of security-level orders, enabling scalable, consistent execution across clients [3].\n- The model order journey comprises steps such as Model Order Initiation, Model Order Details, and Model Order Payment, followed by routing to product processors and settlement, with supervisory approvals as needed. This ensures compliance, risk controls, and traceability of rebalance activities [3], [5].\n- Execution is often performed via an integrated PMS flow that includes order capture, supervisor authorization, order routing to processors, and settlement against holdings, with performance and risk analytics feeding back into reporting modules [5].\n\n7) Reporting and exposure-based oversight\n- Reporting views include Asset Class composition, Sector composition, and Exposures, which provide model-level and portfolio-level visibility into how rebalanced portfolios align with target allocations and risk budgets. These views are supported by the model-based exposure and deviation dashboards described in end-to-end journeys [4].\n- Portfolio Master and related mappings (portfolio, model, holdings, goals, and folio) underpin the governance and traceability of rebalance actions, ensuring consistency and auditability across clients [3], [6].\n\n8) Practical navigation and references across the PM ecosystem\n- Model definitions and sub-asset allocations are defined and linked through the model portfolio creation flow, enabling linkage between asset allocation, security portfolios, and the model that drives orders [6].\n- The G073-based basket-trigger journeys illustrate how model-based orders are initiated, consented, paid, and positioned for execution, including how model and portfolio identifiers propagate through the process [3].\n- The PM ecosystem supports a unified journey from model creation to order placement and settlement, including prerequisites such as risk-profile assessment, risk appetite mapping, and maintenance of security portfolios, which collectively enable consistent rebalance execution [2], [5].\n\n9) Key reference concepts tied to the unified process\n- Model Portfolio Maintenance: central definition of model asset allocations per risk profile, linking to composition, security portfolios, and risk settings [2].\n- Model Portfolio – Order Placement: the journey that transforms a model decision into fleet-wide security orders, enabling scalable, consistent execution [3].\n- Model Portfolio - Composition / Asset Class & Sector views: provide the construct for understanding target vs. actual exposures and the distribution across asset classes and sectors [4], [6].\n- Portfolio Master: governs the master records and mappings (Portfolio, Model, Holdings, Folio) essential for rebalance governance and auditability [3], [6].\n- G073 - Model based order trigger: defines the basket-based, model-driven order trigger flow that activates rebalance actions [3].\n- Exposures: the exposure analytics feed rebalancing decisions and reporting, including asset-cl