ns.  \n  - Ref: Maybank / HSBC onboarding flows.\n\n#### 2. Multi‑Factor Authentication (MFA)\n\n- The platform enforces **two‑factor authentication (2FA)** for ongoing access:\n  - Factor 1: Password/MPIN (knowledge).\n  - Factor 2: OTP or token (possession), typically via:\n    - SMS or email OTP, or\n    - App‑generated token.\n- Often, mobile number verification with OTP is also completed during onboarding, providing an additional verified channel.\n- This is aligned with financial‑sector security and compliance requirements: knowing the password alone is not sufficient to access the account.  \n  - Ref: BOC Philippines Tech – Trust systems; Banque Misr / HSBC security requirements.\n\n#### 3. Device and biometric security\n\n- After credentials are set, the app may prompt the user to enable:\n  - **Touch ID / Face ID** or other device biometrics.\n- Benefits:\n  - Adds a **biometric factor** (something the user is).\n  - Ties access to a specific device.\n- The current device can be marked as “trusted.”  \n  - Logins from new or unrecognized devices trigger extra checks (e.g., fresh OTP) before access is granted.  \n  - Ref: HSBC_DIY onboarding – MPIN & biometric login.\n\n#### 4. Secure session establishment\n\n- Once credentials and any second factor are verified, the app:\n  - Creates a secure **session token/ID**.\n  - Forces all traffic over **HTTPS** to encrypt data in transit.\n  - Uses secure cookies or tokens to bind the session to the authenticated user.\n- Security controls on the session:\n  - **Inactivity timeouts**: automatic logout after a defined idle period.\n  - Optional display of last login time / recent failed attempts to help users spot suspicious activity.  \n  - Ref: BOC / Maybank technical security requirements.\n\n#### 5. Entitlements and access control (RBAC)\n\n- Immediately after the session is established, **role‑based access control (RBAC)** is applied:\n  - The system checks the user’s role/profile.\n  - Only the appropriate menus, data, and functions are shown.\n- Examples:\n  - A retail client sees only their own portfolios and services.\n  - No access to advisor or admin functions.\n- This limits what even a valid, logged‑in user can do, reducing the impact of any compromise.  \n  - Ref: Banque Misr Tech response – Custody; BOC RBAC references.\n\n#### 6. Compliance and additional security controls\n\n- The process is designed to meet financial‑industry security and regulatory expectations:\n  - **MFA** for login.\n  - **Encryption** of sensitive data in transit and at rest.\n  - **Secure storage** of credentials (hashed, never in plain text).\n  - **Audit logging** of authentication events.\n  - **Account lockout** after excessive failed attempts to prevent brute‑force attacks.\n- Combined factors:\n  - Something the user knows: password/MPIN.\n  - Something the user has: OTP, trusted device.\n  - Something the user is: biometric (where enabled).\n- All of this is handled over encrypted channels to provide **defense in depth** from the moment email verification is completed.  \n\n---\n\n**Key References**\n\n1. Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V11 – Email/OTP verification and credential setup.  \n2. HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10 – Post‑verification MPIN and biometric login.  \n3. BOC Philippines Tech – Trust systems – Authentication, MFA, and session security.  \n4. Banque Misr Tech response – Custody – Role‑based access control and entitlements.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Explain how the application ensures a user’s account is secured immediately after the user verifies their email address.",\n  "expanded_question": "What is the secure access process right after a user completes email verification in the wealth management app? Specifically, describe the next authentication steps (credentials setup and MFA), how a session is established, how user permissions are enforced, any device-specific security measures (like biometrics or trusted devices), and what compliance controls ensure the account remains secure at this stage.",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Email Verification",\n    "Authentication Credentials",\n    "Multi-Factor Authentication (2FA)",\n    "Session Management",\n    "Access Control (Entitlements)",\n    "Device/Biometric Security",\n    "Compliance Standards"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    { "id": "1", "source": "Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V11.pdf" },\n    { "id": "2", "source": "HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10.pdf" },\n    { "id": "3", "source": "BOC Philippines Tech - Trust systems.pdf" },\n    { "id": "4", "source": "Banque Misr Tech response - Custody.pdf" }\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Immediate Post-Email Verification Security Steps:** After a user verifies their email (usually by entering an OTP or clicking a verification link), the application immediately prompts them to secure their account with strong authentication. The user is typically asked to set up a personal login credential, such as creating a secure password or a 6-digit MPIN (mobile PIN) for the account ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Internal%20to%20Jio%20BlackRock%20and,Intellect%20Page%208)). This step establishes a **knowledge factor** (something only the user knows) to protect future logins. \\n\\n- **Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):** The platform enforces multi-factor authentication for account access. Email verification itself is one factor of identity proof (since the user had to input a one-time password sent to their email) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=user%20level%2C%202FA%20can%20be,SAML%29%205)). Often a mobile number is verified with an OTP as well during onboarding, adding a second factor. Going forward, logging in will require the user’s password/MPIN **plus** an additional factor (for example, a one-time code sent via SMS or email, or an app-generated token) ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=to%20SMS%2FEmail,for%20transaction%20authorization%2Fworkflow%20approval%20in)). This two-factor authentication is mandatory in financial applications to meet security compliance – it ensures that just knowing the password is not enough to access the account ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)). \\n\\n- **Device & Biometric Security:** As an added layer, the user may enable device-based authentication after email verification. For instance, upon setting their MPIN/password, the app can prompt the user to **enable Touch ID or Face ID** login on that device ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Internal%20to%20Jio%20BlackRock%20and,Intellect%20Page%208)). Enabling biometrics ties the account to the user’s physical device (something the user *is*), allowing convenient yet secure logins. The current device can be marked as trusted once this is set up, whereas any login from a new or unrecognized device will trigger additional verification (such as requiring a fresh OTP) to ensure it’s really the user. This device-aware approach prevents unauthorized devices from accessing the account. \\n\\n- **Secure Session Establishment:** After the user’s credentials (and any second factor) are verified, the system establishes a secure authenticated session. The application generates a session token or ID and **all communication is forced over HTTPS** to protect data in transit ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=into%20the%20application%20through%20Finger,BlackRock%20and%20Intellect%20Page%209)). The session is encrypted and bound to the user’s identity, typically with secure cookies or tokens. For safety, the platform applies session timeout policies – if the user stays inactive beyond a set duration, the session will automatically expire and log out the user, preventing others from hijacking an idle session ([file-LjaRghvPuPPa72CNQ14YLR](file://file-LjaRghvPuPPa72CNQ14YLR#:~:text=n%20Logs,of%20inactivity%20to%20maintain%20security)). At login, the system may also display the time of the last successful login or any recent failed attempts as a security reminder to the user (ensuring they notice any unauthorized access attempts). \\n\\n- **Entitlements & Access Control:** Once logged in, the user’s access is governed by role-based entitlements. The application checks the user’s profile/role to determine what features and data they are allowed to see or use. **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)** is enforced so that the user only sees the menus and functions appropriate to their role and permissions ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Button%20on%20the%20Home%20page,and%20click%20on%20the%20%E2%80%9CSend)) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=ARX%20provides%20Role%20Based%20access,in%20the%20system%20with%20their)). For example, a client user will only have access to their own portfolio and related services, and not any administrative or advisor functions. This entitlement check happens immediately upon session setup to tailor the dashboard and disable any unauthorized options. By limiting functionality to authorized areas, the platform ensures that even a logged-in user cannot stray into areas beyond their scope. \\n\\n- **Compliance and Security Measures:** The post-email-verification login process adheres to stringent compliance standards for financial data. Regulatory policies require measures like MFA for user login and encryption of sensitive information, which the system follows. The user’s newly created password/MPIN is stored securely (hashed and never in plain text) in compliance with security guidelines ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Need%20to%20enter%20the%20email,Yes%20Not%20Applicable%20Set%20MPIN)). All authentication actions are logged for audit, and excessively incorrect login attempts result in account lockout to thwart brute-force attacks ([file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y](file://file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y#:~:text=The%20system%20must%20enforce%20account,Authentication)) ([file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y](file://file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y#:~:text=Use%20multi,Authentication)). The combination of something the user knows (password/MPIN), something they have (OTP code or trusted device), and something they are (biometric ID) — all handled through encrypted channels — provides **defense in depth**. These controls ensure that immediately after verifying their email, the user’s access to the application is protected by multiple layers of security and aligned with industry compliance requirements ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)) ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=into%20the%20application%20through%20Finger,BlackRock%20and%20Intellect%20Page%209)). \\n\\n**Sources:**\\n1. Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V11 (Email/OTP Verification Step)\\n2. HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10 (Post-Email Verification – Set MPIN & Biometric Login)\\n3. BOC Philippines Tech – Trust systems (Authentication & Security Requirements)\\n4. Banque Misr Tech Response – Custody (Role-Based Access Control and Entitlements)"\n}	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"fallback","confidence":0,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765882873367_5sx011vx9","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0222c44ba345f6d90069413bf8b854819ca3169ebb71f3c5e4","reportFormat":"Custom"}	resp_0222c44ba345f6d90069413bf8b854819ca3169ebb71f3c5e4	t	2025-12-16 11:09:52.22