sponding risk levels. [5] - The risk questionnaire itself contains fields and structure used to collect customer responses (question descriptions, mandatory flags, multi-select options, scoring types, computation types, and score ranges). [2] - Question definitions and scoring rules (e.g., None vs Range scoring, Sum computation, and range-based scoring) are standard across implementations. [7] ## 3. Questionnaire configuration and flow - Users can create and configure risk profile questionnaires within the application, including setting up questions, mandatory flags, multi-select options, scoring types, and calculation logic. Screen: Create a new risk profile questionnaire. [1] - Each question supports various attributes such as Mandatory Type, Multi Select, Scoring Type (None/Range), Computation Type (Sum), and from/to score ranges with an associated final Score. [2] - The risk questionnaire structure supports additional elements like warnings, acknowledgements, and disclaimers to be presented during profiling. [2] ## 4. Scoring rules and mapping - Scoring can be configured per question as None or Range, with a Sum computation for aggregating responses across questions. Range-type scoring maps specific response ranges to a final score. [7] - The aggregated scores from the questionnaire feed into a risk appetite/risk profile mapping to produce a final risk rating for the customer. This linkage between questionnaire scores and risk appetite is described in risk profiling configurations. [1] ## 5. Validations and governance - The system enforces governance checks during profiling and transaction processing, including general validations and KYC-related validations (e.g., mandatory fields, length checks, and KYC status gating). [4] - There are risk-profile-specific validations in order-flow scenarios, such as ensuring a risk profile exists and is current; otherwise, certain actions (purchase, switch, SIP) may be disallowed. If the risk profile is expired, related actions are blocked; if no risk profile is present, actions are blocked. [3] ## 6. Storage and ownership of risk data - Risk profiles are surfaced and managed within the customer and RM dashboards, reflecting risk-based grouping and visibility (e.g., customers grouped by risk profile, tracked by AUM). This governance/monitoring is shown in RM dashboards and customer dashboards. [13] - Risk appetite mappings and questionnaire configurations are stored as part of the risk framework, enabling mapping between questionnaire results and risk brackets. [5] ## 7. System modules and screens involved - The risk profiling configuration and execution involve modules such as the risk questionnaire designer (screen for creating risk profile questionnaires) and the PMS/Intellect integration points used to read/write risk-related data during transactions. Screens and flows for risk questionnaires are described in risk profiling journey documents. [1] - The risk profile framework is implemented across multiple platforms (e.g., Intellect, HSBC PWS), with cross-system orchestration to enforce risk constraints during order placement and portfolio actions. [2] ## 8. How the risk profile drives portfolio decisions and approvals - Product risk checks are performed against customer risk; if product risk exceeds customer risk, a notification is generated to alert the user. This gating ensures alignment between customer risk capacity and product selections. [3] - If a risk profile is expired, or if a customer does not have a risk profile, certain actions (Purchase/Switch/SIP) are disallowed, enforcing governance over portfolio changes. [3] - Risk-profile data also informs RM dashboards and customer composition analyses, enabling awareness and governance by risk tier when reviewing portfolios. [16] ## 9. In practice: a high-level flow - Create/configure a risk profile questionnaire (questions, scoring rules, mandatory fields). [1] - Collect customer responses and compute a risk score (sum or range-based computation). [7] - Map the score to a risk appetite/risk profile using predefined risk appetite mappings. [5] - Enforce governance: ensure KYC status is valid, and prevent actions if risk profile is missing or expired. [4] - Reflect and monitor the result in dashboards (customer RM views, risk-profile-based grouping). [16] ## Sources - JBR_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [1] - HSBC_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [2] - HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf [3] - 360One_Journey of Assesing Risk_V10_CCV15.pdf [4] - SBI International_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [5]	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","Customer Risk profile","Product risk profile","Risk Appetite Mapping","Risk Rating","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Intellect","HSBC PWS","PMS application","KYC status validation"],"seed_node_ids":["system:pms_app","aum:risk_profiling","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_rating","dataentity:customer","dataentity:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","aum:customer_risk_profile","dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","system:intellect","compliance:kyc_status_validation","system:risk_appetite_mapping","system:hsbc_pws","report:risk_profile_questionnaire","dataentity:product_risk_profile"],"expanded_nodes":93,"expanded_edges":221,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser's Question: How does risk profiling work in the system?\\n\\n[Retrieval Safety Guardrails]\\nYou are a retrieval-only assistant.\\nYou MUST ans