ed with the model portfolio (and sometimes the individual securities) are used to ensure the rebalanced mix remains within acceptable risk bands [6].\n- Frequency and time horizon: Rebalancing cadence and horizon are configured as part of the model definition, guiding how often rebalance checks are performed or triggered [6].\n- Additional inputs: Investment amount or model investment details and any per-security constraints that drive unit-level calculations during rebalancing [2], as well as potential cut-off and NAV behavior rules that affect feasibility on a given day [11, 12].\n\n2) Triggers that initiate rebalancing\n- System-initiated (auto) triggers: Rebalancing can be automatically triggered by the platform based on schedule, drift, or threshold criteria defined in the model (auto rebalance) [3].\n- Advisor-initiated (manual) triggers: Rebalancing can also be triggered manually by an advisor or RM based on client needs or updated views [3].\n- Tolerance/threshold rules: Rebalancing decisions are governed by tolerance definitions or thresholds that determine when drift from target allocations warrants execution [6].\n- Additional trigger considerations: Cut-off rules and response to fund status or NAV behavior can influence whether a rebalance proceeds on a given day [15].\n\n3) Decision logic: how the rebalance is determined\n- Rule-based vs optimization: The model framework can use rule-based thresholds (tolerance bands, predefined weights) to decide whether to rebalance, or apply optimization to meet target allocations under constraints [6].\n- Thresholds and risk alignment: Thresholds for rebalancing are parameterized in the model portfolio definition to ensure actions stay aligned with risk targets ([6], with rule-parameterization described in the model definition). \n- Dependencies and controls: Rebalancing logic is implemented within model order journeys with configurable maker-checker approvals, ensuring consistent application across portfolios [3].\n\n4) Constraints and considerations that shape the rebalance\n- Tax considerations: Rebalancing decisions may be constrained by tax implications in a real implementation, though explicit tax handling details are not universally mandated across all references; practical platforms often model tax-aware paths within approval rules and scheduling constraints [3].\n- Transaction costs: Costs associated with trades influence whether a rebalance proceeds and its size, often embedded in model parameters or via third-party risk/analytics engines that trigger rebalance actions [15].\n- Liquidity: Availability of liquidity and trading windows affect feasibility; cut-off times and NAV timing rules are used to determine tradable windows on a given day [11, 12, 15].\n\n5) Data and structures involved in the rebalancing process\n- Model portfolio data: Asset allocations, risk profile, time horizon, and tolerance definitions are stored within the model configuration to drive rebalance decisions [6].\n- Per-security inputs: Each security’s current holding, last NAV, risk rating, and other fund-level fields feed into the calculation of new units and order sizing [9], as seen in model-order journeys and market-data fields.\n- Model-level orders: Rebalancing actions generate model orders that aggregate individual security orders under a single rebalance event, with a unique model-order identifier for tracking (and potential grouping with SIP orders) [11].\n- Validation and approvals: Rebalance actions pass through validations and an optional maker-checker workflow to ensure compliance before submission [3].\n\n6) Execution flow from signal to settlement\n- Signal generation and order creation: When a rebalance signal is generated (auto or manual), a model-level rebalance order is created with the target allocations translated into per-security instructions [12].\n- Order routing and execution: After approvals, the system routes the underlying security orders to the product processor or settlement partner for execution; multi-security baskets may be submitted together to optimize settlement timing [12].\n- Settlement and holdings update: Upon trade execution and settlement, the customer holdings are updated to reflect new positions and units, and model investment status is updated accordingly [12].\n- Post-trade auditability: The entire model-order journey is auditable, with an audit trail capturing actions, modifications, and status changes related to model portfolios and associated security orders [4].\n\n7) Approvals and governance\n- Maker-checker approvals: Rebalancing actions at the model level can be governed by configurable approval workflows to ensure governance and compliance prior to execution [3].\n- Centralized model governance: Central definitions for models provide uniform application of rebalance logic across client bases, reducing suitability drift and improving auditability [3].\n\n8) Auditability and traceability\n- Audit trails capture key events across the rebalance lifecycle (model changes, order submissions, and settlements), enabling traceability and compliance reporting [5].\n\n9) Summary of the end-to-end flow\n- Input collection (current holdings, target allocations, risk metrics) → Trigger determination (system/manual, with tolerance checks) → Decision logic (rule-based or optimization under constraints) → Validation and approvals (maker-checker) → Signal generation and per-security order creation → Order routing to execution providers → Settlement and holdings update → Audit logging and reporting.\n\nNotes on where these patterns appear in practice across the referenced materials:\n- Model-level rebalance is described as part of model portfolios, with asset allocations and risk profiles guiding actions [6].\n- Triggers for rebalancing include system-initiated auto triggers and advisor-initiated manual actions, with configurable tolerance for rebalancing [3][6].\n- The order journey shows how model-level rebalance signals are turned into orders, routed for execution, and settled, with per-security details and a unique ID; governance and approvals are involved [12][3].\n- Audit trails cover model portfolios and related actions for governance and compliance [5].\n\nSources\n- JBR_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- JBR_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - G073 Part A and Part B - Basket based order trigger (1).pdf\n- EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx\n- EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx\n- 360One_Audit Trail_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- JBR_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V1_CCV1.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["return of the security","NAV of the security","number of units","Indicative Price/NAV","realized gain","Switch-Out NAV","Market Value (INR)","market value of the customer's current security holdings","Current Market Value","risk profiling"],"seed_node_ids":["aum:market_value_customer_s_current_security_holdings","aum:realized_gain","dataentity:security","aum:risk_profiling","aum:market_value_inr","dataentity:number_units","report:my_customers","dataentity:market_value_inr","dataentity:transaction","aum:indicative_price_nav","aum:switch_out_nav","report:transaction_slip","dataentity:nav","aum:current_market_value","dataentity:switch","aum:nav_security","dataentity:risk_rating","dataentity:realized_gain","aum:return_security","aum:number_units","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_profiling"],"expanded_nodes":57,"expanded_edges":79,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarit