Product Risk Rating\n- What it stands for: PRR is the numeric rating assigned to a product (or security) reflecting its risk level, derived from the product’s Risk Profile and displayed as a risk code (1–6) [1].\n- What it is derived from: PRR is derived from the Product Risk Profile (the product’s own risk characteristics) and is compared directly to the customer’s CRR in risk-workflows [1].\n- How it is displayed and used: PRR is shown as a numeric risk code (1–6) in risk-related screens (e.g., Product Selection Screen) and in risk-focused reports; products are filtered or flagged according to their PRR in relation to the customer’s CRR [3].\n\nHow CRR and PRR interact in risk workflows\n- Risk alignment checks: When PRR equals CRR + 2, the system raises a caution/warning to the user to confirm the increment in product risk relative to the customer’s risk rating [1].\n- Hard stops: If PRR > CRR + 2 (i.e., product risk is more than two levels higher than the customer’s risk rating), the system enforces a hard stop and blocks the transaction, preventing inappropriate risk exposure [1].\n- Focused vs Other funds behavior: The product list differentiates Focused Funds (PRR <= CRR) from Other Funds (PRR > CRR); only Focused Funds are typically eligible for certain actions, while Other Funds may be gated or require additional review [2].\n- Display and interpretation: Across screens (e.g., Product Selection Screen, risk dashboards, and transaction reports), risk is presented using numerical codes (1–6) rather than descriptive text to support consistent risk assessment and automated decisioning; this coding is emphasized in risk-deviation and risk-rating workflows [3].\n\nKey data sources and screens\n- Data sources: Customer Risk Profile (for CRR) and Product Risk Profile (for PRR); both are used to generate the 1–6 risk codes that populate risk screens and decision logic [1][3].\n- Screens and displays: Product Selection Screen and related product risk displays show risk codes; risk-rating-related screens, reports, and overlays (e.g., risk warnings, product risk class displays) use the 1–6 scale to communicate risk and to drive gating rules [3].\n\nImpact on client risk classification and recommendations\n- Alignment rule implications: If PRR is within one level of CRR (or equal/less), no warning is issued; a mismatch of one level prompts a warning, and a mismatch of two levels prompts a warning with review, while a mismatch greater than two levels results in a hard stop. This ensures client risk classifications and investment recommendations stay within acceptable risk boundaries defined by the customer’s risk appetite [1][2].\n- Portfolio construction guidance: Since PRR and CRR govern eligibility and gating (e.g., Focused Funds vs Other Funds), they directly influence which investments are considered suitable for a given client and thus affect recommendations and approved portfolios [2].\n\nIn short, CRR and PRR provide a quantified, codified risk alignment mechanism between a client’s risk appetite (CRR) and a product’s risk characteristics (PRR). They are computed from the respective risk profiles, expressed on a 1–6 scale, and drive warnings, hard stops, and eligible product sets within risk-rating and portfolio-risk workflows to protect clients from misaligned investments [1][2][3].\n\nSources\n- 360ONE_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV13_Part 2.pdf\n- Maybank_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF_V12_CCV10_Part 2.pdf\n- SBI_Journey of Assesing Risk_Deviation document.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Risk Rating","INVESTOR","RM","Order","customer","transaction","Product risk profile","Mutual Funds","Risk Appetite Mapping","Portfolio Performance Report"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:risk_appetite_mapping","dataentity:investor","report:pf_performance_report","dataentity:mutual_funds","dataentity:transaction","dataentity:risk_rating","dataentit