ve portfolio has drifted enough to justify a rebalance.\n\n#### 2. Identify rebalancing need and create a model order\n\nWhen the system or user determines that a client’s portfolio has drifted beyond the defined tolerance for a subscribed model, a **model order** of type **Rebalancing** is initiated:\n- Transactions at model level explicitly support a `Rebalancing` transaction type alongside Purchase, Redemption, and Switch .\n- A unique **Model Order** is created with a system‑generated **Unique ID** (model order unique number). This ID acts as the umbrella identifier under which all underlying security‑level orders for that rebalance are grouped .\n- The **Model Investment Amount** (the total amount for the model after rebalance) is captured at model order level (e.g., `orderamt` in the model order initiation), from which security‑wise amounts are derived based on target allocations .\n\n#### 3. Construct the rebalancing basket (underlying MF orders)\n\nBased on the current holdings versus target allocation and the model’s tolerance setting, the system builds the **rebalancing basket**:\n- For each mutual fund/security in the model, the system compares current actual weights to target weights and calculates buy/sell quantities required to move back within tolerance.\n- The resulting actions are represented as underlying orders under the model order:\n  - For pure buy/sell at fund level, underlying orders appear as **Purchase** or **Redemption** for the respective mutual fund .\n  - For changes between funds, the system can represent it as a **Switch (Rebalancing)**, where there is a **Switch Out Security Name** and **Switch In Security Name** specifically for rebalancing order types .\n- Each underlying MF order gets its own **Order ID**, but remains linked to the model’s **Unique ID** so that the rebalance is tracked as a single event at model level .\n\n#### 4. Submit, validate, and approve the rebalance\n\nOnce the rebalancing basket is prepared, the normal order lifecycle is used, applied to all underlying orders as part of the model order:\n- **Order capture & submission**: The rebalancing transaction (model order) is captured, with computed transaction amounts/units per mutual fund security .\n- **Validations**: Standard validations apply at this stage (e.g., product eligibility, risk profile checks, mandatory field checks), similar to regular mutual fund orders and model‑based orders. The system validates and generates the unique model order ID at this stage .\n- **Authorization/approval**: \n  - Submitted orders go for supervisor approval before execution, consistent with the standard mutual fund workflow .\n  - If any risk deviations or constraints exist, additional approval layers (e.g., higher‑level approvers) may be required, as per the same rule set used for standard MF transactions .\n\n#### 5. Trade execution and routing\n\nAfter approval, the system executes the rebalancing by routing all underlying orders to the product processor/RTA:\n- **Order routing**: Approved underlying orders (Purchase/Redemption/Switch) created under the Rebalancing model order are routed to the fund execution processor/RTA for fulfillment .\n- **Synchronous execution per model order**: All underlying orders under a given model order are expected to be sent together, and the **Order Date** is recorded at model level for the full rebalance set .\n- **Status tracking**: \n  - Model‑level status (e.g., Pending, In Progress, Expired, Failed) reflects the overall state of the rebalance .\n  - Each constituent order has its own **Order Status** (e.g., Pending, In Progress, Settlement Pending, Failed, Rejected, Settled), **Trade Date**, and amount, all visible for monitoring and exception handling .\n\n#### 6. Settlement and portfolio update\n\nWhen the RTA/trade file is received, the holdings are updated to reflect the completed rebalance:\n- **Settlement**: The system processes settlement files from the RTA/product processor and updates the customer’s mutual fund holdings accordingly, following the same settlement flow used for standard MF transactions .\n- **Portfolio realignment**: \n  - Post‑settlement, the client portfolio linked to the model reflects the new holdings and weights, now realigned closer to the model’s target allocation and within the specified tolerance.\n  - The model order’s final status is updated (e.g., Settled) once all underlying orders in the rebalancing basket are settled .\n\n#### 7. Monitoring and reporting\n\nThe rebalancing event and its underlying transactions are visible in the order monitoring and reporting views:\n- The **Order Book** can be searched and viewed by model name/ID, allowing users to see all orders placed within a model, including those with **Rebalancing** transaction type .\n- Model‑level fields like Model Name, Portfolio Name, Model Investment Amount, and Model Investment Status help track and audit each rebalance instance  .\n\nOverall, portfolio rebalancing in the application is executed as a **model order of type Rebalancing**, governed by the tolerance defined in model portfolio maintenance, decomposed into underlying mutual‑fund orders, processed through the standard MF order lifecycle (validation, approval, routing, settlement), and tracked end‑to‑end at both model and individual order level.\n\n---\n\n#### Sources\n\n- [1] JBR_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V1_CCV1.pdf\n- [2] JBR_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - G073 Part A and Part B - Basket based order trigger (1).pdf\n- [3] Maybank_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF_V12_CCV10_Part 1.pdf\n	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Model Portfolio Maintenance","G073 - Model based order trigger","Model Portfolio – Order Placement","CRISIL Portfolio Composition Master","Portfolio Master","MF Portfolio File (Crisil)","CRISIL master","Wealth Qube","HSBC PWS","Intellect"],"seed_node_ids":["datastore:model_pf_maintenance","re