lecommunications**, **retail**, and new energy. The company’s oil refining and petrochemicals unit historically drove its revenues, while in recent years consumer-facing ventures like Reliance Jio (telecom) and Reliance Retail have become major growth engines【1】. RIL’s scale is unparalleled in India – it owns the world’s largest refining complex and has built nationwide telecom and retail networks, positioning itself at the forefront of India’s economic growth【1】.\\n\\n**Core Business Segments:** RIL’s **Oil-to-Chemicals (O2C)** division encompasses oil refining, petrochemicals, and materials. This legacy segment still contributes a substantial share of revenue and operating profit, leveraging high-volume refining capacity and integrated petrochemical production【1】. In **Telecommunications**, RIL’s Reliance Jio Infocomm has become India’s #1 mobile operator with over 430 million subscribers, after disrupting the market with ultra-affordable 4G data and now rolling out 5G services【5】. **Reliance Retail** is India’s largest retailer by revenue and footprint, operating supermarkets, electronics stores, fashion outlets, and e-commerce platforms【5】. These consumer businesses – telecom and retail – have scaled rapidly and now account for nearly half of RIL’s EBITDA, reducing dependence on oil earnings【1】【2】. Additionally, RIL has interests in **media and digital services** (through Network18 and Jio Platforms) and is investing in **new energy** initiatives such as solar panel manufacturing, green hydrogen, and energy storage to drive future growth【1】.\\n\\n**Financial Performance:** Reliance has delivered strong financial performance with a trend of rising revenues and stable profits driven by its diversification. In the fiscal year 2022–23, RIL reported consolidated revenue of roughly ₹8.8 trillion (around $110 billion), a record high supported by robust refining margins, telecom subscriber growth, and retail expansion【2】. Net profit for FY2023 was approximately ₹67,000 