rformance details, including median values and top performers in the zone [3].\n- Specific widgets and metrics frequently surfaced in RM dashboards include: Asset Under Management (AUM), Revenue Under Management (RUM), Customer Composition, Gain/Loss by Number of Customers, Opportunity Summary, and Prospects To Clients. These elements are shown as dashboard widgets with drill-down paths to further detail (L2/L3 views) [1].\n- Additional analytics focus areas include opportunities by product type and sub-product type, AUM by currency, and revenue by product category, each supporting deeper drilling into the data (L2/L3 views) [5], [4].\n- Risk-management analytics appear as alerting mechanisms linked to risk profile events (e.g., risk profile expiry/change, risk-related product vs customer risk checks) and are part of the broader maintenance/alert framework described in governance materials [6].\n\n### KPIs and dashboards (examples)\n- Asset Under Management (AUM): RM dashboard widgets display AUM by customer and by currency in various views [1], [5].\n- Revenue Under Management (RUM): Monthly, by product category (e.g., MF, fixed income, PMS, etc.), for the current year, as captured in RUM widgets [4].\n- Customer Composition: Breakdown by risk profile and by sub-product type, with drill-down options to see customer-level details [1], [13].\n- Gain/Loss by Number of Customers: A metric showing wealth gain/loss across the RM’s customer base, with per-metric drill-downs [3].\n- Opportunity Summary and Prospects-to-Clients: Pipeline-like views showing potential conversions and client conversion flow [4].\n- Peer Benchmarking: Relative performance against peers with hover-enabled details for metrics such as AUM and engagement indicators [3].\n- Sub-Product and Currency Views: Opportunity by Sub Product Type and AUM by Currency, enabling RM to target gaps and currency-specific holdings [5].\n- Risk-Profile Based Alerts: Alerts around risk-profile expiry, changes, and product-versus-customer risk gaps, as part of risk governance and RM supervision [6].\n\n### Data sources commonly referenced by analytics\n- Asset and portfolio data: AUM, investment holdings, and per-product revenue signals (e.g., MF, PMS, fixed income). Widgets explicitly show AUM, revenue by category, and product-level opportunities [1], [4], [5].\n- Customer-level attributes and risk data: Customer risk profiles and risk-profile-based compositions are surfaced in dashboard widgets for composition analyses [1], [5].\n- Interaction/pipeline data: Prospects to clients and opportunity summaries reflect engagement and conversion metrics derived from customer interactions and product opportunities [4].\n\n### Time horizons (typical granularity)\n- Revenue Under Management is presented month-by-month for the current year as a primary time dimension in the RM dashboard [4].\n- Other dashboards support multi-period drill-down (L2/L3 layers) to explore historical or current-period data depending on the widget, with hover or detail views that reveal time-bucket breakdowns where available [1], [3], [5].\n\n### Access roles and consumption\n- The RM dashboard and its components are RM-facing, providing a personal, mapped-customer view and peer benchmarks (e.g., My Space and RM Dashboard concepts appear as RM-centric interfaces in governance documents) [2].\n- The governance materials describe an alert-driven, supervisor-enabled framework that feeds risk-related deviations and ensures oversight, indicating role-based visibility for managers and risk/compliance reviewers in practice [6].\n\n### Export formats and configurability\n- Export formats (CSV, PDF) are not explicitly documented in the captured materials; the primary emphasis is on interactive dashboards with drill-down and hover-based detail, suggesting interactive consumption rather than fixed exports in the described sources [1], [4], [5].\n- Metrics show configurability in practice via interactive UI elements (drill-downs to L2/L3, hover details, and dynamic dashboards) and via alert-rule governance (risk-profile alerts and product-vs-risk checks), indicating at least some degree of configurability for what is measured and when alerts trigger [1], [3], [6].\n\n### Example governance and maintenance context (relevant to RM analytics)\n- Maintenance and alerting rules cover risk-profile expiry/change, product risk vs. customer risk alignment, and other RM-related alerts, illustrating how analytics are governed and what events can drive RM-focused reporting [6].\n\n### References (documents)\n- JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf [1]\n- HSBC_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf [2]\n- JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf [3]\n- JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf [4]\n- HSBC_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf [5]\n- WQ_Journey of Defining Maintenances_HSBC_V10_CCV10.pdf [6]\n\nSources\n- JioBlackRock_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- HSBC_Journey of Self Assessment and Supervisor Assessment - RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- IIFL_Journey of Self-Assessment and Supervisor Assessment-RM Dashboard_CCV13.pdf\n- WQ_Journey of Defining Maintenances_HSBC_V10_CCV10.pdf\n- SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement-G26-G32-G35-Product Selection.pdf\n- SAAB-Journey of Self_Assessment and Supervisor Assessment_RM Dashboard_V10_CCV10docx.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Portfolio Performance Report","RM","MIS Report","Customer Dashboard","Risk Profile Deviation alert","Annexure","View Performance Graph","Order Book Report","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Product Cart"],"seed_node_ids":["report:mis_report","datastore:product_car