**Investor Profile Data:** Key client information such as age, current financial assets, risk tolerance (risk profile score), and KYC status. The investor’s risk profile is derived from a questionnaire and mapped to a risk rating; this must be on record for the planning tool to make suitable recommendations【2】. (If no valid risk profile exists or if it’s expired, the system will prompt for an update and restrict plan creation until done【8】.) KYC must be completed (`KYC Registered` status) for any investment activity【8】.\\n- **Retirement Goal Details:** Attributes of the retirement goal itself – goal type (marked as `Retirement`), target retirement date or age, and target corpus (the amount the investor aims to accumulate). The data model will include a Goal entity linked to the investor’s portfolio, identified as a retirement goal【3】. The goal record holds the target amount, time horizon, and any assumptions (e.g. expected rate of return, inflation rate) used for projections.\\n- **Investment Product Data:** Details of investment products available for the plan. This comes from the product master (funds, securities) and includes each product’s name, asset class, risk rating, historical returns, and transactional rules. The system will utilize flags such as “Plan Type” or tags to identify products suitable for retirement planning (for example, certain mutual funds might be tagged for `Retirement Planning` use)【9】. Product data also provides constraints like minimum/maximum investment amounts for SIP or lump sum, allowed transaction types (purchase, switch, etc.), and cutoff times【8】.\\n- **Account & Folio Information:** Details of the investment account or folio where retirement plan investments will be held. If the retirement plan requires a new folio (for mutual fund investments), the system will gather nominee details as part of account setup. Nomination status is stored at the folio level (e.g., Nomination Available, Opted-Out) and must be updated per new regulations【5】. For instance, if a client chooses not to assign a nominee, an “opt-out” flag is recorded along with the requisite declaration form【5】.\\n- **Transactional Records:** The platform will maintain records of all orders and contributions made toward the retirement goal. This includes pending orders, executed trades, settlement details, and periodic SIP schedules. These records tie into existing order management data stores, allowing audit and reporting on all goal-related transactions.\\n\\n## Regulatory & Compliance Considerations\\nThe retirement planning process will adhere to all applicable regulations in wealth management. Key compliance requirements include:\\n- **KYC and Suitability:** The investor must have completed KYC verification and risk profiling before initiating the retirement plan. The system will enforce this by blocking transactions for customers who are not KYC-verified or who have no current risk profile on file【8】. Suitability checks are integrated: the chosen investment products’ risk ratings are automatically compared to the client’s risk profile. If a client selects a product that exceeds their approved risk level, the platform will issue a warning or disallow the investment without additional approval【8】.\\n- **Nominee Declaration:** When opening any new investment account (folio) as part of the retirement plan, the system must capture either nominee details or an explicit opt-out confirmation from the client, in line with regulatory mandates (e.g., recent directives requiring nomination or opt-out for new folios)【5】. If the client opts not to nominate, they must tick a declaration (and/or sign a form) confirming their choice【5】. The application logs this choice and prevents order submission if the nomination requirement is not satisfied (ensuring compliance with the latest SEBI circulars on nomination).\\n- **Disclosure and Advisory Standards:** The retirement planning tool will include appropriate disclaimers that projections are estimates and not guarantees of future performance. Any advice or recommendations provided (such as suggested investment amounts or products) will comply with financial advisory regulations. In practice, this means the platform presents calculations and options objectively, and RMs using the tool should be certified for investment advice. Only licensed RMs/advisors will be able to officially present or modify plans for clients【12】.\\n- **Audit Trail:** Every key action in the retirement planning journey (goal creation, modifications, transactions, etc.) is logged for compliance audit purposes. This includes maintaining records of any warnings overridden (e.g., if an RM proceeds with a higher-risk product after client consent) and storing copies of any client declarations (such as the nomination opt-out form) in the system. These audit logs ensure that the bank can demonstrate compliance with suitability and documentation requirements if reviewed by regulators.\\n\\n## Integration Points\\n- **CRM (Client Relationship Management):** The retirement planning module will integrate with the CRM system to pull in client profile details, including the risk profile questionnaire results and asset allocation models. The risk profiling and risk appetite mapping are maintained in CRM; for example, the risk score-to-profile mapping and model portfolios by risk level are defined in CRM and imported into our platform【2】. As a prerequisite, the client’s risk profiling should be completed in CRM so that the recommended asset allocation for retirement can be fetched. Updates to a client’s profile (like a changed risk score or life event) in CRM should flow into the planning tool to adjust recommendations accordingly.\\n- **Custodian / RTA Systems:** All investment transactions (mutual fund orders, etc.) generated by the retirement plan will integrate with external custodian or Registrar & Transfer Agent (RTA) systems. For instance, when the client sets up a mutual fund SIP or a one-time