55,0.0066180285,0.012149608,0.03198507,-0.0487226,-0.021493072,-0.0013673741,0.014353548,-0.023355557,-0.0118143605,0.023256224,-0.01290081,0.0132857235,0.020214166,0.0033121186,-0.0067918603,0.0068291104,-0.008933718,0.0035604497,0.020139666,-0.013993468,-0.006167928,0.0045289416,-0.014154883,0.010740328,-0.0054850173,-0.007151941,0.03953434,-0.060791496,0.0025609164,-0.004885918,-0.0018904218,-0.024423381,0.0180661,0.025342207,0.024050884,0.0075244377,0.00037385497,0.008542596,0.005745765,0.010324373,0.025702288,-0.031637404,-0.045990955,-0.0182151,0.019742336,-0.0026788737,0.014328715,0.009194465,0.032208566,-0.054831546,-0.008176307,0.023045143,0.0069532758,0.0005622375,-0.012298606,0.024783462,-0.026496949,0.025093876,-0.013968634,0.008964759,-0.024795879,-0.028011769,0.033400558,0.00068523915,-0.010287124,-0.018128183,0.04571779,0.015433789,-0.006928443,0.03675303,-0.047058776,0.0037001362,0.02547879,-0.0077851857,-0.007822435,-0.0035666581,-0.0134471385,-0.019394673,0.025019377,-0.004134716,0.011733653,-0.009573171,-0.055874538,-0.026919112,0.016017368,0.031860903,-0.003678407,-0.025925785,-0.010038792,-0.0041440283,-0.006475238,0.04216665,-0.010094667,-0.006779444,-0.019220842,-0.0006685544,0.024274383,-0.0026043744,-0.0030079125,-0.020263832,-0.008399806,-0.004997667,-0.010653412,-1.9558514e-05,-0.022896145]	deep	Immediately after a user verifies their email, the application secures access through several layered steps:\n\n### 1. Credential Setup (Password / MPIN)\nRight after email verification (via OTP or verification link), the user is prompted to create their primary login credential, such as:\n- A strong password, or  \n- A 6‑digit MPIN (mobile PIN).\n\nThis establishes a **knowledge factor** (something only the user knows) for all future logins.\n\n### 2. Multi‑Factor Authentication (MFA)\nThe application then enforces MFA for ongoing access:\n\n- During onboarding, the user’s email (and often mobile number) is verified via OTP.\n- For subsequent logins, the user must provide:\n  - Their password/MPIN **plus**\n  - A second factor, such as an OTP via SMS/email or an app-generated token.\n\nThis ensures that knowing the password alone is not enough to access the account, aligning with financial‑sector security and compliance requirements.\n\n### 3. Device & Biometric Security\nAfter setting credentials, the app may offer device-based security:\n\n- Prompt to enable **Touch ID / Face ID** or similar biometrics on that device.\n- Optionally mark the device as **trusted**.\n- Logins from new or unrecognized devices can trigger extra verification (e.g., OTP challenge).\n\nThis adds a **biometric factor** (something the user is) and restricts access from unknown devices.\n\n### 4. Secure Session Establishment\nOnce authentication succeeds:\n\n- A secure, authenticated **session** is created (session ID/token).\n- All traffic is forced over **HTTPS** to encrypt data in transit.\n- **Session timeouts** log the user out after inactivity to reduce the risk of session hijacking.\n- The app may display last login time or recent failed attempts so users can spot suspicious activity.\n\n### 5. Entitlements & Access Control\nImmediately after the session is established:\n\n- **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)** determines what the user can see and do.\n- The system loads only the menus, data, and functions allowed for that user’s role (e.g., client vs. advisor vs. admin).\n- This prevents even authenticated users from accessing unauthorized features or data.\n\n### 6. Compliance & Security Controls\nThroughout this process, the platform applies standard security and compliance practices:\n\n- Passwords/MPINs are stored securely (hashed, not in plain text).\n- All authentication events are **logged** for audit.\n- Repeated failed login attempts trigger **account lockout** to prevent brute‑force attacks.\n- Use of MFA and encryption supports regulatory and internal security requirements.\n\nTogether, these measures ensure that immediately after email verification, the user’s access is protected by strong credentials, MFA, secure sessions, role-based permissions, and device/biometric safeguards.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Explain how the application ensures a user’s account is secured immediately after the user verifies their email address.",\n  "expanded_question": "What is the secure access process right after a user completes email verification in the wealth management app? Specifically, describe the next authentication steps (credentials setup and MFA), how a session is established, how user permissions are enforced, any device-specific security measures (like biometrics or trusted devices), and what compliance controls ensure the account remains secure at this stage.",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Email Verification",\n    "Authentication Credentials",\n    "Multi-Factor Authentication (2FA)",\n    "Session Management",\n    "Access Control (Entitlements)",\n    "Device/Biometric Security",\n    "Compliance Standards"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    { "id": "1", "source": "Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V11.pdf" },\n    { "id": "2", "source": "HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10.pdf" },\n    { "id": "3", "source": "BOC Philippines Tech - Trust systems.pdf" },\n    { "id": "4", "source": "Banque Misr Tech response - Custody.pdf" }\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Immediate Post-Email Verification Security Steps:** After a user verifies their email (usually by entering an OTP or clicking a verification link), the application immediately prompts them to secure their account with strong authentication. The user is typically asked to set up a personal login credential, such as creating a secure password or a 6-digit MPIN (mobile PIN) for the account ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Internal%20to%20Jio%20BlackRock%20and,Intellect%20Page%208)). This step establishes a **knowledge factor** (something only the user knows) to protect future logins. \\n\\n- **Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):** The platform enforces multi-factor authentication for account access. Email verification itself is one factor of identity proof (since the user had to input a one-time password sent to their email) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=user%20level%2C%202FA%20can%20be,SAML%29%205)). Often a mobile number is verified with an OTP as well during onboarding, adding a second factor. Going forward, logging in will require the user’s password/MPIN **plus** an additional factor (for example, a one-time code sent via SMS or email, or an app-generated token) ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=to%20SMS%2FEmail,for%20transaction%20authorization%2Fworkflow%20approval%20in)). This two-factor authentication is mandatory in financial applications to meet security compliance – it ensures that just knowing the password is not enough to access the account ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)). \\n\\n- **Device & Biometric Security:** As an added layer, the user may enable device-based authentication after email verification. For instance, upon setting their MPIN/password, the app can prompt the user to **enable Touch ID or Face ID** login on that device ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Internal%20to%20Jio%20BlackRock%20and,Intellect%20Page%208)). Enabling biometrics ties the account to the user’s physical device (something the user *is*), allowing convenient yet secure logins. The current device can be marked as trusted once this is set up, whereas any login from a new or unrecognized device will trigger additional verification (such as requiring a fresh OTP) to ensure it’s really the user. This device-aware approach prevents unauthorized devices from accessing the account. \\n\\n- **Secure Session Establishment:** After the user’s credentials (and any second factor) are verified, the system establishes a secure authenticated session. The application generates a session token or ID and **all communication is forced over HTTPS** to protect data in transit ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=into%20the%20application%20through%20Finger,BlackRock%20and%20Intellect%20Page%209)). The session is encrypted and bound to the user’s identity, typically with secure cookies or tokens. For safety, the platform applies session timeout policies – if the user stays inactive beyond a set duration, the session will automatically expire and log out the user, preventing others from hijacking an idle session ([file-LjaRghvPuPPa72CNQ14YLR](file://file-LjaRghvPuPPa72CNQ14YLR#:~:text=n%20Logs,of%20inactivity%20to%20maintain%20security)). At login, the system may also display the time of the last successful login or any recent failed attempts as a security reminder to the user (ensuring they notice any unauthorized access attempts). \\n\\n- **Entitlements & Access Control:** Once logged in, the user’s access is governed by role-based entitlements. The application checks the user’s profile/role to determine what features and data they are allowed to see or use. **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)** is enforced so that the user only sees the menus and functions appropriate to their role and permissions ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Button%20on%20the%20Home%20page,and%20click%20on%20the%20%E2%80%9CSend)) ([file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA](file://file-NTqgvymrT13MkJcouJvinA#:~:text=ARX%20provides%20Role%20Based%20access,in%20the%20system%20with%20their)). For example, a client user will only have access to their own portfolio and related services, and not any administrative or advisor functions. This entitlement check happens immediately upon session setup to tailor the dashboard and disable any unauthorized options. By limiting functionality to authorized areas, the platform ensures that even a logged-in user cannot stray into areas beyond their scope. \\n\\n- **Compliance and Security Measures:** The post-email-verification login process adheres to stringent compliance standards for financial data. Regulatory policies require measures like MFA for user login and encryption of sensitive information, which the system follows. The user’s newly created password/MPIN is stored securely (hashed and never in plain text) in compliance with security guidelines ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=Need%20to%20enter%20the%20email,Yes%20Not%20Applicable%20Set%20MPIN)). All authentication actions are logged for audit, and excessively incorrect login attempts result in account lockout to thwart brute-force attacks ([file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y](file://file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y#:~:text=The%20system%20must%20enforce%20account,Authentication)) ([file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y](file://file-93kgYoVBBBDvyNyG4v5p6y#:~:text=Use%20multi,Authentication)). The combination of something the user knows (password/MPIN), something they have (OTP code or trusted device), and something they are (biometric ID) — all handled through encrypted channels — provides **defense in depth**. These controls ensure that immediately after verifying their email, the user’s access to the application is protected by multiple layers of security and aligned with industry compliance requirements ([file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK](file://file-TfnyrsbsfjPfzA31DCnMLK#:~:text=Mailing%20Address%201%20Place%20of,String%20No%20Not%20Applicable%202)) ([file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN](file://file-GpCdS4N71LyZyEqDwJFhLN#:~:text=into%20the%20application%20through%20Finger,BlackRock%20and%20Intellect%20Page%209)). \\n\\n**Sources:**\\n1. Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V