sibility and reconciliation, as STAR represents the gateway to the exchange/clearing ecosystem and its generated reference is used in subsequent trade lifecycle events [2].\n- The OMS-to-STAR routing is followed by STAR delivering execution results to the RTA feed pipeline, which then becomes the primary conduit for clearing and settlement data via RTA data feeds. The bridge between the wealth order and the RTA transaction is the User Transaction Number; the same value is carried from outbound (wealth order) to inbound (RTA transaction) files (and the corresponding inbound/outbound references like USRTRXNO or inward numbers) to maintain end-to-end traceability of the order through its lifecycle [1].\n  - Inbound and outbound RTA files use the User Transaction Number as the connector, enabling the OMS to correlate STAR-executed trades with RTA-reported trades (and ultimately with the wealth order) for status updates and settlements [1].\n\nData exchanges and data mapping\n- RTA data feeds provide the authoritative linkage for order lifecycle events (Authorized, Contracted, Settled, Reversed) and reconciliations. Reconciliation can involve three types of processes (Transactions, AUM, Trail Fee), with a defined three-step approach (define rule, threshold, and matching) to resolve discrepancies between internal records and RTA statements [1].\n- Key identifiers used across the flow include:\n  - User Transaction Number: connector between wealth orders and RTA transactions, carried in outbound and inbound RTA files [1].\n  - External Order Number: generated by BSE STAR and associated with the externally routed order; this identifier is carried in STAR’s communications and is visible to stakeholders when tracking the trade [2].\n  - Payment references (paymentrefno): included in the model/order records and visible in the STAR/RTA flow (as part of the model/order details) to support payment reconciliation and traceability [2].\n- Data mapping artifacts referenced in the flow include the linkage between STAR’s external identifiers and RTA data, enabling consistent traceability from order capture to settlement. The presence of payment reference fields in the STAR/Order flow is demonstrated in the external-order flow views, illustrating how payment references are surfaced as part of order-level data [2].\n\nConfirmation generation and delivery\n- Post-execution, confirmations flow back through the system, with notifications generated upon settlement and rejection events. The end-to-end confirmation and notification lifecycle is described in practice journeys where settlement-related emails/SMS are sent to customers when trades settle or when orders are rejected, indicating that confirmations are delivered via system-generated messages to the customer’s registered channels [3].\n- The settlement step in the flow updates customer holdings and order statuses (from Contracted to Settled) after receiving the trade file from the RTA. This confirms that the actual trade has settled and the associated holdings need to reflect the new state [3].\n- For partial confirmations (where only a portion of the RTA-confirmed quantity is matched), the system can modify the existing wealth order (Modified Order) or generate a new order (New Order) with the residual amount/units and appropriate status (Contracted or Rejected). This mechanism ensures the customer and the book reflect partial confirmations accurately; the reconciliation workflow governs these adjustments [1].\n\nRouting logic and destination mapping\n- The routing model follows a pattern where the wealth OMS delegates execution to STAR; STAR’s response (including external order number and trade status) is then reconciled against RTA-provided results. The external order number acts as the durable reference across OMS, STAR, and RTA for tracking and reconciliation, while the User Transaction Number ensures linkage back to the internal wealth order and its origins [2][1].\n- The Order Book and related transaction records are updated based on reconciliation outcomes, with statuses progressing through Authorized → Contracted → Settled, and appropriate handling for reversals or partial confirmations per documented flows [1].\n\nConfirmation delivery and user notification\n- Settlement communications (emails/SMS) are part of the customer-facing confirmations, with templates and notice timing tied to settlement events. Email matrices show that settlement notices are sent at settlement, while rejections trigger separate communications; these are generated by the system as part of the post-settlement or post-rejection workflow [3].\n- The actual confirmations delivered to customers reflect the outcome of the settlement process, including the transaction details, order identifiers, and the settlement date, ensuring customers have timely and verifiable trade confirmations [3].\n\nReconciliation, exceptions, and compliance considerations\n- Reconciliation is a structured process that ensures internal records (OMS, holdings, transaction master) align with RTA statements. The process includes rule-definition, threshold-setting, and matching of records, with multiple reconciliation outcomes (e.g., fully matched, differential matched, accepted, or manual adjustment) that drive subsequent order-status updates [1].\n- Partial confirmation scenarios are explicitly handled via reconciliation, allowing manual acceptance to adjust an existing order or create a new one to reflect RTA-provided quantities. This mechanism preserves accurate position and P&L integrity while aligning the system state with market reality [9].\n- Legal/regulatory and audit considerations are embedded in the reconciliation and settlement processes, ensuring traceability of actions, proper status changes, and accurate delivery of confirmations to investors; the lifecycle is designed to support auditability and regulatory reporting needs (e.g., settlement timing, partial confirmations, and reversal hand