 Price Master [1]. In practice, this appears as a screen titled View Performance Graph – Max Drawdown [1], and is referenced across multiple journeys as the mechanism to display drawdown information [2].\n- Backtesting contexts also reference drawdown in conjunction with performance projection and max drawdown calculations, with annexures documenting the calculation methodology and sample calculations (e.g., Backtesting, Performance Projection and Max Drawdown) [3], [4], [5].\n\nWhere drawdown appears and data inputs\n- Where it appears: Max Drawdown appears on the View Performance Graph screen as a dedicated graph (View Performance Graph – Max Drawdown) [1], [2].\n- Data inputs: The calculation is grounded in prices from the Security Price Master, i.e., drawdown is plotted based on these prices [1].\n\nEnablement, configuration, and limitations\n- Enablement/configuration: Documentation references annexures that describe how drawdown is calculated and present sample calculations (Backtesting, Performance Projection, and Max Drawdown). This indicates the capability is embedded in the standard performance graph tooling and is documented via annexures rather than a separate toggle [3], [5].\n- Limitations: The available excerpts do not explicitly enumerate operational limitations or step-by-step enablement instructions beyond the existence of the Max Drawdown graph and annexure calculations; explicit export options are not described in the cited materials [5].\n\nRelation to backtesting and related concepts\n- Backtesting functionality is described as part of the performance view, with references to backtesting displays and calculations, and annexures detailing how backtesting and max drawdown are computed [3], [4], [5].\n\nNotes on related domains\n- Drawdown concepts feature in other contexts (e.g., trade capture and risk-related accounting) as part of the broader investment workflow, illustrating that drawdown-related calculations are part of the instrumented risk 