 progress and review the plan over time.\n\nScope includes:\n\n- Goal-based planning with “Retirement” as a distinct goal type.\n- Support for accumulation (pre‑retirement) and decumulation (post‑retirement withdrawals).\n- Integration with client profile, risk profiling, product catalog, and order execution.\n- Compliance with KYC and suitability requirements (e.g., SEBI‑style norms).\n- Advisor‑led and optional self‑service client journeys.\n\nOut of scope (for now):\n\n- Detailed tax optimization engine.\n- Complex estate planning.\n- Cross‑jurisdiction regulatory variations beyond baseline suitability/KYC.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Stakeholders\n\n- **Clients (Investors)**  \n  Provide personal and financial data, define retirement objectives, review and accept plans, and monitor progress.\n\n- **Advisors / Relationship Managers (RMs)**  \n  Gather client information, create and adjust retirement plans, explain projections, and initiate investments.\n\n- **Supervisors / Compliance Officers**  \n  Review and approve plans (maker‑checker), ensure suitability and policy adherence, and support audits.\n\n- **Operations & IT Teams**  \n  Maintain integrations (CRM, product master, pricing, order systems), ensure data quality, performance, security, and reporting.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Core Business Entities\n\n- **Client** (investor, with KYC and risk profile)\n- **Advisor / RM**\n- **Retirement Goal**\n- **Risk Profile**\n- **Model Portfolio / Strategy**\n- **Investment Order / SIP / SWP**\n- **Account / Portfolio** (investment accounts linked to goals)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Client Profile & Data Model Requirements\n\nThe module must use a comprehensive client data model, including:\n\n### 4.1 Client Demographics\n\n- Name, DOB, gender, residency.\n- Current age (derived from DOB).\n- Target retirement age or date.\n- Life expectancy assumption (or planning horizon after retirement).\n\n### 4.2 Financial Profile\n\n- Income (current and expected growth if available).\n- Existing assets (cash, investments, retirement accounts, pensions).\n- Liabilities (loans, obligations).\n- Existing retirement‑specific savings (PF, pension, etc.).\n- Regular savings capacity (max affordable monthly/annual contribution).\n\n### 4.3 Family & Dependents\n\n- Marital status.\n- Number and age of dependents.\n- Any expected financial responsibilities (education, healthcare).\n\n### 4.4 Risk Profile\n\n- Risk assessment questionnaire and score.\n- Risk category (e.g., Conservative, Moderate, Aggressive).\n- Date of last assessment and validity.\n- Business rule: **No plan implementation** if risk profile is missing or expired.\n\n### 4.5 KYC & Regulatory\n\n- KYC status (e.g., Not Done / Pending / Verified).\n- Regulatory flags (e.g., high‑risk client, PEP, etc., if applicable).\n- Business rule: **No investment orders** if KYC is not verified.\n\n### 4.6 Data Validation\n\n- Retirement age > current age.\n- Life expectancy > retirement age.\n- Amounts ≥ 0 and within configured limits.\n- Mandatory fields enforced before plan generation.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Retirement Goal Definition\n\nThe module must provide a **Goal Definition** interface for retirement with:\n\n### 5.1 Goal Parameters\n\n- Goal name (default: “Retirement” but editable).\n- Goal type: **Retirement** (for reporting and filtering).\n- Target retirement age or date.\n- Target retirement **income** (per month/year) and/or **corpus**.\n- Current retirement savings (amount and instruments).\n- Time horizon:\n  - Years to retirement.\n  - Years in retirement (planning horizon).\n\n### 5.2 Assumptions\n\n- Pre‑retirement inflation rate.\n- Post‑retirement inflation rate (optional if different).\n- Expected return by asset class or blended portfolio return.\n- Default assumptions configurable at system level; advisor can override with justification.\n\n### 5.3 Contribution Constraints\n\n- Maximum affordable monthly/annual contribution.\n- Existing SIPs that can be mapped to this goal.\n- Preference for lump‑sum vs. SIP vs. combination.\n\n### 5.4 Goal–Portfolio Linkage\n\n- Each retirement goal must be linked to:\n  - Client.\n  - One or more investment accounts/portfolios.\n- All investments created from the plan must be tagged to the retirement goal for:\n  - Reporting.\n  - Progress tracking.\n  - Goal‑level performance.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Financial Projections & Calculations\n\nThe module must support:\n\n### 6.1 Required Contribution Calculation\n\n- Given:\n  - Target corpus or income.\n  - Time to retirement.\n  - Expected return and inflation.\n  - Current savings.\n- Calculate:\n  - Required monthly/annual contribution.\n  - Or, given a fixed contribution, calculate projected corpus and shortfall/surplus.\n\nSupport:\n\n- SIP‑style accumulation calculator.\n- Lump‑sum growth calculator.\n- Combination of lump‑sum + periodic contributions.\n\n### 6.2 Asset Allocation Strategy\n\n- Determine recommended asset allocation based on:\n  - Risk profile.\n  - Time horizon.\n  - Goal type = Retirement.\n- Use:\n  - Predefined **model portfolios** (e.g., “Retirement – Moderate 20+ years”, “Retirement – Conservative <5 years”), or\n  - Rules‑based allocation engine.\n- Ensure:\n  - Total allocation = 100%.\n  - Allocation respects risk category thresholds.\n\n### 6.3 Growth Projection (Accumulation Phase)\n\n- Project portfolio value from now until retirement:\n  - Year‑by‑year (or configurable period).\n  - Show:\n    - Contributions.\n    - Investment growth.\n    - Total corpus at retirement.\n- Display:\n  - Graph of projected corpus over time.\n  - Breakdown: total contributions vs. investment returns.\n\n### 6.4 Withdrawal / Decumulation Phase\n\n- Support **Systematic Withdrawal Plan (SWP)** modeling:\n  - Given corpus at retirement, expected return, and desired monthly/annual withdrawal:\n    - Estimate how long corpus will last.\n  - Or given desired duration:\n    - Estimate required corpus or sustainable withdrawal amount.\n- Project portfolio value during retirement:\n  - Show depletion trajectory and risk of shortfall.\n\n### 6.5 Scenario Modeling\n\n- Allow multiple scenarios per goal:\n  - Baseline, Optimistic, Pessimistic.\n- Adjustable parameters per scenario:\n  - Return assumptions.\n  - Inflation.\n  - Contribution amount.\n  - Retirement age.\n- Show side‑by‑side comparison:\n  - Projected corpus.\n  - Probability of shortfall (if supported).\n  - Shortfall/surplus amounts.\n\n### 6.6 Risk & Performance Metrics\n\n- For each plan/scenario, show:\n  - Expected annualized return.\n  - Projected shortfall/surplus vs. target.\n  - Simple risk indicators (e.g., volatility band, best/worst case projections).\n- Optional: highlight historical drawdown or risk rating of recommended portfolio.\n\n---\n\n## 7. User Interface & Experience\n\n### 7.1 Entry Point\n\n- From client dashboard:\n  - “Goals” section with option to **Create Retirement Plan**.\n- If KYC or risk profile is missing/expired:\n  - Prompt user to complete before proceeding.\n  - Hard stop on implementation until resolved.\n\n### 7.2 Goal Definition Screen\n\n- Form‑based UI capturing:\n  - Goal parameters (name, type, target age/date, corpus/income).\n  - Current savings.\n  - Assumptions (inflation, returns).\n  - Contribution constraints.\n- Features:\n  - Inline validations and error messages.\n  - Default values for assumptions with ability to override.\n  - Save as **Draft**.\n\n### 7.3 Planning Results & Scenario Screen\n\n- After saving goal:\n  - Display:\n    - Required contribution (monthly/annual).\n    - Projected corpus at retirement.\n    - Shortfall/surplus vs. target.\n  - Charts:\n    - Corpus over time (accumulation and optional decumulation).\n    - Contribution vs. growth breakdown.\n    - Scenario comparison (baseline/optimistic/pessimistic).\n- Allow:\n  - On‑the‑fly adjustment of assumptions with instant recalculation.\n  - Saving multiple scenarios.\n\n### 7.4 Product Recommendation & Allocation Screen\n\n- Show recommended portfolio:\n  - Asset classes and weights.\n  - Underlying products (funds, schemes, etc.) with:\n    - Risk rating.\n    - Category.\n    - Minimum investment.\n- Indicate:\n  - Strategy name (e.g., “Retirement – Moderate”).\n  - Alignment with client risk profile.\n- Allow:\n  - Limited advisor overrides within risk constraints.\n  - Clear warnings if overrides increase risk.\n\n### 7.5 Workflow & Approval Screens\n\n- Advisor view:\n  - Plan status (Draft / Pending Approval / Approved / Active / Closed).\n  - Button to **Submit for Approval**.\n- Supervisor view:\n  - Queue of plans pending approval.\n  - Detailed view of:\n    - Client profile & risk.\n    - Goal details.\n    - Recommended allocation and products.\n    - Compliance flags/warnings.\n  - Actions:\n    - Approve.\n    - Reject with comments.\n    - Request modification.\n\n### 7.6 Client Presentation & Dashboard\n\n- **Retirement Plan Report** (on‑screen and PDF):\n  - Goal summary.\n  - Assumptions.\n  - Contribution schedule.\n  - Asset allocation.\n  - Projections and charts.\n  - Disclaimers and branding.\n- Client dashboard:\n  - Goal summary widget:\n    - Target amount.\n    - Current value.\n    - % of goal achieved.\n  - Goal detail view:\n    - Linked holdings.\n    - Performance vs. plan.\n    - Updated projections.\n\n### 7.7 Order Placement Integration\n\n- From approved plan:\n  - “Implement Plan” / “Invest Now” button.\n- Pre‑populate order cart with:\n  - Selected products.\n  - Amounts or SIP details.\n  - Client account details.\n- Follow standard order journey:\n  - Confirm details.\n  - Payment selection.\n  - Submission.\n- Tag all orders to the retirement goal.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Data Flow & Integrations\n\n### 8.1 Upstream Data\n\n- **CRM / Client Master**:\n  - Client demographics, KYC status, risk profile.\n- **Account Master**:\n  - Investment and bank accounts.\n- **Product Master**:\n  - Funds/securities, categories, risk ratings, minimums.\n- **Market Data / Pricing**:\n  - NAVs and prices for projections and order creation.\n\n### 8.2 Downstream & Lateral Integrations\n\n- **Order Management / Execution Systems**:\n  - Mutual fund gateways, exchanges, RTAs, payment gateways.\n  - Receive orders (lump‑sum, SIP, SWP) from plan.\n  - Send back status and confirmations.\n- **Analytics / Risk Engines** (optional):\n  - Advanced simulations (e.g., Monte Carlo).\n- **Reporting / Data Warehouse**:\n  - Store plan data, projections, and performance for BI and compliance.\n\n### 8.3 Data Flow Highlights\n\n- Plan creation:\n  - Pull client & product data → compute projections → store plan & assumptions.\n- Plan implementation:\n  - Push orders to execution system → receive confirmations → update holdings and goal progress.\n- Ongoing:\n  - Periodic refresh of valuations and projections using latest prices.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Compliance & Control Requirements\n\n### 9.1 KYC & Eligibility\n\n- No investment orders allowed if:\n  - KYC not completed/verified.\n- UI must clearly indicate KYC status and block implementation if non‑compliant.\n\n### 9.2 Suitability & Risk Alignment\n\n- Enforce:\n  - Recommended products’ risk rating must not exceed client’s risk profile (configurable as hard or soft rule).\n  - Investment horizon of products must be compatible with goal horizon (e.g., avoid long lock‑in products for short‑term goals).\n- If advisor selects higher‑risk products:\n  - Prominent warning.\n  - Optionally require supervisor override/approval.\n\n### 9.3 Risk Profiling\n\n- Risk profile must:\n  - Exist.\n  - Be within validity period.\n- If missing/expired:\n  - Block new investments from the plan until re‑profiling is completed and approved.\n\n### 9.4 Maker–Checker (Approval Workflow)\n\n- All retirement plans:\n  - Created by advisor (maker).\n  - Approved by supervisor (checker) before implementation.\n- Configurable:\n  - Which roles can approve.\n  - Thresholds for additional approvals (e.g., high AUM).\n\n### 9.5 Audit Trail\n\n- Log all key events:\n  - Plan creation, edits, scenario changes.\n  - Assumption changes.\n  - Approvals/rejections (with user, timestamp, comments).\n  - Order creation and execution.\n- Logs must be:\n  - Tamper‑evident.\n  - Searchable for audits.\n\n### 9.6 Client Communication & Disclaimers\n\n- All client‑facing outputs (reports, screens) must include:\n  - Market risk disclaimers.\n  - Statement that projections are estimates, not guarantees.\n  - Any required regulatory text (e.g., suitability, conflict of interest notes).\n\n---\n\n## 10. Reporting & Dashboards\n\n### 10.1 Retirement Plan Report (Client‑Facing)\n\n- Sections:\n  - Executive summary (goal, target vs. projected).\n  - Client profile snapshot (risk, horizon).\n  - Contribution plan (amounts, frequency).\n  - Asset allocation and product list.\n  - Projection charts and tables (accumulation and, if modeled, decumulation).\n  - Assumptions and disclaimers.\n\n### 10.2 Goal Progress Dashboard\n\n- For each retirement goal:\n  - Target corpus.\n  - Current value of goal‑linked investments.\n  - % of goal achieved.\n  - On‑track / off‑track indicator.\n- Goal‑filtered holdings view:\n  - Show only investments tagged to the retirement goal.\n- Key performance indicators:\n  - Annualized return of goal portfolio.\n  - Updated projected corpus vs. target.\n\n### 10.3 Periodic Review Reports\n\n- At configurable intervals (e.g., annually):\n  - Compare actual vs. original projections.\n  - Highlight deviations and causes (e.g., lower returns, missed contributions).\n  - Suggest remedial actions (e.g., increase contributions, adjust retirement age).\n\n### 10.4 Compliance & Internal Reports\n\n- Portfolio of retirement plans:\n  - Count, status (draft, approved, active).\n  - Risk profile distribution.\n  - Exceptions (e.g., overridden suitability warnings).\n- Suitability documentation:\n  - Ability to export or view plan rationale and risk assessment for each client.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Data Governance, Security & Validation\n\n### 11.1 Validation Rules\n\n- Field‑level:\n  - Numeric ranges, date logic, mandatory fields.\n- Business‑level:\n  - Asset allocation sums to 100%.\n  - No projections without required inputs.\n  - No implementation without KYC and valid risk profile.\n\n### 11.2 Data Consistency & Versioning\n\n- Single source of truth:\n  - Client data from CRM.\n  - Product data from product master.\n- Plan versioning:\n  - Each major change (e.g., assumptions, contributions, retirement age) creates a new version.\n  - Ability to view historical versions and their assumptions.\n\n### 11.3 Security & Privacy\n\n- Role‑based access control:\n  - Advisors see only their assigned clients.\n  - Supervisors see their teams’ clients.\n- Data protection:\n  - Encryption at rest and in transit (as per enterprise standards).\n  - No sensitive data in unsecured logs.\n\n### 11.4 Data Retention\n\n- Retain:\n  - Plan data and related orders for at least the regulatory minimum (e.g., several years after goal closure).\n- Support:\n  - Archival of old plans with read‑only access for audits.\n\n---\n\n## 12. End‑to‑End Workflow\n\n1. **Initiation**\n   - Advisor selects client and opens Retirement Planning.\n   - System checks KYC and risk profile; prompts completion if missing/expired.\n\n2. **Goal Setup**\n   - Advisor enters retirement goal details and assumptions.\n   - System validates inputs and saves plan as **Draft**.\n\n3. **Plan Development**\n   - System calculates required contributions and proposes asset allocation.\n   - Advisor reviews projections, adjusts assumptions/products, and may create multiple scenarios.\n\n4. **Client Discussion & Refinement**\n   - Advisor presents draft plan to client (on‑screen or via draft report).\n   - Based on feedback, advisor refines goal parameters and reruns projections.\n\n5. **Internal Approval**\n   - Advisor submits plan for supervisor approval.\n   - Plan status: **Pending Approval**.\n   - Supervisor reviews, checks suitability/compliance, and:\n     - Approves → status: **Approved**.\n     - Rejects/returns with comments → advisor revises and resubmits.\n\n6. **Client Confirmation**\n   - Advisor presents approved plan to client.\n   - Client formally accepts (e‑consent or documented offline).\n   - Plan status: **Active**.\n\n7. **Execution of Investments**\n   - Advisor triggers “Implement Plan”.\n   - Orders (lump‑sum, SIP, SWP) are created and sent to execution systems.\n   - On confirmation, holdings are updated and tagged to the retirement goal.\n\n8. **Ongoing Monitoring & Review**\n   - Dashboard shows progress and updated projections.\n   - System may generate alerts (off‑track, risk drift, missed contributions).\n   - Periodic reviews may lead to plan revisions (new version, re‑approval if material).\n\n---\n\n## 13. Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe Retirement Planning module will be considered successfully delivered if:\n\n1. **Data Capture**\n   - All required client and goal fields can be captured with correct validations.\n   - Mandatory fields are enforced before plan generation.\n\n2. **Calculation Accuracy**\n   - SIP/lump‑sum and projection calculations match agreed formulas within tolerance.\n   - Scenario changes recalculate outputs correctly and promptly.\n\n3. **Risk & Suitability Controls**\n   - System blocks implementation without valid KYC and risk profile.\n   - Recommended portfolios respect client risk profile and horizon.\n   - Higher‑risk selections trigger clear warnings and, where configured, hard stops.\n\n4. **Workflow Integrity**\n   - Maker–checker flow works end‑to‑end:\n     - Plans route to correct supervisors.\n     - Advisors cannot edit while pending approval.\n     - Status transitions are correct and auditable.\n\n5. **Order Integration**\n   - Orders generated from plans carry correct products, amounts, and account details.\n   - Both lump‑sum and SIP/SWP flows function without errors.\n   - Execution confirmations update goal status and holdings.\n\n6. **UI & Reporting**\n   - All key screens (goal setup, results, allocation, approvals, dashboards) are implemented and usable.\n   - Retirement Plan Report generates correctly with all sections and disclaimers.\n   - Advisors can complete a full journey (from profile to plan to orders) without training beyond basic orientation.\n\n7. **Performance & Security**\n   - Projections for long horizons (e.g., 30+ years) run within acceptable response times.\n   - System supports concurrent advisor usage without material degradation.\n   - Access controls and encryption are in place; no sensitive data exposure in logs.\n\n8. **Compliance & Audit**\n   - UAT test cases for KYC, risk profiling, suitability, and maker–checker all pass.\n   - Audit logs are complete and retrievable for all key actions.\n   - Compliance team signs off that the process meets regulatory and internal policy requirements.\n\n---\n\nThis BRD defines the functional, data, workflow, UI, integration, and compliance requirements for a robust, compliant **Retirement Planning** capability within a wealth management platform.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Provide a comprehensive outline of business requirements for a Retirement Planning module in a wealth management platform.",\n  "expanded_question": "What are the detailed business requirements for adding a Retirement Planning module to our wealth management platform, covering scope, stakeholders, data model (client info, retirement goals), processes (goal setting, risk profiling, contribution planning), data flows, UI screens, compliance controls (KYC, suitability per SEBI), outputs (projections, dashboards), workflow (advisor/client/supervisor steps), integrations (fund data, pricing), and acceptance criteria?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Client (Investor)",\n    "Advisor (Relationship Manager)",\n    "Retirement Goal",\n    "Risk Profile",\n    "Model Portfolio",\n    "Investment Order"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Journey from Order Placement till Settlement – Basket Based Order Trigger (Jio/Intellect)"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Journey of Creating Model Portfolio (SBI)"},\n    {"id": "3", "source": "Journey from Order Placement till Settlement (HSBC)"},\n    {"id": "4", "source": "Journey from Order Placement till Settlement (360One)"},\n    {"id": "5", "source": "Journey from Order Placement till Settlement (SBI)"},\n    {"id": "6", "source": "Model Portfolio/Basket Based Investments (Product Spec)"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "## Scope and Objectives\\nThe **Retirement Planning module** will enable advisors and clients to define retirement goals and formulate a savings and investment plan to achieve them. It covers capturing the client’s financial profile and retirement objectives, computing required contributions, designing an investment strategy, and providing projections up to and through retirement. This module supports multiple goal types (e.g. emergency, education, retirement), with retirement explicitly handled as a distinct goal category ([file-Mnd1bRpJt17LcQfEHEZyXB](file://file-Mnd1bRpJt17LcQfEHEZyXB#:~:text=5%20Goal%20Type%20This%20displays,Wealth)). When a retirement goal is defined, it is linked to the client’s portfolio so the goal’s investments can be tracked and managed in alignment with that purpose ([file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd](file://file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd#:~:text=Basket%20based%20order%20trigger%20%281%29,%E2%97%8F%20Master%20Records)). The solution aims to ensure that the retirement plan is *suitable* for the client’s risk appetite and complies with all regulatory guidelines (e.g. SEBI’s mandates on KYC and investment suitability).\\n\\n## Stakeholders\\n- **Clients (Investors):** End-users whose financial data and retirement objectives are captured. They review the retirement plan and its projections, and benefit from ongoing tracking of goal progress.\\n- **Advisors/Relationship Managers:** Wealth advisors who gather client information, input retirement goals, and use the module to generate and present plans. They initiate any investment orders arising from the plan.\\n- **Supervisors/Compliance Officers:** Oversee and approve proposed plans (maker-checker control) to ensure they meet internal policies and regulatory suitability standards. They have authority to authorize or require changes to the plan before it is finalized  .\\n- **Operations/IT Teams:** Manage data integration (client data, product data) and ensure the module’s outputs (reports, dashboards) are properly generated, stored, and auditable for compliance purposes.\\n\\n## Client Profile & Data Model\\nA comprehensive **client data model** underpins the planning process. The module will utilize existing client profile details including personal demographics (age, current age to infer time to retirement), financial details (income, existing assets, retirement benefits, current investments), liabilities, and family/dependent information. It will also leverage the client’s **KYC status** and **risk profile**. Each client’s risk profile is established via a questionnaire assessing financial situation and risk tolerance ([file-5aRrTupwN6UTT4BNDV7L2r](file://file-5aRrTupwN6UTT4BNDV7L2r#:~:text=navigate%20to%20the%20risk%20profile,Risk%20Profiling)). The risk profile (e.g. Moderate, Aggressive) indicates how much risk the client can take, and is a foundational input to the retirement plan ([file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz](file://file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz#:~:text=Every%20customer%20will%20have%20a,created%20at%20the%20asset%20level)). If a risk profile is not already on record or is outdated, the advisor must complete the risk profiling process before proceeding ([file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J](file://file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J#:~:text=12,is%20greater%20than%20customer%20risk)). This ensures alignment with regulatory suitability requirements – for example, the system will not allow proceeding if the client’s risk assessment is missing or expired ([file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J](file://file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J#:~:text=12,is%20greater%20than%20customer%20risk)). All client data fields needed for the plan (e.g. target retirement age, desired retirement corpus or income, assumed life expectancy, etc.) will have defined validations (e.g. retirement age must be above current age, life expectancy within a reasonable range). Mandatory fields must be filled in, otherwise the system prompts for completion before moving forward ([file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J](file://file-6SMqrxCE3DXF22B5VpMi2J#:~:text=12,there%20would%20be%20a%20hard)). \\n\\n## Retirement Goal Definition\\nThe module will provide a dedicated **Goal Definition** interface where the advisor (or client, if using a self-service portal) can set up the retirement goal. Key parameters to capture include:\\n- **Target Retirement Age or Date:** When the client plans to retire.\\n- **Retirement Income/Corpus Goal:** The desired yearly income during retirement, or equivalently the total corpus required by the retirement date. The system may assist in translating an income goal into a corpus based on expected lifespan and withdrawal rate.\\n- **Current Savings for Retirement:** Any assets already earmarked for retirement (e.g. provident fund balances, pension accounts) to factor into the plan.\\n- **Time Horizon:** The number of years until retirement (which is derived from current age and target retirement age) and the duration of the retirement period to plan for (e.g. life expectancy beyond retirement). The time horizon is a critical input that influences asset allocation strategy ([file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz](file://file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz#:~:text=Figure%203%3A%20Asset%20Allocation%20form,the%20asset%20class%20is%20100)) ([file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz](file://file-TbzHuXXUUqd8h6onMDGbjz#:~:text=16,If%20the%20customer)).\\n- **Assumptions:** Planners can input or adjust assumptions like expected inflation rate during accumulation and retirement, and expected rates of return for different asset classes. Default assumption values will be provided (for example, a default investment return rate might be 12% annually, which the user can override based on the client’s expected portfolio mix) ([file-FW8gd42fNtEAxEvSedQDDe](file://file-FW8gd42fNtEAxEvSedQDDe#:~:text=2%20Expected%20Return%20Rate%20%28,4%20Invested%20Amount)) ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=1%20Monthly%20Investment%20Input%20Numeric,Calculator%20as%20displayed%20in%20the)). These assumptions are documented and can be fine-tuned to create different scenarios (e.g. conservative vs. optimistic growth).\\n- **Contribution Constraints:** Any preferences or constraints on contributions, such as maximum monthly contribution the client can afford, or existing SIP (Systematic Investment Plan) commitments that can be counted toward the goal.\\n\\nThe goal setup screen will allow specifying the goal name (e.g. “Retirement Plan”), and will classify it under the *Retirement* goal type for reporting purposes ([file-Mnd1bRpJt17LcQfEHEZyXB](file://file-Mnd1bRpJt17LcQfEHEZyXB#:~:text=5%20Goal%20Type%20This%20displays,Wealth)). Once the retirement goal details are entered, the system can link this goal to the client’s portfolio structure. In practice, this means any investments made as part of this retirement plan are flagged and grouped under this goal for monitoring. The platform maintains mappings between the customer, their accounts, portfolios and goal identifiers so that goal-linked investments are tracked separately in holdings and reports ([file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd](file://file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd#:~:text=Basket%20based%20order%20trigger%20%281%29,%E2%97%8F%20Master%20Records)) ([file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd](file://file-G5PiGEUD6wsJF9vFDtcNFd#:~:text=The%20mappings%20of%20Customer%2C%20Account%2C,Applicable%20for%20JIO)).\\n\\n## Financial Projections and Calculations\\nWith the goal defined, the module will generate **cash-flow projections** and compute how much the client needs to save and invest to reach the retirement corpus goal. The core calculations and features include:\\n- **Required Contribution Calculation:** Based on the target amount and time available, the system calculates the required monthly or annual contribution. This uses the specified return assumptions to solve for the contribution that, when invested over the accumulation period, will yield the target corpus. For example, a **SIP calculator** can be used: inputting the goal amount, time horizon, and expected return will output the monthly investment needed ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=1,fields%20for%20the%20SIP%20Calculator)) ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=5%20Estimated%20Returns%20Output%20Output,Customer%20and%20Intellect%20Page%20163)). Conversely, a lump-sum or ad-hoc investment calculator is available to show how a one-time investment now would grow by retirement ([file-FW8gd42fNtEAxEvSedQDDe](file://file-FW8gd42fNtEAxEvSedQDDe#:~:text=1,This%20will%20be%20defaulted%20to)) ([file-FW8gd42fNtEAxEvSedQDDe](	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","jobId":"job_1765729673121_91gk73w3h","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_03f35748604802bd00693ee586e0948193b249c737da1daefa","reportFormat":"BRD"}	resp_03f35748604802bd00693ee586e0948193b249c737da1daefa	t	2025-12-14 17:29:42.913	2025-12-14 17:29:42.913	1	f	\N
