.\n2. Within Lead List Management, they choose **Automatic Lead Generation** as the method to create a list of target customers from existing records in the wealth system  .\n\nAutomatic Lead Generation specifically:\n- Uses customers already **onboarded / present in the wealth system** as the source population.\n- Relies on **filter criteria** defined by the user in a rule definition interface to select potential targets .\n\n---\n\n## 2. Defining Lead Rules (Segmentation Criteria)\n\n### 2.1 Lead Rule Setup\n\nThe user works in a **Lead Rule** or **Lead Criteria** setup screen, which is used to define how existing customer records will be filtered to create a list of potential targets for a campaign   .\n\nFrom this screen, they can:\n- **Add a new lead rule**.\n- **View existing lead rules**.\n- **Modify existing lead rules**.\n- **Trigger list generation** for a given rule   .\n\n### 2.2 Selecting Criteria and Operations\n\nWithin the lead rule definition, the user:\n\n1. **Selects a data attribute (criteria)** from a dropdown list—for example:\n   - AUM or total relationship value.\n   - Product holdings or product gaps.\n   - Demographics (age band, geography, segment).\n   - Channel or contact preferences.\n2. **Chooses a mathematical or logical operation** such as `Greater`, `Less`, `Equal`, `Between`, `Contains`, etc.\n3. **Enters the criteria value** (e.g., AUM > 1,000,000) to define the threshold or matching value. An example in the documentation is: Criteria = *Total AUM/Credit*, Operation = *Greater*, Value = *1,000,000* .\n4. Repeats this for multiple conditions and combines them using logical AND/OR (as supported by the rules interface) to build more complex segmentation.\n\nThis rules engine can conceptually support criteria across:\n- **Account and relationship data** (account type, segment, booking center).\n- **AUM and portfolio data** (overall AUM, holdings in particular products, under-penetration in certain products).\n- **Investment preferences and risk profile** (risk rating, product bans, suitability flags).\n- **Demographic attributes** (age, occupation, region).\n- **Behavioral signals** (recent transactions, inactivity, campaign responses) – typically sourced from CRM and transaction history.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Applying Rules Across Data Sources\n\nWhen the user saves or runs a lead rule, the platform’s rules engine:\n\n1. **Reads customer master and profile data** from the core CRM/onboarding system (e.g., name, segment, demographics, mapped RM, risk profile) .\n2. **Uses holdings/AUM and transaction data** from the wealth system—customers are described as "existing customers present/onboarded in the wealth system" and are the basis for filtering  .\n3. **Applies the filter criteria** defined in the lead rule over this combined dataset to identify which customers match the criteria for the campaign.\n4. **Produces a filtered set of customer records** as the candidate lead pool, which is then associated to a new or existing lead list.\n\nThis mechanism abstracts away the underlying data sources (CRM, client master, transaction store) and exposes them as selectable criteria to the user through dropdowns and operators .\n\n---\n\n## 4. Managing Lead Rules\n\nFrom the **View All Lead Rules** screen, the user can manage rule lifecycle   :\n\n- **View existing rules:** Inspect the criteria definition and status.\n- **Add lead rule:** Create a new segmentation rule for a specific campaign or product.\n- **Modify lead rule:** Update thresholds (e.g., AUM bands) or conditions as strategy changes.\n- **Generate list:** Execute the rule to refresh or create a lead list with up-to-date customers.\n\nThis supports continuous refinement of targeting logic without IT intervention.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Generating and Using the Lead List\n\n### 5.1 Generate List Action\n\nWhen the user selects **Generate List** for a given lead rule:\n\n1. The system runs the rule against the current customer base.\n2. It **displays the filtered customer records** that meet the defined criteria—these constitute the target leads for the campaign   .\n3. A **Lead List** object is created or updated, containing these leads for further campaign actions (such as assignment, calling, or digital communication).\n\n### 5.2 Lead List Management\n\nWithin Lead List Management, users can typically:\n- View different lead lists associated with campaigns.\n- Modify a list (e.g., add/remove specific leads, change status).\n- Merge multiple lead lists into a single consolidated list for broader campaigns .\n\n### 5.3 Output and Integration\n\nAlthough the documents describe list management within the platform UI, the generated lead lists can be conceptually:\n- **Consumed directly in the CRM module** for allocation to RMs or contact centers.\n- **Exported** (e.g., in a format suitable for CSV download or batch import) to external campaign tools, subject to platform capabilities.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Scheduling and Automation Considerations\n\nThe core referenced flows focus on **on-demand generation** via the Generate List action, but the same rules framework is suited for scheduling:\n\n- Define a lead rule once (e.g., "High AUM clients without product X").\n- Configure it to run at defined intervals (daily/weekly/monthly) using a scheduler component, so that new qualifying customers are automatically added to the associated lead list.\n- Notify users (e.g., campaign managers or RMs) when a list refresh completes.\n\nThis approach ensures ongoing, automated identification of target leads without manual re-definition of criteria.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Validations, Data Quality, and Error Handling\n\nTypical validations and checks around automatic lead generation include:\n\n- **Rule definition validation:**\n  - Ensuring mandatory fields (criteria, operation, value) are provided.\n  - Checking that combinations of criteria are syntactically and logically valid (e.g., no conflicting operators).\n- **Data existence and type checks:**\n  - Making sure the selected attributes exist for all or most customers; dealing gracefully with missing or null values.\n- **Upload vs. automatic generation:**\n  - In addition to automatic generation, the platform supports **Lead Upload**, where users can upload external lists and then review an **error log** to see invalid or rejected entries, which illustrates the use of validation and error reporting whenever new leads are created or updated .\n\nThese same principles apply to automatically generated lists—invalid or incomplete customer records should be handled consistently and, where relevant, flagged for data remediation before being used in campaigns.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Privacy, Consent, and Compliance\n\nWhen automatically generating lead lists from existing customers, the workflow must be constrained by privacy and regulatory requirements, for example:\n\n- **Use only permitted data:** Ensure that the criteria use data that is allowed for marketing or sales targeting, in line with consent, internal policies, and local regulations.\n- **Respect customer contact preferences:** Before a customer is added to a callable/emailable lead list, check do-not-contact flags or communication preferences stored in the customer profile.\n- **Purpose limitation:** Use segmentation and lead generation only for permitted purposes (e.g., servicing, suitable cross-sell) and not beyond what the customer has consented to.\n- **Auditability:** Maintain an audit trail showing:\n  - Which rules were run.\n  - When a lead list was generated or refreshed.\n  - Which users initiated changes to rules or lists.\n\nThese controls sit alongside the functional lead-rule and list-management flows to ensure compliant use of customer data.\n\n---\n\n## 9. End-to-End Automated Lead Generation Flow (Summary)\n\n1. **Access Lead List Management** and select **Automatic Lead Generation**.\n2. **Create or select a lead rule** in the Lead Rule setup screen.\n3. **Define criteria** (e.g., AUM, product holdings/gaps, demographics, behavior) using dropdown attributes, operations, and values .\n4. **Save the rule** and optionally configure a schedule (if supported) for periodic execution.\n5. **Run “Generate List”** to apply the rule to existing onboarded customers and produce a filtered set of records as a **lead list**   .\n6. **Review and manage the lead list** (view, refine, merge lists, export or feed into CRM/campaign tools) .\n7. **Apply validations and compliance checks** (data quality, consent, contact preferences, audit trail) before executing outbound campaigns.\n\nThis provides a structured, repeatable, and largely automated way for wealth-management users to generate targeted lead lists based on specific customer criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n[1] HSBC_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV13docx.pdf   \n[2] 360One_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf   \n[3] SBI_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV13.pdf 	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Lead","Customer Search","My Customers","INVESTOR","RM","Customer Dashboard","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Focus Funds","Mutual Funds","Product risk profile"],"seed_node_ids":["report:risk_profile_questionnaire","dataentity:lead","system:rmws","dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","report:customer_dashboard","datastore:focus_funds","report:my_customers","dataentity:rm","dataentity:mutual_funds","dataentity:investor","dataentity:fund_cut_off_time","report:customer_search","dataentity:product_risk_profile"],"expanded_nodes":83,"expanded_edges":181,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: resp_0c5ec1f943dff3bb00693f021f163081a29cbb5a910126e9fa\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"the