ll active campaigns assigned to them  \n- See key metrics in real time, such as:\n  - Total leads in the campaign  \n  - Leads contacted vs. not contacted  \n  - Conversions and other response breakdowns  \n\nThe system also calculates and updates metrics like **conversion rate** (e.g., percentage of targeted leads who responded positively), typically refreshed at each day’s end during the campaign.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Recording Customer Feedback\n\n**Capture Response screen**\n\nWhen an RM contacts a prospect or client under a campaign, they log the outcome via the **Capture Response** screen:\n\n- **Structured fields**:\n  - **Lead Status** – e.g., Ready for Follow-Up, In Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected  \n  - **Sub-Status** – e.g., Call Back, Uncontactable – Max Attempts  \n\n- **Free-text remarks**:\n  - RMs can enter **Remarks** to capture specific comments, reasons for acceptance/rejection, interests, or any qualitative feedback.\n\nThis combination of structured fields and free-text notes ensures both quantitative and qualitative feedback are recorded for each lead.\n\n**Surveys for detailed feedback**\n\nFor more detailed input, the platform supports **surveys**:\n\n- Surveys can be sent to customers (e.g., post-event satisfaction, interest in a new product).  \n- The system stores:\n  - Questions and answers  \n  - Customer ID  \n  - Survey name/version  \n  - Submission timestamp  \n\nSurveys can include rating scales or scoring logic, and the platform can compute an overall **survey score** or rating, which becomes part of the campaign’s feedback data.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Dashboards and Management Oversight\n\n**Frontline (RM) view**\n\nThe **Campaign Dashboard** gives RMs:\n\n- At-a-glance progress for each campaign  \n- Counts of leads by status (e.g., New, In Progress, Accepted, Rejected)  \n- Drill-down capability to update responses or review details, helping ensure no lead is missed.\n\n**Supervisor / management view**\n\nSupervisor-level dashboards provide:\n\n- Aggregated views of all leads under active campaigns  \n- Breakdown by:\n  - Relationship manager  \n  - Response status (New, In Progress, Client Accepted, Client Rejected, etc.)  \n\nThis helps management:\n\n- Monitor overall campaign performance  \n- Compare RMs and campaigns (e.g., acceptance rates)  \n- Identify stalled or untouched leads for timely follow-up.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Controls, Approvals, and Audit Trail\n\n**Maker-checker for campaigns**\n\nCampaigns follow a **maker-checker** process:\n\n- New or modified campaigns start as **Unauthorized/Pending**.  \n- An authorized supervisor must **approve** them before they become Active.  \n\n**Audit trail**\n\nAll key actions are logged:\n\n- Campaign creation, modification, authorization/rejection  \n- Lead status updates and response captures  \n\nThe **audit trail** records who did what, when, and the before/after values, supporting internal controls and regulatory compliance.\n\n---\n\n**Referenced documents (as in the original answer):**\n\n1. *Journey of Suspect to Lead* – Campaign Dashboard (Functional Specification)  \n2. *Journey of Suspect to Lead* – Campaign Record Fields (Functional Specification)  \n3. *Campaign Management Enhancements* – Timeline & Conversions (Design Document)  \n4. *Journey of Suspect to Lead* – Lead Response Capture (Functional Specification)  \n5. *Client Portal Journey* – Survey Feedback Capture (Functional Specification)  \n6. *Lead Status by RM Dashboard* – Supervisor Campaign Summary (Product Document)  \n7. *Audit Trail* – Campaign Approval & Audit (System Specification)	{\n  "stepback_intent": "To explain the platform's features for monitoring active campaign progress and capturing customer feedback.",\n  "expanded_question": "What capabilities does the wealth management platform offer to track the progress and status of active campaigns (including campaign lifecycle stages, key dates, assigned owners, and timelines) and to capture customer feedback (through structured fields, free-text notes, or ratings) associated with each campaign, covering data models, input forms or surveys, workflow steps, dashboards, and reporting for management and compliance?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Campaign",\n    "Campaign Dashboard",\n    "Lead",\n    "Response Status",\n    "Survey",\n    "Audit Trail"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    {\n      "id": "1",\n      "source": "SBI_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV13.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "2",\n      "source": "JBR_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "3",\n      "source": "SBI_Journey of Suspect to Lead_R1 Enhancement Lot3_V10.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "4",\n      "source": "360One_Journey of Suspect to Lead_V10_CCV10docx.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "5",\n      "source": "SBI_Journey of Client Portal_V10_CCV15.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "6",\n      "source": "SBI_Journey of Assesing Risk_DC3_Lead status by RM.pdf"\n    },\n    {\n      "id": "7",\n      "source": "SBI_Audit Trail_V10.pdf"\n    }\n  ],\n  "answer": "## Campaign Progress Tracking\\nThe platform provides a **Campaign Management** module that lets users monitor each campaign through its full lifecycle. A dedicated **Campaign Dashboard** allows relationship managers to view all active campaigns assigned to them and track key metrics in real time ([file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2](file://file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2#:~:text=on%20the%20left%20panel,to%20the%20Capture%20Response%20screen)). Every campaign is set up as a record with fields capturing its details – for example, each campaign has a **Type** (such as event-based or normal) and a **Status** indicating its stage in the lifecycle (e.g. *New*, *Active*, *Completed*, or *Rejected*) ([file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S](file://file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S#:~:text=t%20Status%20Displays%20the%20status,Completed)). Campaign records also include important timeline fields like the **Start Date** and **End Date** of the campaign, as well as any defined *yield period* for measuring post-campaign outcomes ([file-H1Lip4sQcVVTfgYDYUWa7N](file://file-H1Lip4sQcVVTfgYDYUWa7N#:~:text=ii,above%20campaign%20has%2010%20leads)). As the campaign progresses, the system continuously updates performance data. For instance, it can calculate the campaign’s conversion rate (the percentage of targeted leads who responded positively) and display this metric on the campaign’s record – updated at each day’s end through the campaign’s duration ([file-3vct5kPBRCGmT9SezB2Kt7](file://file-3vct5kPBRCGmT9SezB2Kt7#:~:text=4,at%20each%20EOD%20till%20the)). This gives users a clear view of how the campaign is performing against its targets at any point in time.\\n\\n## Capturing Customer Feedback\\nFor each campaign, the platform enables structured capture of customer responses and feedback. When an RM reaches out to a prospect or client as part of a campaign, they use the **Capture Response** screen to log the outcome of that interaction. The response form includes structured fields for **Lead Status** and **Sub-Status** – for example, the RM can mark the lead as *Ready for Follow-Up*, *In Progress*, *Client Accepted*, *Client Rejected*, etc., with sub-status details like “Call Back” or “Uncontactable – Max Attempts” to further categorize the result ([file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S](file://file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S#:~:text=details%20for%20the%20Lead%3A%20a,viewed%20on%20the%20Campaign%20Dashboard)). In addition to these standardized fields, the RM can enter free-text **Remarks** to record any specific comments or feedback the customer provided during the conversation ([file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S](file://file-1hgFoDxoZZQucmwNwSS38S#:~:text=details%20for%20the%20Lead%3A%20a,viewed%20on%20the%20Campaign%20Dashboard)). This ensures that along with the quantitative status updates, any qualitative insights or reasons (such as why a client declined or what product they showed interest in) are documented in the system.\\n\\nThe platform also supports capturing feedback through **surveys** when more detailed input is needed. Users can design and send survey forms to customers – for example, to gauge satisfaction after an event or to rate interest in a new product. The system stores all survey responses in a structured way, recording the questions asked and the answers given, along with metadata like the customer’s ID, the survey name/version, and the submission time . Surveys can include rating scales or score calculations; the platform will compute an overall **survey score** or rating based on the customer’s responses and save it as part of the feedback record . This allows campaigns to have associated customer satisfaction metrics or sentiment scores in addition to the direct lead responses.\\n\\n## Dashboards and Oversight\\nAll the captured campaign data feeds into real-time dashboards and reports for ongoing tracking and management oversight. The **Campaign Dashboard** gives an at-a-glance summary of each active campaign’s progress for the frontline user (RM), showing metrics like the total number of leads in the campaign, how many have been contacted, and how many have converted or responded in each way ([file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2](file://file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2#:~:text=on%20the%20left%20panel,to%20the%20Capture%20Response%20screen)). From this dashboard, RMs can quickly drill down to update responses or view details, ensuring no lead falls through the cracks ([file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2](file://file-D9Q7nWRQy7h2w2WNbTgBi2#:~:text=on%20the%20left%20panel,to%20the%20Capture%20Response%20screen)). \\n\\nFor management, the platform provides aggregate views to monitor campaign performance across the team. A supervisor-level dashboard widget, for example, can display all leads under active campaigns broken down by relationship manager and response status ([file-JG2ioJH7P2aRhsSPJiZH4E](file://file-JG2ioJH7P2aRhsSPJiZH4E#:~:text=2,Details%20of%20the%20entity)). This means a manager can see, for each RM, how many of their campaign leads are *New*, *In Progress*, *Client Accepted*, *Client Rejected*, etc., along with totals ([file-JG2ioJH7P2aRhsSPJiZH4E](file://file-JG2ioJH7P2aRhsSPJiZH4E#:~:text=2,Details%20of%20the%20entity)). Such a view helps in identifying overall campaign progress and comparing performance (e.g., which campaigns or RMs are achieving higher client acceptance rates). It also serves a compliance function by highlighting if any active campaign leads remain untouched or stalled (e.g., too many “New” or “Ready for Follow-Up” leads), prompting timely intervention.\\n\\nThe platform’s design includes workflow steps and controls to ensure campaigns are executed in a compliant manner. There is a built-in **maker-checker approval process** for launching campaigns: when a campaign record is created or modified, it starts in an **Unauthorized/Pending** state and must be reviewed and approved by an authorized supervisor before becoming *Active* . All changes and updates – from campaign creation and activation to each lead’s status update – are logged in the system’s **audit trail** . This audit log captures who performed each action and when, as well as the before/after status (e.g. whether a campaign was authorized or rejected by the approver) . These features provide transparency and support compliance requirements, allowing internal teams or regulators to review the history of a campaign and the feedback collected. \\n\\n**Sources:**\\n1. Campaign Dashboard – *Journey of Suspect to Lead* (Functional Specification)\\n2. Campaign Record Fields – *Journey of Suspect to Lead* (Functional Specification)\\n3. Campaign Timeline & Conversions – *Campaign Management Enhancements* (Design Document)\\n4. Lead Response Capture – *Journey of Suspect to Lead* (Functional Specification)\\n5. Survey Feedback Capture – *Client Portal Journey* (Functional Specification)\\n6. Supervisor Campaign Summary – *Lead Status by RM Dashboard* (Pro