tion and handover capabilities where a new agent can be designated for a set of clients (and customers may receive notifications when reassignment occurs) [1].\n- The operation typically results in updating each client’s primary agent/ownership reference and related entitlements, and it may drive downstream workflow changes (e.g., order routing, compliance checks, and client communications) consistent with the platform’s change-management policies [1].\n\n2) Permissions and governance\n- Access to bulk reassignment features is governed by role-based access controls (RBAC) or equivalent entitlement systems. Ensure the Operations role has the required permissions to perform agent reassignment and to view/modify client-agent mappings [3].\n- Changes should be auditable and traceable; system logs should capture who initiated the bulk action, when, what scope (client subset or full batch), and the before/after agent mappings [2].\n\n3) Data requirements and eligibility\n- The operation requires clear identifiers for the source agent and the destination agent, and a list or criteria identifying which client records are to be reassigned (client/investment account identifiers or equivalent primary keys). In practice, identifiers used for client-agent mapping are treated as the authoritative keys for reassignment [3].\n- Ensure all clients in scope are eligible for reassignment under policy (e.g., entitlements, regulatory/compliance constraints, and any client-level approvals). The platform should validate these before finalizing the bulk action [3].\n\n4) Bulk action approaches (UI and API)\n- UI approach (bulk action): Admin or Operations consoles commonly provide a Bulk Reassignment feature. The steps generally include selecting the bulk action, specifying source and destination agents, defining the target client scope (e.g., via a filter, batch import, or pre-defined group), validating the scope, and executing the reassignment. Post-action, a confirmation and audit trail are produced, and notifications may be issued to clients per policy [1].\n- API/batch approach: For automated or integrated workflows, an API or batch job can be invoked to perform the reassignment in bulk. The API would accept sourceAgentId, destinationAgentId, and a list of client identifiers (or an alternative scope descriptor). The system should return a batch job/operation ID for tracking and provide an audit trail on completion [2].\n\n5) Post-action notifications and client impact\n- Clients may receive notifications about their reassignment to a new agent, depending on policy. When such notifications are configured, there should be an automated mechanism to alert the client about the change of agent/relationship owner [1].\n- Downstream workflow implications can include updated advisor dashboards, order routing recalculations, and re-validation steps to ensure ongoing compliance and alignment with risk/approach profiles [1].\n\n6) Auditing, rollback, and compliance considerations\n- All bulk reassignment activities should be logged with sufficient detail to support audits, including who performed the action, the scope, timestamps, and before/after mappings. This supports traceability and regulatory review [2].\n- Where feasible, include rollback or compensating actions to revert the reassignment if a subsequent review or error is detected. This capability should be part of the platform’s change-management and auditing framework [2].\n- Permissions and changes should be captured in the entitlements and access-control framework to ensure only authorized users can perform bulk reassignments, and that changes stay within compliance guidelines [3].\n\n7) Related considerations and examples\n- Delegation and handover concepts exist in practice where an agent is reassigned to a client, with administrative notifications to clients upon reassignment [1].\n- Individual changes to a client’s agent mapping (e.g., editing a customer profile to update the Primary Agent) illustrate the fundamental operation of reassigning ownership at the client level, which bulk operations extend to the multi-record case [4].\n\nSources:\n- Maybank_Handover and Delegation_V12_CCV10.pdf [1]\n- BOC Philippines Tech - Trust systems.pdf [2]\n- EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx [3]\n- Maybank_Journey of Editing Customer Profile_V12_CCV10.pdf [4]	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["RM","Order","customer","transaction","Product risk profile","CIF id","securities","warning message","security","Mutual Funds"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:order","dataentity:cif_id","dataentity:securities","dataentity:security","dataentity:warning_message","dataentity:mutual_funds","dataentity:customer","dataentity:rm","system:rmws","report:warning_message","dataentity:product_risk_profile","dataentity:transaction"],"expanded_nodes":95,"expanded_edges":254,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustive coverage\\n\\nUser's Question: How can an Operations User transfer a large number of clients to a new agent at once without selecting them individually?","How can an Operations User perform a bulk reassignment of multiple client records to a different agent without selecting each client individually?","Within the wealth-management platform, what options exist for an Operations User to bulk-transfer multiple client records from one agent to another without per-client selection? Provide guidance on supported bulk actions, required permissions, eligible client criteria, batch size limits, data requirements (source 