nsfer-related records. This exact authorization flow is demonstrated in supervisor workflows where changes or transfers require prior approval [4].\n- In practice, the authorization flow is surfaced as a dedicated Authorization screen within wealth-management journeys, e.g., an Order Authorization screen used to approve orders initiated in the system [2].\n\n2) View and act on the transfer item\n- The supervisor/checker reviews the pending transfer item from the approval queue. In the example workflows, the interface presents the user’s tasks in a queue such as "My Group Task" and "My Task" for selection and action, enabling the supervisor to claim and authorize a specific transfer record [1].\n\n3) Make the approval decision\n- The supervisor/checker approves (or rejects) the transfer. Upon approval, the system progresses the transfer to downstream processing; the architecture emphasizes that an authorization step enables subsequent processing, including reconciliation with RTA flows [3].\n\n4) Downstream impact and data touchpoints\n- After approval, the transfer moves into the external/internal processing path (e.g., RTA transmission and reconciliation). The wealth-management journey documents describe that authorized wealth orders are reconciled and updated through subsequent engines, with statuses moving through stages such as Authorized → Contracted → Settled as processing occurs with RTA feeds [3]. The connection between the wealth order and the RTA transaction is maintained (e.g., via a transaction number), enabling traceability into the RTA system and folio updates [3].\n\n5) Documentation and audit considerations\n- The authorization event is documented within the system’s governance flow, and the related screens and queues provide an auditable trail of who approved what and when (e.g., authorization actions captured in the RM/Ops office workflow and order authorization histories) as shown in supervisory authorization examples [4].\n\nKey artifacts and touchpoints (examples across journeys)\n- Authorization screen in RM Office / Operations Office used by supervisors to authorize or reject items [1, 4].\n- Order Authorization screen used to authorize wealth-system orders, with an order book displaying statuses for monitoring [2].\n- Queues and claim workflow (My Group Task, My Task) to assign and process approvals [1].\n- Downstream processing path post-authorization includes integration with RTA feeds and status transitions on the order/transaction records [3].\n\nNotes\n- The described pattern—supervisor approval via an Authorization screen, queue-based task handling, and downstream processing after approval—appears across multiple journey documents and is the established model for transfer-related approvals in these examples [1][2][4].\n\nSources\n- JBR_Journey of Editing Customer Profile_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf [1]\n- 360ONE_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV13_Part 1.pdf [2]\n- SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V10_CCV12.pdf [3]\n- WQ_Journey of Defining Maintenances_HSBC_V10_CCV10.pdf [4]	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["sum of percentage should be 100","SCM_REDEEM_MIN_BALANCE","unit/amount","Close AC Flag","systematic day/date","ARNCODE","Approval Date & Time","PMS application","India Infoline Wealth","RTA"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:rta_ref_no","dataentity:systematic_day_date","dataentity:approval_date_time","dataentity:arncode","dataentity:unit_amount","dataentity:close_ac_flag","dataentity:scm_redeem_min_balance","system:india_infoline_wealth","system:rta","system:pms_app","compliance:sum_percentage_should_be_100","compliance:rta"],"expanded_nodes":53,"expanded_edges":107,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: 9822b9a5-a913-4ac0-b74b-397d8ecaf176\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - C