verification steps are followed by a formal sign-in. This sequence is described in documented onboarding flows where mobile verification uses OTP to complete verification steps before access is granted [1].\n- If multi-factor authentication (MFA) is configured for the user or the role, the second factor is enforced at this step. This aligns with best-practice patterns for securing initial access and subsequent logins during onboarding and ongoing use [1].\n\n2) Secure session establishment\n- Upon successful authentication, a session is established and a session identifier is issued. Sessions should be created using securely generated, sufficiently random tokens to prevent predictive attacks [2].\n- The system should regenerate session tokens upon authentication and whenever privilege levels or encryption status changes to minimize session fixation risks [2].\n- Implement robust session lifecycle controls: idle session timeouts (automatic logout after inactivity) and absolute session timeouts (maximum time since login) to limit exposure from stale sessions [2].\n- If there is any sign of tampering or misuse (e.g., session cloning), terminate the session and require re-authentication to continue access [2].\n- On logout, destroy the session and related server-side data to prevent revival of the session [2].\n\n3) Device recognition and risk checks (post-verification)\n- Perform device and risk-based checks at sign-in: evaluate device integrity, location/IP reputation, and other contextual signals to decide whether to allow access or challenge the user with additional verification [3].\n- If a device or risk signal is deemed high-risk, prompt for additional verification or enforce stricter authentication measures before granting access [3].\n\n4) Multi-factor authentication (MFA) guidance\n- MFA is recommended or required where configured, leveraging factors such as time-based one-time passwords (TOTP), push-based approvals, biometrics, or other second factors. The onboarding/documentation patterns show OTP-based verification as a core step in verification and access flows, illustrating MFA-like two-factor prompts during secure entry [1].\n- In high-risk sign-ins or first-time access, MFA can be intensified (e.g., risk-based triggers) to reduce credential abuse while balancing user experience [3].\n\n5) Token handling and session security\n- Access tokens should be short-lived and bound to the authenticated session; refresh tokens (where used) should be securely stored and rotated as part of token lifecycle management. The guidance emphasizes secure token handling, regeneration on authentication, and protection against token theft or replay [2].\n- Token handling should support re-authentication on privilege changes or encryption state transitions to maintain continuous risk-appropriate access [2].\n\n6) Login prompts and user experience considerations\n- The login prompt should clearly guide the user through the required steps (credentials, MFA if applicable, device verification prompts) and present any compliance or policy notices relevant to initial and ongoing access. Risk and compliance prompts are typically aligned with the onboarding/risk assessment flows described in product journeys [4].\n\n7) Security and compliance policies governing initial vs. subsequent access\n- Initial access is governed by identity verification, verification-channel trust, and mandatory MFA where configured; subsequent access is governed by persistent session security controls (token hygiene, re-authentication on sensitive actions, idle/absolute timeouts, and tamper-detection). The security guidance documents outline session management and control requirements (random session identifiers, token regeneration, timeouts, and tamper-detection) to ensure ongoing protection across sessions [2].\n- Risk-profile and entitlement validations (as part of onboarding and ongoing access governance) influence permitted actions and entitlements, aligning with enterprise risk controls and compliance expectations [3][4].\n\nIn summary, securing post-email-verification access centers on binding verified identity to a securely established session, applying device and risk signals, enforcing MFA as configured, managing tokens carefully, and adhering to strict session lifecycle and tamper-detection policies to protect initial and subsequent access.\n\nSources:\n- [1] Maybank_DTC_Journey of Customer Onboarding_V11.pdf\n- [2] BOC Philippines Security - Trust systems.pdf\n- [3] 360ONE_Journey of Assesing Risk_V10_CCV15.pdf\n- [4] IIFL_Journey of Self-Assessment and Supervisor Assessment-Customer Dashboard_V10_CCV13.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Login","system generated mail","Validations","General Validation","authorization","Supervisor Approval","Risk Profile Questionnaire","Security Maintenance","Intellect","India Infoline Wealth"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:risk_profile_questionnaire","system:security_maintenance","dataentity:validations_warning","compliance:supervisor_approval","system:intellect","report:risk_profile_questionnaire","dataentity:login","datastore:security_maintenance","system:generated_mail","report:pop_up_message","report:login","compliance:validations","system:india_infoline_wealth","dataentity:security","compliance:authorization","compliance:general_validation"],"expanded_nodes":53,"expanded_edges":68,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: 9822b9a5-a913-4ac0-b74b-397d8ecaf176\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it