 be lasting. \n\n- **Delegation**\n  - Does **not** permanently change the ultimate owner in principle; instead, it assigns the day‑to‑day management to another agent for a defined period.\n  - The original agent is considered to be temporarily replaced or supported, and the arrangement is meant to be reversible once the delegation period ends.  \n\n### 2. Duration and Intent\n\n- **Handover (Permanent)**\n  - Described as a *permanent* movement of Prospects/Customers from one agent to another. \n  - No end date is defined as part of the process; the assumption is that the new agent continues to own and manage the relationship going forward.\n\n- **Delegation (Temporary)**\n  - Explicitly positioned as *temporary* in nature, with clear start and (optionally) end dates captured in the delegation details.  \n  - Typical use cases include temporary leave, short‑term role changes, or workload balancing, after which the relationship can revert to the original agent.\n\n### 3. Process Behaviour\n\n- **Handover**\n  - Selected Leads/Prospects/Customers are re‑assigned so that all subsequent activities and ownership reporting align to the new agent.\n  - Often used in bulk (e.g., when an agent exits), with the system supporting prospect and client handover flows.  \n\n- **Delegation**\n  - The system captures delegation details such as reassignment reason, start date, and end date for the delegated period. \n  - The delegated agent manages the client during the specified period, but functionally the arrangement is understood as temporary relationship management rather than a full transfer of book.\n\n### 4. Conceptual Summary\n\n- Use **Handover** when you want to **reallocate the client/prospect book permanently** to a new primary agent.\n- Use **Delegation** when you want to **temporarily assign management responsibilities** to another agent while preserving the underlying ownership context for eventual reversion.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n- [1] Maybank_Handover and Delega