ogin/credential‑setup step rather than being silently logged into a full session.\n\n### 2. Required Authentication Steps After Email Verification\n\nImmediately after email verification, the recommended flow is:\n\n1. **Initial credential setup or confirmation**  \n   - If this is a first‑time user: prompt to **set a strong password/PIN** that meets policy (length, complexity, disallow reuse, etc.).  \n   - If the user already has credentials: prompt a **standard login** (user ID + password) using the now-verified email for account association.\n\n2. **Multi‑Factor Authentication (MFA)**  \n   - For first login after email verification, enforce **step‑up MFA** (OTP to mobile/email, or app-based token) in addition to password.  \n   - The same OTP pattern as used in onboarding (e.g., send OTP, user inputs OTP on verification screen) can be reused for MFA, but with distinct purpose/labels .\n\n3. **Session creation only after successful password + MFA**  \n   - An authenticated application session is established **only after both** password authentication and MFA succeed.  \n   - Prior steps (email verification screens) run in a pre‑auth, limited session that does not expose customer or portfolio data.\n\n### 3. Session Management Immediately Post‑Verification\n\n1. **Session start and scope**  \n   - The authenticated session starts once the user completes password login and mandatory MFA.  \n   - Default session scope should provide access to general dashboards and non-transactional views, with **separate step‑up prompts for high‑risk actions** (e.g., order placement, changes to risk profile, entitlements).\n\n2. **Session timeout and idle limits**  \n   - Set a **shorter idle timeout** for the **first session after email verification** (e.g., 5–10 minutes of inactivity) to limit exposure if the environment or device is not yet trusted.  \n   - Enforce an **absolute session lifetime** regardless of activity (e.g., 30–60 minutes) before re‑authentication is required for any further access.\n\n3. **Re-authentication for sensitive actions**  \n   - Before the user performs security‑sensitive or risk‑sensitive actions (e.g., changing contact details, submitting a high‑risk purchase order), prompt for:  \n     - Password re‑entry and/or  \n     - Another OTP/app‑based factor.  \n   - This aligns with risk‑based controls already defined for product and customer risk, where deviations trigger warnings or hard stops during order journeys .\n\n### 4. Device and Risk-Based Access Controls\n\n1. **Basic device and channel checks**  \n   - Tag the device/browser at the time of the first post‑verification login (user agent, IP, geo metadata).  \n   - If the device/geo appears anomalous vs. typical usage, **force MFA** even if the user later marks the device as trusted.\n\n2. **Trusted device flag with constraints**  \n   - Optionally allow the user to mark a device as **trusted** (e.g., suppress some MFA prompts for low‑risk actions).  \n   - Even on trusted devices, **always require MFA** for high‑risk actions like placing orders in products with higher product risk profile than the customer’s risk profile or modifying key profile attributes .\n\n3. **Risk-aware access controls**  \n   - Ensure that once logged in, all transactional screens (e.g., purchase/order flows) continue to apply **risk profile validations**, preventing orders where product risk exceeds the customer’s risk tolerance beyond allowed thresholds .  \n   - Alert and notification configurations for risk mismatches and exceptional cases (e.g., product risk > customer risk by X levels) should remain active from the very first session .\n\n### 5. Role-Based Access and Entitlements\n\n1. **Role derivation post-verification**  \n   - Upon authenticated login, the system resolves the user’s **role and entitlements** (e.g., customer, RM, supervisor) from central maintenance/definition modules .  \n   - Screens, menus, and actions exposed in this first session must strictly follow these entitlements.\n\n2. **Segregation of duties and approvals**  \n   - For actions that require additional approvals (e.g., orders with higher risk deviation), ensure the same multi‑level authorization logic applies from the first post‑verification session, routing orders to supervisors or heads as configured .\n\n### 6. System-Generated Communication and Notifications\n\n1. **Confirmation mails/messages**  \n   - After email verification and first successful authenticated access, send a **system-generated notification** (email/SMS/in‑app) confirming:  \n     - Email verified successfully.  \n     - Date/time and channel of first secure login.\n\n2. **Security alerts**  \n   - If an unusual device/location is detected, generate alerts to the user and/or internal monitoring teams, using the existing alert/notification framework that also handles product‑risk and exception alerts .\n\n### 7. Logging and Audit Requirements\n\nDuring the immediate post‑email‑verification period, ensure that the following events are fully logged and auditable:\n\n1. **Verification and authentication events**  \n   - Email verification request and outcome (success/failure) with timestamp and channel .  \n   - Password setup/change events.  \n   - All login attempts, MFA challenges, and results.\n\n2. **Session lifecycle events**  \n   - Session creation (with correlation to email-verified identity).  \n   - Session termination due to explicit logout, idle timeout, or absolute timeout.\n\n3. **Security‑relevant actions**  \n   - Changes to customer profile that affect risk assessment, limits, or contact details (based on defined maintenance and role modules) .  \n   - Any order or purchase attempts where product risk is higher than customer risk, including triggered warnings, hard stops, and approvals  .\n\n4. **Entitlement and configuration changes (back-office)**  \n   - Although not done by the end user during this session, any changes to roles, service groups, or alert definitions that could affect how the user is controlled should also be audited in the same ecosystem .\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nImmediately after email verification, the application should:\n\n- Treat verification as a **pre‑auth step**, not a full login.  \n- Require **password authentication plus MFA** before creating a full session.  \n- Start a **tightly controlled initial session** (short idle and absolute timeouts), with step‑up re‑authentication for sensitive actions.  \n- Apply **risk-aware validations** (e.g., product vs. customer risk profile) and standard role-based entitlements from the first session  .  \n- Generate **system notifications** for verification and first secure login, and comprehensively **log/audit** all verification, authentication, session, and risk-relevant actions.\n\n### Sources\n\n[1] HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10.pdf  \n[2] IIFL_Journey of Defining Maintenance_V10_CCV13_Part 1.pdf  \n[3] 360One_Journey of Creating Model Portfolio_V11_CCV13.pdf  \n[4] SBI_Journey of Defining Maintenances__V10.pdf  \n[5] SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF V10_SBI_CCV13.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["OTP verification screen","Login","User Office Landing Screen","system generated mail","Notification to User screen"],"seed_node_ids":["system:generated_mail","report:login","dataentity:login","report:otp_verification_screen","report:user_office_landing_screen","report:notification_to_user_screen"],"expanded_nodes":16,"expanded_edges":639,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exis