 with clear instructions and limited validity (e.g., a few minutes). \n- On the Email Verification screen, the user inputs the OTP; the system validates it and marks the email as verified in the user record.\n\n**Security controls:**\n- OTP is single‑use, time‑bound, and bound to the specific onboarding session and email ID. \n- Limited retry attempts; on exceeding retries or expiry, the OTP must be regenerated, and the old one invalidated.\n\n### 2. Transition from “verified email” to “first secure access”\nOnce the OTP is successfully validated, the user should be led through *one controlled step* to obtain secure application access:\n\n1. **If credentials are not yet created (typical DIY onboarding):**\n   - Redirect the user to a *First‑Time Login / Set Credentials* screen.\n   - Require the user to set a strong login password (and optionally a PIN or security questions) that meets configured complexity rules.\n   - Bind the new credentials to the user profile just created during onboarding.\n\n2. **If credentials already exist (e.g., pre‑created by operations / User Office):**\n   - Show a confirmation screen that email is verified.\n   - Prompt the user to proceed to the standard Login screen and authenticate with existing credentials.\n\nIn both cases, **successful login after email verification** is what actually establishes the authenticated session; email verification alone does not. \n\n### 3. Authentication and session establishment\nAfter email verification and (if needed) credential setup, the next step is a proper login:\n\n- The user accesses the **Login** screen and enters their username (or registered email/ID) and password.\n- The system authenticates against the user directory / user maintenance layer, enforcing password policies and lockout rules.\n- On success, a secure session is created (e.g., via session token/cookie) with:\n  - An idle timeout.\n  - A hard session expiry.\n  - Device/browser binding where required (e.g., flagging new devices for additional checks).\n\n**First‑login hardening (post‑verification):**\n- Enforce password reset on first login if credentials were system‑generated and sent via email/SMS.\n- Optionally trigger a step‑up factor (e.g., OTP to email or mobile) for the very first authenticated session, then mark the device as trusted.\n\n### 4. Entitlement activation after secure login\nOnly *after* a successful authenticated login should business entitlements be activated:\n\n- The platform applies actor/entitlement rules to determine what the user can see and do (e.g., which dashboards, which accounts, which transactions). \n- Based on role and entitlements, the user is routed to the appropriate landing screen (e.g., Customer Dashboard, STP dashboard, or RM/Back‑office workspace).  \n- Transactional journeys such as STP, SWP, or order placement are enabled only if the user’s role and account status meet prerequisites and validations defined in the platform. \n\n### 5. Landing on the Customer Dashboard / workspace\nOnce authenticated and entitled, the user is directed to the relevant workspace:\n\n- For an end customer in a DIY journey, the **Customer Dashboard** typically becomes the default landing screen after login, displaying portfolio, holdings, and other summary details. \n- For an RM or internal user, the system may redirect to an RM office or equivalent workspace, from which they can open a Customer Dashboard or other tools.\n- In onboarding journeys where KYC or other steps are still pending, the system may allow **view‑only** or limited‑function dashboards until all prerequisites are complete. \n\n### 6. Role of related systems and components\nWithin this flow, various logical components play distinct roles:\n\n- **Login / Authentication layer**\n  - Handles credential verification, first‑time login, password changes, and enforcement of security policies.\n  - Issues and maintains the authenticated session token.\n\n- **User maintenance / User Office**\n  - Maintains user master data (IDs, contact details, status, roles, and entitlements).\n  - May pre‑create users, trigger initial credential generation, and manage lifecycle events (activation, lock, disable).\n\n- **System‑generated mail & Email body**\n  - Delivers OTPs for verification and other notifications (e.g., transactional emails in later journeys). \n  - The email body templates convey purpose, masking sensitive data, and confirm that the message is system‑generated (no reply).\n\n- **Core wealth / transaction platform (e.g., STP, order journeys)**\n  - Exposes post‑login transaction journeys (STP, SWP, purchases, redemptions) that rely on authenticated user context and entitlements. \n  - Performs field‑level and business validations before allowing orders.\n\n- **Dashboards and desks (Customer Dashboard, Customer Profile Desk)**\n  - Provide a consolidated, post‑login view of the customer’s data and activities.\n  - Act as a secure entry point into holdings, orders, and other detailed screens. \n\n### 7. Recommended control summary for “immediate post‑verification access”\nTo specifically answer *how a user secures access immediately after email verification*:\n\n1. Verify email using a time‑bound OTP sent via system‑generated mail.\n2. Upon successful verification:\n   - If no credentials exist, force the user into a one‑time credential setup screen, with strong password rules.\n   - If credentials exist, instruct the user to proceed to the standard Login screen.\n3. Require a full login (ID + password, optionally with an additional factor for first login) to create an authenticated session.\n4. After login, apply entitlements and navigate to the appropriate dashboard (e.g., Customer Dashboard) while enforcing session timeouts and device/security policies.\n5. Keep transactional capabilities and sensitive data strictly behind this authenticated and entitled session boundary.\n\nAll of the above ensures that email verification improves assurance of contact ownership but does **not** itself grant full application access; secure access is only established once the user completes authentication and the platform activates the correct entitlements.\n\n\n### Sources\n- [1] HSBC_DIY_Journey of Customer Onboarding V10.pdf\n- [2] SAAB-DIY Journey of Self_Assessment and Supervisor Assessment_Customer Dashboard_V10_CCV12docx.pdf\n- [3] HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 3.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"balanced","model":"gpt-5.1","seed_node_names":["Login","User","Security maintenance","system generated mail","Email Body","User Office","Intellect","HSBC PWS","Wealth Qube","Validation type - Security master fields"],"seed_node_ids":["system:generated_mail","system:user_office","system:intellect","dataentity:user","system:wealth_qube","report:login","dataentity:security","dataentity:login","datastore:security_maintenance","dataentity:email_body","system:hsbc_pws","system:security_maintenance","compliance:validation_type_security_master_fields"],"expanded_nodes":69,"expanded_edges":152,"kg_guided_queries":["Previous context ID: d91b121e-5ac3-40dd-897b-23e557cf2ff5\\n\\nQuestion: [Context-Aware Follow-up Question with Focus Directives]\\n\\nPrevious conversation history is provided for context. Please follow these instructions:\\n\\nSTEP 1 - Context Understanding:\\n• Evaluate if this question contains pronouns or unclear references (e.g., \\"this\\", \\"it\\", \\"that\\", \\"these\\", \\"the above\\")\\n• If such references exist, identify what they refer to based on the conversation history\\n• Internally clarify the question to make it self-contained and explicit\\n\\nSTEP 2 - Focused Response Generation:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Pri