9,0.008732652,-0.041376658,-0.009153678,0.022924121,-0.0073389127,0.010046543,0.008369699,-0.021907851,0.002996178,0.03803749,-0.0033990561,0.009828771,0.011832273,-0.018147657,-0.0117742,-0.030778427,0.023853282,-0.014278577,-0.028949143,0.0042320336,0.02022375,-0.0054116314,0.010053802,0.026785942,-0.021385198,-0.014685084,0.011498355,0.013291344,0.016231265,-0.004703873,-0.02463726,-0.013022759,0.008275332,-0.0152149955,-0.008892352,0.023591954,0.004475212,-0.02317093,0.012906614,-0.030778427,0.009277082,0.014793971,-0.027671548,0.015171441,-0.0019563173,0.052875016,-0.0063335323,0.03943123,-0.0020615738,0.01076519,-0.028832998,0.0052664503,0.0016868247,0.05081344,0.009719885,-0.017610487,0.06144071,0.042799436,0.0007776271,0.021327127,-0.007240915,-0.019091336,0.0072626923,-0.040534608,0.019236516,-0.01951236,0.029646013,0.006623895,0.0028183311,-0.010032025,0.0042175157,-0.050145607,0.022807976,-0.013487339,-0.011977454,0.0045042485,-0.0010788782,0.0047365385,-0.0044243988,-0.057956357,0.024172679,-0.0061230194,-0.024942141,0.035656516,0.032520603,0.026379434,-0.019047782,-0.010278833,-0.0348435,-0.032840002,-0.012870318,0.0067001153,0.031852767,-0.0044606943,-0.016289337,-0.041318584,0.020615738,-0.03455314,0.0007857936,-0.01185405,-0.01758145,0.011549169,0.00018340476,0.020731883,0.009712626,0.012659806,0.013298604,-0.012187967,0.019773688,-0.005524147]	deep	The system uses a fixed, multi-level sort based on lead status counts for each Relationship Manager (RM). It does **not** use a weighted score, and users cannot change the sort order in the UI.\n\n### Sorting logic\n\nRMs are ordered by these metrics, in this exact priority, all in **ascending** order (fewer leads = higher in the list):\n\n1. **Client Accepted** – RMs with fewer “Client Accepted” leads appear first.  \n2. **In Progress** – If there’s a tie on accepted leads, the RM with fewer “In Progress” leads is ranked higher.  \n3. **Ready for Follow-up** – If still tied, the RM with fewer “Ready for Follow-up” leads is ranked higher.  \n4. **New** – Next, the RM with fewer “New” leads is ranked higher.  \n5. **Client Rejected** – Finally, if all above are equal, the RM with fewer “Client Rejected” leads is ranked higher.\n\nThe system applies these criteria sequentially as tie-breakers; it does not combine them into a single composite metric.\n\n### Configurability\n\n- This sort order is **predefined and fixed** for the lead performance view.\n- Supervisors and users **cannot** change the sort field or direction from the dashboard; any change would require configuration or code changes.\n\n### Data scope and visibility\n\n- Counts are based on **current, active leads** (e.g., leads in active campaigns), reflecting the RM’s current pipeline rather than all historical leads.\n- In some implementations, the view may be scoped to a period such as the **current month**, but by default it focuses on active leads as of now.\n- A supervisor only sees RMs **within their management hierarchy**; the list is limited to those RMs and their active lead data.\n- Search and pagination help navigate the list but do **not** affect the underlying sort logic.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Explain the system's logic for ordering Relationship Managers by their lead performance metrics in the dashboard.",\n  "expanded_question": "How does the system determine the order of Relationship Managers in the lead performance display? What performance metrics are used (and are they weighted), in what sequence or sort direction are RMs ranked, is this sorting fixed or can it be changed, what time period of lead data is considered, and are there any filters (like user role or lead status) that limit which RMs are shown?",\n  "business_entities": ["Relationship Managers (RMs)", "Lead Status Metrics", "Supervisor Dashboard"],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Lead Status by RM – Supervisor Dashboard (Sorting Logic)"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Supervisor Dashboard – Leads Widget (Configuration Document)"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Sorting Criteria for RM Lead Performance:** In the system’s lead performance view, Relationship Managers are sorted based on the counts of leads at various status stages in their pipeline. The sorting uses a predefined hierarchy of lead status metrics rather than a single composite score. Specifically, the list of RMs is ordered according to these priority criteria [1]:\\n\\n1. **Client Accepted Leads:** RMs are first sorted by the number of leads marked as \\"Client Accepted\\" (i.e. successfully converted leads). This is the primary performance indicator – the fewer the accepted leads, the higher (earlier) the RM appears in the list (the system uses an **ascending** order by this count) ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=Details%20Last%20Name%20Displays%20the,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)).\\n2. **In Progress Leads:** If two RMs have the same count of accepted leads, the tie is resolved by comparing their count of \\"In Progress\\" leads (active leads currently being worked). The RM with fewer in-progress leads is ranked higher in the list ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=customer%20Display%20No%20String%20Yes,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)).\\n3. **Ready for Follow-up Leads:** If a tie still exists, the system next compares the number of leads \\"Ready for Follow-up\\" for those RMs, again ordering them by the lower count first ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=JBR_Journey%20of%20Editing%20Customer%20Profile_V11_CCV10,So%2C%20RM%20with%20least%20number)).\\n4. **New Leads:** If RMs are still tied, the count of \\"New\\" (just acquired/uncontacted) leads is used, with fewer new leads placing an RM higher ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=JBR_Journey%20of%20Editing%20Customer%20Profile_V11_CCV10,So%2C%20RM%20with%20least%20number)).\\n5. **Client Rejected Leads:** Finally, if all the above metrics are equal, the tie-breaker is the count of \\"Client Rejected\\" leads (leads that did not convert), with lower rejection counts ranked higher ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=ranked%203%20respectively%202,ranked%201%20and%20so%20on)).\\n\\nThis tiered sorting means the system prioritizes the most positive outcome (client accepted) first when ranking RMs, and only looks at the next criteria if necessary. **No weighted averaging is applied** – instead, each metric is applied in sequence as a strict filter for sorting, rather than combining into a single score ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=Details%20Last%20Name%20Displays%20the,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)) ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=Capacity%20is%20the%20number%20of,120%20customers%20and%20Suresh%20is)). The sort direction for each metric is ascending (RMs with *lower* numbers go to the top of the list on that metric), which effectively highlights RMs with fewer conversions first in this default configuration ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=Details%20Last%20Name%20Displays%20the,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)). (This ordering is defined by design; it is essentially a performance **ranking** where a lower count in a higher-priority category indicates relatively better performance under the system’s criteria.)\\n\\n**Default vs. Configurable Behavior:** The above sorting logic is the system’s default and **fixed** behavior for the lead performance display. There is no user option in the UI to change the sort field or sort order – the list is always ordered by the sequence of metrics as described ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=Details%20Last%20Name%20Displays%20the,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)). In other words, Relationship Managers are automatically ranked using the preset criteria and order, and an end user (or supervisor) cannot re-sort this list by a different metric on the fly. Any change to this sorting approach would require a configuration or code change; the interface does not expose alternative sorting options for this particular widget by default. \\n\\n**Time Frame of Data:** The performance data being displayed is typically a snapshot of *current* lead activity rather than an all-time aggregate. Only **active leads** are counted – for example, leads associated with ongoing (active-status) campaigns are included in these metrics ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=1%20Personal%20Details%20Title%20Displays,Title%202)). This ensures the sorting reflects the **current pipeline status** of each RM. In many implementations, the lead counts are essentially as of today (real-time up to the current date). Some configurations further scope the data to a particular period; for instance, one bank’s dashboard shows lead counts per RM for the **current month** only ([file-4vDj4PyGVFHc3vPfUiieLd](file://file-4vDj4PyGVFHc3vPfUiieLd#:~:text=information%20that%20will%20be%20readily,to%20the%20Customer%20dashboard%20where)). By default, however, the system focuses on active leads at present, rather than historical or closed leads, so that the ranking is based on ongoing performance.\\n\\n**Filters and Permissions:** The lead performance list adheres to role-based visibility. A supervisor can only see the RMs that fall under **their management hierarchy** in this view ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=Capacity%20is%20the%20number%20of,120%20customers%20and%20Suresh%20is)). In other words, the widget will list **only the RMs reporting to that supervisor** (directly or indirectly), and not all RMs in the organization. Within that scope, all such RMs are included if they have lead data in the active campaigns. Additionally, only leads meeting the criteria (e.g. belonging to active campaigns) are considered for the counts, as noted. The interface also typically provides a search field and pagination to help navigate the list of RMs if the team is large ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=and%20so%20on%20For%20example%2C,Suresh%20is%20serving%20100%20customers)), but these do not alter the sorting logic – they simply aid in finding specific managers. The core ranking of RMs by lead performance remains governed by the fixed multi-level sort order described above.\\n\\n**Sources:** The sorting rules and behavior are based on the system’s design specifications for the Supervisor Dashboard’s lead performance widget ([file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU](file://file-M9GujXYkBzS1RxCuWdx2FU#:~:text=Details%20Last%20Name%20Displays%20the,HSBC%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2030)) ([file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG](file://file-EkN3TXLPgQjZW9huGbZCtG#:~:text=ranked%203%20respectively%202,ranked%201%20and%20so%20on)) and standard configuration of the leads module ([file-4vDj4PyGVFHc3vPfUiieLd](file://file-4vDj4PyGVFHc3vPfUiieLd#:~:text=information%20that%20will%20be%20readily,to%20the%20Customer%20dashboard%20where)).",\n  "sources": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Lead Status by RM – Supervisor Dashboard (Sorting Logic)"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Supervisor Dashboard – Leads Widget (Configuration Document)"}\n  ]\n}	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"fallback","confidence":0,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765950377684_divysfjqt","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_05070ed73de8c87e00694243a8b7708194b0926b765e25943c","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-17T05:53:43.174Z"}	resp_05070ed73de8c87e00694243a8b7708194b0926b765e25943c	t	2025-12-17 05:53:46.169	2025-12-17 05:53:46.169	1	f	\N
