\n   - Choose the **new agent** from the eligible agents list.\n   - Enter a **mandatory handover reason** (e.g. “Advisor resigned”, “Client requested change”).\n\n4. **Complete checklist / validations**\n   - Review any **scrutiny checklist** items (e.g. pending tasks, documentation).\n   - Mark items as completed / not applicable and add **remarks** where needed.\n\n5. **Submit for approval (maker-checker)**\n   - Click **Save/Confirm** to create the bulk handover request.\n   - A separate Operations **Checker** reviews and approves it.\n   - Once approved, all selected clients are reassigned to the new agent in one action.\n\nAll actions and status changes are captured in the **audit trail** (who initiated, who approved, when, and which clients/agents were involved).\n\n---\n\n## Option 2: Bulk handover via file upload\n\nUse this when the number of clients is very large (e.g. hundreds):\n\n1. **Prepare upload file**\n   - Create a CSV/Excel file with required fields (typically client ID and target agent).\n\n2. **Upload the file**\n   - Go to the **Batch Upload / Import** section.\n   - Choose the **Client Handover** upload type.\n   - Upload the file; the system processes each row and reassigns clients automatically.\n\n3. **Review results**\n   - Check the **upload summary / error log** for any failed records (e.g. invalid IDs).\n   - Successfully processed clients are reassigned without further manual steps.\n\nIn most implementations, this upload by an authorized Operations user is treated as **self-approved** (no separate checker step), but the entire upload event is fully **logged in the audit trail**.\n\n---\n\n## Key points\n\n- **Who can do it:** Only Operations / admin users with the right entitlements can perform bulk handovers; agents cannot.\n- **No per-client clicking:** Use **filters + Select All** in the Handover UI, or a **file upload**, to avoid selecting clients individually.\n- **Controls & compliance:**  \n  - Mandatory **reason** for every bulk transfer.  \n  - **Validations/checklists** before submission.  \n  - Full **audit trail** for both UI-based and file-based bulk transfers.\n\nThis is how an Operations user can transfer a large number of clients to a new agent in a single, controlled operation.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "Explain how an operations user can perform a bulk transfer of many client accounts to a new agent in one action (without selecting each client individually).",\n  "expanded_question": "In a wealth management platform, how can an Operations user reassign a large number of client records to a new agent in bulk (instead of updating clients one-by-one)? What bulk transfer methods are available, what roles/permissions and UI steps are involved, what filters or batch selection options exist (including any limits), and how are validations, audit logging, and related workflows handled during this mass reassignment?",\n  "business_entities": ["INVESTOR", "Validations", "remarks"],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Maybank_Handover and Delegation_V12_CCV10.pdf"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "SBI_Audit Trail_V10.pdf"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "# Bulk Client Reassignment to a New Agent\\n\\n**Bulk Transfer Overview:** An Operations user can reassign a large set of clients to a new agent using the platform’s bulk **Handover** functionality, rather than updating each client individually. This is typically done when an agent (relationship manager) leaves or when many clients need to be moved to a different agent at once (for example, upon a client’s request for a new advisor) [1]. The system provides dedicated tools to handle this in one action, ensuring the transfer of ownership is efficient, controlled, and audited [1].\\n\\n## Handover via Operations Interface (UI)\\n- **Accessing Handover:** The Operations user (back-office staff) navigates to the **Handover** screen through the operations or relationship management menu in the platform [1]. This interface is used to permanently assign or reassign multiple client accounts from one agent to another, usually in scenarios like an advisor’s exit or a bulk client realignment [1]. \\n- **Filtering and Selecting Clients:** On the Handover screen, the user can filter the list of clients by various criteria (for example, by the current agent’s name, client segment, or branch) to isolate the group of clients that need to be moved. All columns in the client list are filterable, allowing the Operations user to quickly obtain the exact subset of clients for transfer [1]. The user can then **select multiple clients at once** from the filtered results (e.g. by multi-select checkboxes or a “Select All” option), instead of having to pick clients one by one [1]. These selected clients are added to a “Selected Clients” list for the handover.\\n- **Choosing New Agent & Reason:** The Operations user next specifies the **incoming agent** who will take over those clients. The new agent is chosen from a dropdown list of eligible agents/advisors in the system (ensuring the agent is active and has the proper credentials to manage those clients) [1]. The user must also enter a **handover reason** – a mandatory field that documents why the clients are being reassigned (for example, *“Advisor resigned”* or *“Client requested change”*) [1]. This reason is recorded with the transaction for transparency.\\n- **Scrutiny Checklist & Remarks:** Before finalizing, the interface may present a **Scrutiny Checklist** of validations that need to be addressed prior to transfer [1]. For instance, it might list checks such as confirming any outstanding promises to the client have been fulfilled, that a last meeting or call report has been logged by the outgoing advisor, or that key client contact details are up to date. The Operations user reviews these items and updates each checklist entry’s status (e.g. marking them as *completed* or *not applicable*) and can add remarks or comments for each item as needed [1]. These remarks provide additional context or confirmation (for example, noting that the client was informed of the advisor change). Completing this checklist ensures all necessary prerequisites are met before the clients are handed over.\\n- **Submitting for Approval:** Once the Operations user has selected the clients, chosen the new agent, provided a reason, and satisfied all validations, they click **Save/Confirm** to initiate the bulk transfer request [1]. At this point, the system will typically route the handover request for authorization by a second user – an Operations **Checker** – as part of a maker-checker control process [1]. The request remains in a pending state until the checker reviews and approves it. (The checker can usually view the details of the transfer, including which clients are moving and the stated reason, before authorizing.) Upon approval, the reassignment of all selected clients to the new agent is finalized in the system.\\n\\n## Bulk Reassignment via File Upload\\n- **Batch Upload Option:** For an extremely large number of clients, the platform provides a file-based bulk upload feature. An Operations user with appropriate rights can go to the batch upload/import section of the system and select the **“Client Handover”** upload type [1]. They then upload a file (typically in CSV or Excel format) that contains the list of client identifiers and the target new agent for each of those clients. This approach allows dozens or even hundreds of client records to be reassigned in one go by processing a single file, avoiding the need to manually select clients through the UI.\\n- **Processing the File:** Once the file (containing all required details for the transfer) is uploaded, the system processes the bulk handover. It will read each client entry and reassign that client’s ownership to the specified new agent automatically [1]. The platform provides feedback on the upload outcome – for example, it may show an **error log** or summary report of the batch operation [1]. Any records that failed to transfer (due to issues like invalid client IDs or an agent mismatch) would be listed here, so the Operations user can address them separately. All successfully processed clients are now reassigned to the new agent without further manual intervention.\\n- **No Manual Authorization Needed:** Handover via file upload generally does **not require a separate checker authorization step** – the act of uploading the file by an authorized Operations user is considered the approval in itself [1]. In other words, the system assumes that the bulk file has been prepared and vetted according to internal policies, so it applies the changes immediately upon upload. The absence of a second approval streamlines the process for large transfers. (The trade-off is that organizations typically limit this capability to highly trusted operations roles.) The bulk upload is fully logged, however, ensuring that there is a record of who executed the upload and when, in lieu of the interactive approval step [2].\\n\\n## Roles and Authorization Controls\\n- **Operations-Only Feature:** Bulk client reassignment is restricted to Operations personnel or other administrative users. Front-line advisors/agents **do not have the permission** to reassign clients on their own in bulk. This ensures that mass reassignments go through proper channels. Only a user in the Operations role (with the appropriate entitlement in the system) can access the Handover screen or initiate a client transfer upload [1]. The platform’s user entitlements thus protect client data by preventing unauthorized transfers.\\n- **Maker-Checker Workflow:** The interactive Handover process is governed by a **maker-checker** (dual control) mechanism. The Operations user who initiates the handover (the “Maker”) cannot finalize it alone; a separate Operations user with approval rights (the “Checker”) must review and **authorize** the transfer request before it takes effect [1]. This dual approval process