Cart workflow  \n\nFor each, it identifies where process deadlocks or supervisor visibility gaps can occur, and how to mitigate them.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Validations & Warnings (Risk Controls)\n\n**System logic**\n\n- **Soft stops**  \n  - Trigger warnings (e.g., product risk slightly above client risk profile).  \n  - RM can override with justification; system logs deviation.  \n  - On submission, such orders are escalated for higher approval (e.g., Circle/Zonal head, then Supervisor).\n\n- **Hard stops**  \n  - Trigger when critical rules are breached (e.g., product far outside risk profile, missing mandatory data).  \n  - System blocks transaction until the issue is resolved.  \n  - Hard-stop and soft-stop issues are shown in the Product Cart deviation overlay (e.g., “Guardian details required for minor nominee”).\n\n**Collision during abrupt RM handover**\n\n- Orders with **acknowledged soft-stop warnings** created by the outgoing RM:\n  - Still valid and visible; they carry the logged deviations forward.\n  - Require supervisor review and approval as usual.\n\n- Orders with **unresolved hard stops**:\n  - Remain blocked; cannot progress regardless of RM status.\n\n**Potential deadlocks / gaps**\n\n- **Deadlock**:  \n  - Hard-stop conditions left unresolved when RM exits (e.g., missing guardian details, mandatory KYC fields).  \n  - No one updates the order → it remains permanently blocked.\n\n- **Visibility gap for Supervisor**:  \n  - If the supervisor does not systematically review deviation overlays for the departed RM’s clients, accepted risks and pending requirements may be missed.\n\n**Controls & recovery actions**\n\n- Supervisor (or operations) must:\n  - Run a **sweep of all orders** for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n  - Review Product Cart deviation overlays for each pending order.  \n  - Ensure:\n    - Soft-stop deviations are revalidated by the new RM and explicitly approved by the supervisor.  \n    - Hard-stop issues are either:\n      - Resolved by the new RM/ops (e.g., capture missing data, upload documents), or  \n      - The non-compliant product is removed/cancelled.\n\n- Governance:  \n  - Make “review all deviations for outgoing RM’s book” a mandatory off‑boarding checklist item.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Supervisor Approval Process\n\n**System logic**\n\n- All investment orders require supervisor (or designated approver) authorization before execution.\n- Once submitted by an RM, orders enter **“Pending Approval”** and appear in the **Supervisor Approval screen**.\n- Supervisor can:\n  - View all pending orders.  \n  - Search/filter by Order Number, Security/Scheme, Customer Name, Transaction Type, and **RM Name**.\n\n**Collision during abrupt RM handover**\n\n- Pending approvals created by the outgoing RM:\n  - Remain in the supervisor’s queue even if the RM is later deactivated.  \n  - Are still executable; they do not need to be re-entered by the new RM.\n\n**Potential deadlocks / gaps**\n\n- **Visibility gap**:\n  - If supervisors rely only on the **RM Name** filter and the outgoing RM is removed or not obvious in filters, some pending approvals may be overlooked.\n  - Intermediate approvers (e.g., Circle/Zonal heads) being unavailable can stall approvals.\n\n- **Process deadlock**:\n  - Orders stuck in “Pending Approval” beyond normal timelines because:\n    - The intermediate approver is absent, and  \n    - No escalation or alternate approver is triggered.\n\n**Controls & recovery actions**\n\n- Supervisor actions:\n  - On RM exit, run a **pending-approvals report** filtered by:\n    - Outgoing RM, and  \n    - Client or order number (not just RM filter).\n  - Review and act on all such orders:\n    - Approve/reject, or  \n    - Escalate to higher authority if intermediate approver is unavailable.\n\n- Escalation design:\n  - Define **age-based escalation**: if an order remains in “Pending Approval” beyond a threshold, it is:\n    - Auto-flagged to the next-level approver, or  \n    - Reassigned to another supervisor.\n\n- Governance:\n  - Daily monitoring of:\n    - Ageing approvals, and  \n    - Orders with risk deviations awaiting approval.  \n  - All approvals/overrides logged for audit.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Performance Projection Tools\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Performance Projection allows RMs to simulate future performance of securities/portfolios under various scenarios (optimistic/base/pessimistic).\n- It is **analytical only**:\n  - Does not create or block transactions.  \n  - Uses underlying market/portfolio data; projections are reproducible.\n\n**Collision during abrupt RM handover**\n\n- The outgoing RM may have:\n  - Run projections to support recommendations.  \n  - Shared specific scenarios or reports with the client.\n\n**Potential deadlocks / gaps**\n\n- **No technical deadlock**:\n  - The tool does not hold transactional state; it cannot block orders.\n\n- **Knowledge/visibility gap**:\n  - New RM and supervisor may not know:\n    - What projections were shown to the client.  \n    - What strategy or expectations were set.\n\n**Controls & recovery actions**\n\n- Ensure that:\n  - Any **saved projection reports** or key outputs are attached to the client record or logged in client notes.\n  - New RM can re-run projections on the same portfolio/proposed investments.\n\n- Supervisor role:\n  - Verify that the new RM reviews prior projections and aligns communication so the client experiences continuity in advice.\n\n- Governance:\n  - Include “attach or document key projections used in client proposals” in advisory process standards.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Mutual Fund Order & Product Cart Workflow\n\n**System logic**\n\n- RMs use the **Mutual Funds module** and **Product Cart** to:\n  - Select products.  \n  - Capture client/order details.  \n  - Address validations (risk, eligibility, documentation).  \n  - Obtain client authentication (e.g., OTP).  \n  - Submit orders for approval.\n\n- The system:\n  - Lists deviations and requirements in the Product Cart (min/max amounts, nominee/guardian, risk deviations, etc.).  \n  - Allows **orders to be saved in a “Pending State”** if not fully completed/submitted.\n\n- Certain transaction types (e.g., physical-mode redemptions/switches) require **mandatory document upload** before submission.\n\n**Collision during abrupt RM handover**\n\n- Outgoing RM may have:\n  - Draft orders saved in **Pending State**.  \n  - Orders requiring document upload not yet completed.  \n  - Orders where client OTP/authentication was initiated but not completed.\n\n**Potential deadlocks / gaps**\n\n- **Deadlocks**:\n  1. **Pending State orders**:\n     - No one picks them up after RM exit → client instructions remain unexecuted.\n  2. **Mandatory documentation not uploaded**:\n     - Orders cannot be submitted; they remain blocked indefinitely.\n  3. **Expired or incomplete OTP/authentication**:\n     - Transaction cannot proceed without re-authentication.\n\n- **Visibility gap**:\n  - If there is no systematic retrieval of:\n    - All “Order(s) in Pending State” for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n    - All orders flagged with “document upload is mandatory”.\n\n**Controls & recovery actions**\n\n- Supervisor / operations actions:\n  - On RM exit, extract:\n    - All **Pending State** orders for that RM’s clients.  \n    - All orders with **mandatory document upload** flags.  \n  - Reassign these to the new RM.\n\n- New RM actions:\n  - Review each pending order:\n    - Confirm with the client whether to proceed, modify, or cancel.  \n    - Complete missing data and documentation.  \n    - Re-initiate client authentication (OTP) where required.\n\n- Governance:\n  - Make “sweep Pending State bucket and documentation-required orders” a standard step in RM off‑boarding.  \n  - Ensure Product Cart deviation overlays are used as the single source of truth for unresolved issues.\n\n---\n\n## Integrated View: Collision of the Four Workflows\n\nWhen an RM leaves abruptly, these workflows can intersect in ways that create risk. The key combined failure modes and mitigations are:\n\n### A. Combined Process Deadlocks\n\n1. **Order with hard-stop + pending documentation + RM exit**\n   - Hard-stop blocks submission; missing document prevents resolution; RM is gone.\n   - Mitigation:\n     - Supervisor/ops identify such orders via Product Cart overlays and documentation flags.  \n     - New RM or ops obtains and uploads documents or cancels the order after client confirmation.\n\n2. **Order with soft-stop deviation + stuck in approval chain + RM exit**\n   - Deviation accepted by old RM; order in “Pending Approval”; intermediate approver unavailable.\n   - Mitigation:\n     - Age-based escalation to higher approver.  \n     - Supervisor runs exception report for all pending approvals with deviations for the outgoing RM.\n\n3. **Draft order in Pending State + client expecting execution**\n   - Client believes instruction was given; order never submitted due to RM exit.\n   - Mitigation:\n     - Mandatory sweep of Pending State bucket.  \n     - New RM contacts client to confirm and complete or cancel.\n\n### B. Supervisor Visibility Gaps\n\n- **By RM filter only**:\n  - If supervisor relies solely on RM Name filter and the outgoing RM is deactivated, some orders may not be surfaced.\n- **Advisory context loss**:\n  - Supervisor/new RM may not see what projections or strategies were discussed with the client.\n\n**Mitigation**\n\n- Use multiple dimensions for retrieval:\n  - Client ID, order number, transaction type, and RM ID.  \n  - Dedicated reports for:\n    - Pending approvals.  \n    - Pending State orders.  \n    - Orders with deviations or mandatory documents.\n\n- Ensure advisory context:\n  - Projection outputs and key recommendations attached to client records.\n\n---\n\n## Governance, Escalation, and Controls\n\n**1. Off‑boarding checklist for outgoing RM**\n\n- Reassign all:\n  - Clients, prospects, and leads via Handover functionality.  \n  - In-flight orders (Pending Approval, Pending State) to new RM/supervisor.\n- Generate and review:\n  - Report of all orders with:\n    - Hard/soft-stop deviations.  \n    - Mandatory documentation flags.  \n    - Pending client actions (e.g., OTP).\n\n**2. On‑boarding checklist for incoming RM**\n\n- Provide:\n  - Full list of inherited clients and their pending items.  \n  - Access to:\n    - Supervisor Approval view (as needed).  \n    - Product Cart details and deviation overlays.  \n    - Historical projections and client notes.\n\n**3. Supervisor / Operations responsibilities**\n\n- Daily/transition-period controls:\n  - Sweep:\n    - Pending Approval queue.  \n    - Pending State bucket.  \n    - Orders with deviations or mandatory documents.\n  - Use age-based dashboards to escalate:\n    - Stale approvals.  \n    - Long-pending client inputs.\n\n- Audit & logging:\n  - Ensure all:\n    - Reassignments, overrides, and escalations are logged.  \n    - Actions around the handover period are auditable.\n\n**4. Client communication**\n\n- Inform clients of:\n  - RM change and new point of contact.  \n  - Status of any pending instructions.  \n- Confirm:\n  - Whether to proceed with inherited pending orders.  \n  - Any changes to recommendations, based on fresh projections if needed.\n\n---\n\nBy explicitly coordinating these four workflows—validations/warnings, supervisor approvals, performance projections, and mutual fund/Product Cart processing—the institution can:\n\n- Avoid process deadlocks (blocked orders, stalled approvals, abandoned drafts).  \n- Close supervisor visibility gaps (missed deviations, unseen pending items).  \n- Preserve advisory continuity (consistent strategy and expectations for the client).  \n\nThis integrated approach materially reduces operational and compliance risk during abrupt RM handovers in the wealth management context.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "To develop a strategy ensuring business continuity when a Relationship Manager (RM) leaves abruptly, by examining how the system manages four overlapping workflows (validations/warnings, supervisor approvals, performance projections, and mutual fund order processing) and identifying any process deadlocks or visibility issues for the supervisor.",\n  "expanded_question": "How can we create an operational continuity plan for an abrupt RM handover, focusing on how the system’s logic handles the overlap of four workflows (validations & warnings, supervisor approval processes, performance projections, and mutual fund order/product cart workflows) and pinpointing potential process deadlocks or supervisor visibility gaps, along with necessary recovery actions, escalations, and governance controls?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Validations and Warning",\n    "Supervisor Approval screen",\n    "Performance Projection",\n    "Mutual Funds",\n    "product cart"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Handover and Delegation (v10) - Internal Product Document"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Risk & Authorization (v11)"},\n    {"id": "3", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Supervisor Approval Process"},\n    {"id": "4", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Performance Projection Feature"},\n    {"id": "5", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Product Cart Validations"},\n    {"id": "6", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Documentation Requirements"},\n    {"id": "7", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Pending Orders Workflow"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Operational Continuity Strategy for Abrupt RM Handover**\\n\\nWhen a Relationship Manager exits unexpectedly, the system must seamlessly transfer all ongoing activities and client data to maintain service continuity. The first step is to immediately reassign the departing RM’s clients, prospects, and leads to an active RM (or a supervisor) using the platform’s handover functionality. This *Handover* process permanently remaps each customer record and pipeline item to the new owner, ensuring no client is left unmanaged and formally establishing who is responsible for day-to-day management going forward ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=1,nature%2C%20then%20Delegation%20is%20used)) ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=4,from%20the%20Relationship%20Handover%20screen)). Alongside the reallocation of clients, a thorough review of in-flight workflows is necessary to avoid any stalled transactions or oversight lapses. Four critical concurrent workflows require special attention during the handover:\\n\\n1. **Validations & Warnings (Risk Controls)** – The wealth platform enforces both *soft stops* and *hard stops* to uphold compliance and suitability rules during order entry. Soft-stop validations trigger warning pop-ups (for example, if a chosen product’s risk level is slightly above the client’s risk profile) that the RM can acknowledge and override with justification ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=7,will%20go%20first%20to%20Circle)). In these cases, the system logs the deviation and, upon order submission, automatically escalates the order for higher approval – first to a senior manager (e.g. Circle or Zonal head) and then to the Supervisor for final sign-off ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=8,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). By contrast, hard-stop validations indicate a critical breach (such as a product far outside the client’s risk tolerance or missing mandatory details) and **block the transaction entirely**, preventing the RM from proceeding until the issue is resolved ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=9,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). During an abrupt handover, any soft-stop warnings that were acknowledged by the outgoing RM become important flags for the incoming RM and supervisors. The system’s Product Cart interface highlights all such deviations in an order overlay – listing any hard-stop issues (e.g. “Guardian details required for minor nominee”) and soft-stop warnings associated with that transaction ([file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA](file://file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA#:~:text=Product%20Cart%20,Not%20Applicabl%20e%20Example%3A%20Guardian)). As part of the continuity plan, the Supervisor should review these deviation lists for any pending orders the former RM was handling, to ensure that accepted risks or pending requirements won’t be overlooked. If a hard-stop condition was left unresolved by the time of handover, that order cannot move forward – creating a potential deadlock. The resolution would be to have the new RM or an operations user provide the required information or documentation to clear the hard stop, or else remove the non-compliant product from the order. In summary, the continuity strategy calls for **capturing and transferring all validation outcomes**: warnings need to be revalidated by the new RM and approved by the supervisor, and no order should remain blocked due to an unmet hard-stop condition.\\n\\n2. **Supervisor Approval Process** – Every investment order initiated by an RM must ultimately be authorized by a supervisor (or designated approver) before execution. When an RM submits an order, it enters a *“Pending Approval”* state and becomes visible in the Supervisor’s approval queue ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=SBI_Journey%20from%20Order%20Placement%20till,in%20the%20top%20panel)) ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=Supervisor%20Approval%20screen%20Screen%3A%20Supervisor,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). The Supervisor uses the **Supervisor Approval screen** (accessible via a dedicated icon in the application) to view and process all pending orders. On this screen, orders awaiting approval are listed and can be searched by various criteria such as Order Number, Security/Scheme, or Customer Name ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=3,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). Notably, the interface also allows filtering by *Transaction Type* and by *RM Name*, so a supervisor can display orders associated with a particular RM under their oversight ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=5,Customer%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2050)). In an abrupt handover scenario, this filtering mechanism introduces a **visibility consideration**: if a departing RM’s orders are still pending approval, they may initially be indexed under that RM’s name. The continuity plan should ensure that supervisors actively search by client or order number if needed, rather than relying solely on the RM filter, especially if the outgoing RM’s profile is inactivated or removed from the reporting hierarchy. The system should not drop or hide pending approvals even if the RM who created them is no longer active; those orders remain in the queue until acted upon. To prevent any *process deadlock*, the organization can define an escalation timeline for approvals – for example, if an order sits in “Pending Approval” beyond a certain cutoff (perhaps due to an intermediate approver like a department head being unavailable), the next higher authority or the supervisor can intervene to approve or reroute it. This ensures that orders do not languish unapproved due to the absence of the originating RM or any approver in the chain. All approval decisions and any overrides (such as approving an order that had a risk warning) are logged for audit. As a governance control, the Supervisor taking over should run a report of all pending orders by that outgoing RM and verify their status. Any order that was submitted by the old RM will follow the normal authorization flow – meaning the new RM typically does *not* need to re-enter it, but the supervisor should communicate with the incoming RM about the context of that order (especially if there were risk deviations or special client instructions attached).\\n\\n3. **Performance Projection Tools** – The platform provides a *Performance Projection* feature that allows RMs to simulate and view the potential future performance of selected securities or portfolios under various scenarios (e.g. optimistic, current, and pessimistic market conditions) ([file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9](file://file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9#:~:text=7.%20Performance%20Projection%20,the%20calculator%20on%20Max%20Drawdown)). RMs often use this functionality during product selection to illustrate potential returns and risks to clients. While this workflow is more analytical (it doesn’t create a transaction by itself), it runs in parallel with the order-building process and can inform an RM’s recommendations. In the context of an RM handover, the continuity strategy should ensure that any insights or materials generated from these projections are not lost. Since the projections are based on underlying data (prices, model portfolios, etc.) and are reproducible, a new RM stepping in can re-run the same simulations on the client’s portfolio or proposed investments. However, if the departing RM had saved any specific projection reports or used them in a client proposal, those should be archived or made accessible to the new RM. There is minimal risk of system deadlock with the projection tool itself (as it doesn’t hold state that would block processes), but there is a *knowledge transfer aspect*: the incoming RM should be briefed on any performance analysis the client was shown or any strategy being pursued. Governance measures can include attaching any generated projection reports to the client’s record or notes. This way, the Supervisor and new RM have full visi	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":