 recovery actions to maintain continuity.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Validations & Warnings (Risk Controls)\n\n**System logic**\n\n- **Soft stops**  \n  - Trigger warnings (e.g., product risk slightly above client risk profile).  \n  - RM can override with justification; system logs deviation.  \n  - On submission, such orders are routed for higher approval (senior manager → Supervisor).\n\n- **Hard stops**  \n  - Trigger when critical rules are breached (e.g., missing mandatory data, product far outside risk profile).  \n  - System blocks the transaction until the condition is resolved.  \n  - These appear in the Product Cart deviation list (e.g., “Guardian details required for minor nominee”).\n\n**Collision during abrupt handover**\n\n- Soft-stop orders may have been acknowledged by the outgoing RM but are still:\n  - In the Product Cart, or  \n  - In the approval chain.\n- Hard-stop orders may be left unresolved in the Product Cart.\n\n**Potential deadlocks**\n\n- **Hard-stop unresolved at handover**  \n  - Order is permanently blocked until someone supplies missing data or removes the product.\n- **Soft-stop acknowledged but not yet fully approved**  \n  - Order is stuck in the approval chain if no one picks it up.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- If the supervisor only looks at “by RM” views and the outgoing RM is deactivated, they may miss:\n  - Orders with unresolved hard stops in the Product Cart.  \n  - Orders with soft-stop deviations already accepted by the old RM.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- As part of handover, Supervisor/ops must:\n  - Pull a **deviation list** from Product Cart for all clients of the outgoing RM.  \n  - Ensure:\n    - Hard-stop items are either completed (data/documents added) or the product is removed.  \n    - Soft-stop deviations are re-reviewed by the new RM and, where required, re-escalated/approved.\n- Policy: **No order remains blocked solely because the originating RM left.**\n\n---\n\n## 2. Supervisor Approval Process\n\n**System logic**\n\n- All submitted orders go to **“Pending Approval”** and appear in the **Supervisor Approval screen**.  \n- Supervisor can:\n  - View all pending orders.  \n  - Filter/search by Order No., Scheme/Security, Customer Name, Transaction Type, and RM Name.  \n- Orders remain in the queue until explicitly approved/rejected; they are not auto-dropped if the RM is deactivated.\n\n**Collision during abrupt handover**\n\n- Orders created by the outgoing RM may be:\n  - In “Pending Approval” with deviations.  \n  - Awaiting intermediate approvals (e.g., Circle/Zonal head) before supervisor sign-off.\n\n**Potential deadlocks**\n\n- **Approver unavailable** (e.g., intermediate approver or supervisor absent) → order remains in “Pending Approval” indefinitely.\n- **RM filter dependency**  \n  - If the supervisor relies on RM-based filters and the outgoing RM is removed from hierarchy, some pending orders may not be surfaced through that filter.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Orders still tied to the old RM’s ID may:\n  - Not appear under the new RM.  \n  - Be overlooked if the supervisor does not search by client/order.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- On RM exit, Supervisor/ops must:\n  - Run a **pending approvals sweep**:\n    - Filter by outgoing RM (if still visible).  \n    - Additionally search by **client** and **order number** to ensure nothing is missed.\n  - Define **escalation timelines**:\n    - If an order remains in “Pending Approval” beyond X days, it is escalated to the next authority or reassigned.\n- Orders submitted by the old RM:\n  - Continue through the normal approval flow; re-entry is not required.  \n  - Supervisor must brief the new RM on any orders with risk deviations or special client instructions.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Performance Projection\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Performance Projection is a **simulation/analytics tool**:\n  - Runs scenarios (optimistic/base/pessimistic) on securities/portfolios.  \n  - Does not itself create or block transactions.\n\n**Collision during abrupt handover**\n\n- Outgoing RM may have:\n  - Used projections to build a proposal.  \n  - Shared specific scenarios with the client.\n\n**Potential deadlocks**\n\n- None at the system level:  \n  - The tool is stateless with respect to order processing; it does not hold orders or approvals.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- **Knowledge gap**, not a technical gap:\n  - New RM and Supervisor may not know what projections or strategies were presented to the client.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- Ensure any **saved projection reports** or key outputs are:\n  - Attached to the client record or notes.  \n  - Accessible to the new RM and Supervisor.\n- New RM can **re-run projections** on the same portfolio to:\n  - Validate continuity of advice.  \n  - Maintain consistent communication with the client.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Mutual Fund Orders & Product Cart\n\n**System logic**\n\n- RMs use the **Mutual Funds module + Product Cart** to:\n  - Select products, capture details, run validations, and submit orders.  \n  - See deviations (hard/soft stops, missing data, min/max amounts, nominee/guardian requirements, etc.).\n- Orders can be:\n  - **Saved in “Pending State”** (partially completed, not yet submitted).  \n  - Marked with **mandatory documentation** flags (e.g., physical mode transactions requiring uploads).  \n  - Subject to **client authentication** (e.g., OTP) at submission.\n\n**Collision during abrupt handover**\n\n- Outgoing RM may leave:\n  - Draft orders in **Pending State**.  \n  - Orders in Product Cart with unresolved deviations.  \n  - Orders awaiting document upload or client OTP.\n\n**Potential deadlocks**\n\n- **Pending State orders**  \n  - Remain incomplete if no one picks them up; client instructions may effectively stall.\n- **Mandatory document not uploaded**  \n  - System will not allow submission; order is blocked until document is provided.\n- **Expired or unused OTP**  \n  - Authentication step must be re-initiated; otherwise, order cannot proceed.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- If there is no systematic sweep of:\n  - “Order(s) in Pending State” for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n  - Product Cart entries with mandatory-document flags.\n- These items may not appear in the standard approval queue and can be missed.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- On RM exit, Supervisor/ops must:\n  - Retrieve **all Pending State orders** for the outgoing RM’s client base.  \n  - Assign them to the new RM for:\n    - Client re-confirmation.  \n    - Completion and submission or cancellation.\n  - Review Product Cart for:\n    - **Mandatory document flags** and ensure documents are obtained/uploaded.  \n    - Any pending client authentication; arrange for **fresh OTP** and client contact.\n- Policy: No client instruction remains in a draft state without explicit decision (proceed/cancel) after handover.\n\n---\n\n## Cross-Workflow Collision: Where Deadlocks and Gaps Arise\n\nWhen these four workflows run concurrently around an abrupt RM exit, the main risk points are:\n\n1. **Orders blocked by validations but not owned by anyone**\n   - Hard stops in Product Cart with no RM to fix them.  \n   - Soft-stop deviations acknowledged by the old RM but not yet fully approved.\n\n2. **Orders stuck in approval queues**\n   - “Pending Approval” items where:\n     - The intermediate approver is absent, or  \n     - The supervisor does not see them due to RM-based filtering.\n\n3. **Draft orders and documentation gaps**\n   - “Pending State” orders never completed.  \n   - Mandatory documents not uploaded.  \n   - OTP/authentication steps not re-initiated.\n\n4. **Advisory continuity gaps**\n   - New RM unaware of prior projections and proposals, leading to inconsistent advice.\n\n---\n\n## Operational Continuity Framework\n\n### A. Deadlock Prevention & Recovery Actions\n\n- **Queue sweeps on RM exit**\n  - Supervisor/ops must systematically review:\n    - Product Cart deviations (hard/soft stops).  \n    - “Pending Approval” queue (by RM, client, order).  \n    - “Order(s) in Pending State” bucket.  \n    - Orders flagged for mandatory documents or client action.\n- **Resolution actions**\n  - Hard stops: complete missing data/docs or remove product.  \n  - Soft stops: new RM revalidates; Supervisor confirms/overrides.  \n  - Pending approvals: escalate or reassign if ageing beyond threshold.  \n  - Pending drafts: new RM contacts client to proceed or cancel.\n\n### B. Supervisor Visibility Controls\n\n- Use **multiple search dimensions**:\n  - Not only “by RM”, but also by **client ID**, **order number**, **transaction type**.  \n- Generate **exception reports**:\n  - All pending activities linked to the outgoing RM (orders, applications, service requests).  \n- Rely on:\n  - Product Cart overlays for deviations and required actions.  \n  - Audit trails tagged by creator ID and client ID.\n\n### C. Escalation Paths\n\n- Define clear rules such as:\n  - If an order is in “Pending Approval” > X days → escalate to next-level approver.  \n  - If a hard stop or mandatory document remains unresolved > Y days → Supervisor decides to cancel or formally defer with client consent.\n- Use alerts/notifications for:\n  - Ageing approvals.  \n  - Ageing pending drafts.  \n  - Orders awaiting client action (e.g., OTP, documents).\n\n### D. Governance & Handover Checklists\n\n- **RM off-boarding checklist**\n  - Confirm:\n    - All clients reassigned via Handover functionality.  \n    - All pending orders identified and assigned.  \n    - All deviations and mandatory-document flags reviewed.\n- **New RM onboarding for that book**\n  - Provide:\n    - List of all pending and in-flight items.  \n    - Access to any saved performance projections and client notes.  \n- **Audit & oversight**\n  - Use system logs to verify:\n    - Who reassigned orders.  \n    - Who overrode validations.  \n    - That no orders were executed without proper approvals during the transition.\n\n---\n\nBy explicitly managing these four workflows together—validations, approvals, projections, and mutual fund/Product Cart processing—the organization can:\n\n- Avoid process deadlocks (blocked orders with no owner or approver).  \n- Close supervisor visibility gaps (no “orphaned” pending items).  \n- Preserve advisory continuity for clients despite an abrupt RM change.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "To develop a strategy ensuring business continuity when a Relationship Manager (RM) leaves abruptly, by examining how the system manages four overlapping workflows (validations/warnings, supervisor approvals, performance projections, and mutual fund order processing) and identifying any process deadlocks or visibility issues for the supervisor.",\n  "expanded_question": "How can we create an operational continuity plan for an abrupt RM handover, focusing on how the system’s logic handles the overlap of four workflows (validations & warnings, supervisor approval processes, performance projections, and mutual fund order/product cart workflows) and pinpointing potential process deadlocks or supervisor visibility gaps, along with necessary recovery actions, escalations, and governance controls?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Validations and Warning",\n    "Supervisor Approval screen",\n    "Performance Projection",\n    "Mutual Funds",\n    "product cart"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Handover and Delegation (v10) - Internal Product Document"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Risk & Authorization (v11)"},\n    {"id": "3", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Supervisor Approval Process"},\n    {"id": "4", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Performance Projection Feature"},\n    {"id": "5", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Product Cart Validations"},\n    {"id": "6", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Documentation Requirements"},\n    {"id": "7", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Pending Orders Workflow"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Operational Continuity Strategy for Abrupt RM Handover**\\n\\nWhen a Relationship Manager exits unexpectedly, the system must seamlessly transfer all ongoing activities and client data to maintain service continuity. The first step is to immediately reassign the departing RM’s clients, prospects, and leads to an active RM (or a supervisor) using the platform’s handover functionality. This *Handover* process permanently remaps each customer record and pipeline item to the new owner, ensuring no client is left unmanaged and formally establishing who is responsible for day-to-day management going forward ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=1,nature%2C%20then%20Delegation%20is%20used)) ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=4,from%20the%20Relationship%20Handover%20screen)). Alongside the reallocation of clients, a thorough review of in-flight workflows is necessary to avoid any stalled transactions or oversight lapses. Four critical concurrent workflows require special attention during the handover:\\n\\n1. **Validations & Warnings (Risk Controls)** – The wealth platform enforces both *soft stops* and *hard stops* to uphold compliance and suitability rules during order entry. Soft-stop validations trigger warning pop-ups (for example, if a chosen product’s risk level is slightly above the client’s risk profile) that the RM can acknowledge and override with justification ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=7,will%20go%20first%20to%20Circle)). In these cases, the system logs the deviation and, upon order submission, automatically escalates the order for higher approval – first to a senior manager (e.g. Circle or Zonal head) and then to the Supervisor for final sign-off ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=8,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). By contrast, hard-stop validations indicate a critical breach (such as a product far outside the client’s risk tolerance or missing mandatory details) and **block the transaction entirely**, preventing the RM from proceeding until the issue is resolved ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=9,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). During an abrupt handover, any soft-stop warnings that were acknowledged by the outgoing RM become important flags for the incoming RM and supervisors. The system’s Product Cart interface highlights all such deviations in an order overlay – listing any hard-stop issues (e.g. “Guardian details required for minor nominee”) and soft-stop warnings associated with that transaction ([file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA](file://file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA#:~:text=Product%20Cart%20,Not%20Applicabl%20e%20Example%3A%20Guardian)). As part of the continuity plan, the Supervisor should review these deviation lists for any pending orders the former RM was handling, to ensure that accepted risks or pending requirements won’t be overlooked. If a hard-stop condition was left unresolved by the time of handover, that order cannot move forward – creating a potential deadlock. The resolution would be to have the new RM or an operations user provide the required information or documentation to clear the hard stop, or else remove the non-compliant product from the order. In summary, the continuity strategy calls for **capturing and transferring all validation outcomes**: warnings need to be revalidated by the new RM and approved by the supervisor, and no order should remain blocked due to an unmet hard-stop condition.\\n\\n2. **Supervisor Approval Process** – Every investment order initiated by an RM must ultimately be authorized by a supervisor (or designated approver) before execution. When an RM submits an order, it enters a *“Pending Approval”* state and becomes visible in the Supervisor’s approval queue ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=SBI_Journey%20from%20Order%20Placement%20till,in%20the%20top%20panel)) ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=Supervisor%20Approval%20screen%20Screen%3A%20Supervisor,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). The Supervisor uses the **Supervisor Approval screen** (accessible via a dedicated icon in the application) to view and process all pending orders. On this screen, orders awaiting approval are listed and can be searched by various criteria such as Order Number, Security/Scheme, or Customer Name ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=3,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). Notably, the interface also allows filtering by *Transaction Type* and by *RM Name*, so a supervisor can display orders associated with a particular RM under their oversight ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=5,Customer%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2050)). In an abrupt handover scenario, this filtering mechanism introduces a **visibility consideration**: if a departing RM’s orders are still pending approval, they may initially be indexed under that RM’s name. The continuity plan should ensure that supervisors actively search by client or order number if needed, rather than relying solely on the RM filter, especially if the outgoing RM’s profile is inactivated or removed from the reporting hierarchy. The system should not drop or hide pending approvals even if the RM who created them is no longer active; those orders remain in the queue until acted upon. To prevent any *process deadlock*, the organization can define an escalation timeline for approvals – for example, if an order sits in “Pending Approval” beyond a certain cutoff (perhaps due to an intermediate approver like a department head being unavailable), the next higher authority or the supervisor can intervene to approve or reroute it. This ensures that orders do not languish unapproved due to the absence of the originating RM or any approver in the chain. All approval decisions and any overrides (such as approving an order that had a risk warning) are logged for audit. As a governance control, the Supervisor taking over should run a report of all pending orders by that outgoing RM and verify their status. Any order that was submitted by the old RM will follow the normal authorization flow – meaning the new RM typically does *not* need to re-enter it, but the supervisor should communicate with the incoming RM about the context of that order (especially if there were risk deviations or special client instructions attached).\\n\\n3. **Performance Projection Tools** – The platform provides a *Performance Projection* feature that allows RMs to simulate and view the potential future performance of selected securities or portfolios under various scenarios (e.g. optimistic, current, and pessimistic market conditions) ([file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9](file://file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9#:~:text=7.%20Performance%20Projection%20,the%20calculator%20on%20Max%20Drawdown)). RMs often use this functionality during product selection to illustrate potential returns and risks to clients. While this workflow is more analytical (it doesn’t create a transaction by itself), it runs in parallel with the order-building process and can inform an RM’s recommendations. In the context of an RM handover, the continuity strategy should ensure that any insights or materials generated from these projections are not lost. Since the projections are based on underlying data (prices, model portfolios, etc.) and are reproducible, a new RM stepping in can re-run the same simulations on the client’s portfolio or proposed investments. However, if the departing RM had saved any specific projection reports or used them in a client proposal, those should be archived or made accessible to the new RM. There is minimal risk of system deadlock with the projection tool itself (as it doesn’t hold state that would block processes), but there is a *knowledge transfer aspect*: the incoming RM should be briefed on any performance analysis the client was shown or any strategy being pursued. Governance measures can include attaching any generated projection reports to the client’s record or notes. This way, the Supervisor and new RM have full visi	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765953887233_4k0vth05f","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-17T06:55:49.549Z"}	resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7	t	2025-12-17 06:55:50.802	2025-12-17 06:55:50.802	1	f	\N
