onfirmation:** In some setups, the calculated risk profile is shown for acknowledgment. Typically, the system does not allow arbitrarily overriding the computed profile. If the client disagrees with the result, the usual approach is to review answers or retake the questionnaire rather than manually set a different risk level.\\n\\nUpon completion, the system may present a summary of the client’s responses and the resulting risk profile for transparency. Only after successful profiling will the workflow proceed to saving the profile.\\n\\n## Storage, Updates, and Linkage to Client Records\\nOnce determined, the client’s risk profile is stored in their central client record:\\n- **Profile Record:** The risk profile category (and possibly the numeric score) is saved, along with the date of assessment and the questionnaire version used. This becomes part of the client’s profile data accessible to other modules.\\n- **Validity Period:** Many institutions assign a validity period to risk profiles (for example, one year). The system tracks the risk profile’s effective date and expiry. If the profile is outdated or expired, the platform will prompt for a new assessment.\\n- **Historical Data:** Previous risk profiles and their dates may be archived for reference and audit. This allows comparison over time (e.g. if a client’s risk tolerance changes, advisors can see the progression).\\n- **Linkage:** The risk profile is linked to the client’s account so that every investment transaction or portfolio analysis can reference it. It’s typically accessible on the client dashboard or financial profile screen for advisors to review at a glance.\\n\\nUpdating a risk profile involves re-running the questionnaire. The platform ensures that only authorized users can initiate an update, and it preserves the old profile record when a new one is saved.\\n\\n## Roles, Permissions & Approvals\\nProper controls ensure that risk profiling is conducted by appropriate parties:\\n- **Who Can Pro