y must therefore explicitly manage the interaction of these four concurrent workflows:\n\n1. Validations & Warnings (risk controls)  \n2. Supervisor Approval process  \n3. Performance Projection usage  \n4. Mutual Fund / Product Cart order workflow  \n\nand identify where these can collide to create:\n\n- **Process deadlocks** (items stuck with no actor able to move them), and  \n- **Supervisor visibility gaps** (items that exist but are hard to see or interpret).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Workflow 1 – Validations & Warnings\n\n**System logic**\n\n- **Soft stops**  \n  - Trigger warning pop‑ups (e.g., product risk slightly above client risk profile).  \n  - RM can override with justification; system logs deviation.  \n  - On submission, order is routed for higher approval (e.g., Circle/Zonal head, then Supervisor).\n\n- **Hard stops**  \n  - Trigger when a critical rule is breached (e.g., missing mandatory data, product far outside risk profile).  \n  - System **blocks** transaction until corrected.  \n  - Hard‑stop and soft‑stop items are listed in the **Product Cart deviation overlay**.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 1 – Unresolved hard stops**  \n  - Orders with hard‑stop issues created by the outgoing RM remain blocked.  \n  - If no one takes ownership to correct data or remove the product, the order is stuck indefinitely.\n\n- **Deadlock 2 – Soft‑stop overrides with no follow‑through**  \n  - Outgoing RM may have accepted warnings and submitted orders that still require higher‑level approval.  \n  - If these are not visible or reviewed, risk‑deviant orders may sit in limbo.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Deviations are visible at **order level** (Product Cart overlay), but:  \n  - There is no inherent “RM has left” flag on those deviations.  \n  - If the supervisor only looks at approvals by RM name, they may miss risk‑deviant orders tied to a now‑inactive RM.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Immediate sweep** after RM exit:\n  - Query all orders with:\n    - Hard‑stop deviations outstanding, and  \n    - Soft‑stop deviations accepted but still pending approval.\n- **Reassignment rule**:\n  - New RM or operations user must:\n    - Complete missing data/documents to clear hard stops, or  \n    - Remove non‑compliant products and re‑discuss with client.\n- **Supervisor check**:\n  - Supervisor re‑reviews all soft‑stop overrides from the outgoing RM before approval.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Workflow 2 – Supervisor Approval Process\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Orders submitted by RMs go to **“Pending Approval”**.  \n- Visible in **Supervisor Approval screen**:  \n  - Search by Order No., Scheme/Security, Customer Name.  \n  - Filter by Transaction Type and **RM Name**.  \n- Orders remain in the queue even if the originating RM becomes inactive.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 3 – Approvals stuck due to reliance on RM filter**  \n  - If the outgoing RM’s profile is disabled, filtering by RM name may no longer be reliable.  \n  - Pending approvals still exist but may not be surfaced if the supervisor relies only on that filter.\n\n- **Deadlock 4 – Multi‑level approvals with absent approver**  \n  - Orders escalated to intermediate approvers (e.g., Circle/Zonal head) can stall if that approver is unavailable and no escalation rule is applied.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are visible, but:\n  - They may be “orphaned” conceptually (no active RM to provide context).  \n  - There is no automatic consolidation of “all pending items from RM X who has left” unless the supervisor runs targeted queries.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Standard operating step on RM exit**:\n  - Supervisor runs a **pending approvals report** filtered by:\n    - Outgoing RM ID (if still available), and  \n    - Client IDs reassigned to the new RM.\n- **Escalation SLA**:\n  - Define time‑based rules:\n    - If an order remains in “Pending Approval” beyond X hours/days, it escalates to the next authority.  \n- **No re‑entry rule**:\n  - Orders already submitted by the outgoing RM are **not re‑captured**; they are reviewed and approved/rejected as is, with the new RM informed of context.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Workflow 3 – Performance Projection\n\n**System logic**\n\n- Performance Projection is an **analytical tool**:\n  - Simulates future performance under different scenarios.  \n  - Does not create or hold transactional state by itself.  \n  - Outputs (reports, illustrations) may be used in client discussions.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks**\n\n- No technical deadlock: projections do not block or gate orders.  \n- **Risk is advisory continuity**, not process blockage:\n  - Client may have seen a specific projection or strategy from the outgoing RM that is not documented.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- If projections or proposals are not attached to the client record:\n  - New RM and supervisor may not know what was shown or promised.  \n  - This can lead to inconsistent advice or client confusion.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Documentation rule**:\n  - Any projection used in a client proposal should be:\n    - Saved/attached to the client record, or  \n    - Summarized in client notes.\n- **Onboarding brief**:\n  - Supervisor ensures new RM:\n    - Re‑runs key projections for active opportunities, and  \n    - Aligns recommendations with what the client has already seen.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Workflow 4 – Mutual Funds & Product Cart\n\n**System logic**\n\n- RM builds orders in **Product Cart**:\n  - Product selection, validations, documentation checks, client OTP (if applicable), then submission.  \n- System supports **“Order(s) in Pending State”**:\n  - Partially completed orders can be saved and resumed.  \n- Certain transaction types require **mandatory document upload** before submission.\n\n**Collision / Deadlock risks during handover**\n\n- **Deadlock 5 – Orders in Pending State with no owner**  \n  - Outgoing RM leaves with partially completed orders saved but not submitted.  \n  - If not reassigned/reviewed, these instructions remain indefinitely in pending state.\n\n- **Deadlock 6 – Mandatory documents not uploaded**  \n  - Orders that require a document (e.g., physical mode redemption/switch) cannot be submitted without upload.  \n  - If the outgoing RM had not obtained/uploaded the document, the order is blocked.\n\n- **Deadlock 7 – Expired or incomplete client authentication (OTP)**  \n  - If OTP was initiated but not completed before RM exit, the transaction attempt expires.  \n  - No one triggers a fresh OTP; the order never progresses.\n\n**Supervisor visibility gaps**\n\n- Pending orders are tied to:\n  - Client ID and (original) RM ID.  \n- Without a targeted review of **“Order(s) in Pending State)”** for the outgoing RM’s clients, the supervisor may not see:\n  - Draft orders,  \n  - Orders awaiting documents, or  \n  - Orders awaiting client action.\n\n**Continuity controls**\n\n- **Pending bucket sweep**:\n  - On RM exit, operations/supervisor:\n    - Extract all “Order(s) in Pending State” for that RM’s clients.  \n    - Reassign to the new RM.\n- **Action rules** for each pending order:\n  - New RM must:\n    - Confirm with client whether to proceed, modify, or cancel.  \n    - Obtain and upload any mandatory documents.  \n    - Re‑initiate OTP or other client authentication as needed.\n- **Supervisor oversight**:\n  - Supervisor reviews Product Cart deviation overlays for:\n    - Missing documents,  \n    - Hard/soft stops,  \n    - Any “document upload is mandatory” flags.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cross‑Workflow Collision Analysis\n\nThe four workflows can overlap on the same order or client. Key collision patterns:\n\n1. **Pending Cart + Validations + Approvals**  \n   - Order in Product Cart with:\n     - Hard‑stop deviation unresolved, and  \n     - Not yet submitted for approval.  \n   - If RM leaves, order is stuck in Pending State with no path to approval.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Pending bucket sweep + new RM resolves deviations, then submits for approval.\n\n2. **Soft‑stop Override + Supervisor Approval + RM Exit**  \n   - Outgoing RM overrides a soft stop and submits.  \n   - Order is in supervisor queue with risk deviation.  \n   - If not explicitly reviewed, it may age in the queue.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Supervisor runs targeted report of all pending approvals with deviations from outgoing RM; applies escalation SLA.\n\n3. **Projection‑Driven Proposal + Draft Order**  \n   - RM shows client a projection, starts building a corresponding MF order, saves it, then exits.  \n   - New RM sees only a draft order with no context.  \n   - **Mitigation**: Require projection/proposal notes attached to client record; supervisor briefs new RM on strategy before order completion.\n\n4. **Mandatory Document + Multi‑Level Approval**  \n   - Order requires document upload and higher‑level approval.  \n   - Document not uploaded; RM exits; intermediate approver unavailable.  \n   - **Mitigation**: New RM/ops obtains document; escalation SLA ensures higher authority can approve if intermediate approver is absent.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Supervisor‑Centric Continuity Playbook\n\n**A. Immediate actions on RM exit**\n\n1. **Client & pipeline reassignment**\n   - Execute Handover to assign all clients to new RM/supervisor.\n\n2. **Queue sweeps**\n   - Supervisor/ops to extract:\n     - All **Pending Approval** orders created by outgoing RM.  \n     - All **Order(s) in Pending State)** for outgoing RM’s clients.  \n     - All orders with **hard/soft‑stop deviations** linked to those clients.\n\n3. **Visibility checks**\n   - Use multiple search keys:\n     - Client ID, Order No., Scheme/Security, not just RM name (in case RM profile is disabled).\n\n**B. Deadlock resolution rules**\n\n- **Hard stops**:  \n  - Must be cleared by new RM/ops (data/documents) or product removed.  \n- **Soft stops**:  \n  - Supervisor re‑validates risk acceptance; may request new RM to reconfirm with client.  \n- **Pending approvals**:  \n  - Apply escalation SLA if intermediate approver is unavailable.  \n- **Pending cart orders**:  \n  - New RM contacts client to confirm intent; either complete, modify, or cancel.\n\n**C. Governance & audit**\n\n- **Off‑boarding checklist for RM**:\n  - Confirm:\n    - All pending orders identified and reassigned.  \n    - All key client proposals/projections documented in client records.\n\n- **On‑boarding checklist for new RM**:\n  - Review:\n    - List of pending approvals and pending cart orders.  \n    - Deviations and documents outstanding.  \n    - Client notes and projection reports.\n\n- **Audit trail**:\n  - Use system logs to verify:\n    - Who reassigned orders,  \n    - Who overrode deviations,  \n    - Who approved or cancelled pending items during the handover window.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Summary of Deadlocks & Visibility Gaps\n\n**Potential Process Deadlocks**\n\n1. Orders blocked by **unresolved hard stops**.  \n2. **Pending approvals** tied to an inactive RM or unavailable approver.  \n3. **Pending cart orders** with no active owner.  \n4. Orders requiring **mandatory documents** that were never obtained.  \n5. Transactions with **expired OTP/authentication** not retriggered.\n\n**Potential Supervisor Visibility Gaps**\n\n1. Reliance on **RM‑name filters** when RM profile is disabled.  \n2. Lack of consolidated view of:\n   - All **pending approvals**,  \n   - All **pending cart orders**,  \n   - All **deviation‑bearing orders** for the outgoing RM’s clients.  \n3. Missing documentation of **projections/proposals**, leading to advisory discontinuity.\n\n**Core Strategy**\n\n- Use existing system queues (Pending Approval, Pending State, deviation overlays) as **control points**.  \n- Make supervisor responsible for:\n  - Sweeping these queues on RM exit,  \n  - Reassigning and resolving items,  \n  - Enforcing escalation SLAs.  \n- Ensure all advisory context (projections, risk deviations, documents) is attached to client records so the new RM can continue seamlessly.\n\nThis integrated approach minimizes operational, compliance, and client‑experience risk during an abrupt RM handover.	{\n  "stepback_intent": "To develop a strategy ensuring business continuity when a Relationship Manager (RM) leaves abruptly, by examining how the system manages four overlapping workflows (validations/warnings, supervisor approvals, performance projections, and mutual fund order processing) and identifying any process deadlocks or visibility issues for the supervisor.",\n  "expanded_question": "How can we create an operational continuity plan for an abrupt RM handover, focusing on how the system’s logic handles the overlap of four workflows (validations & warnings, supervisor approval processes, performance projections, and mutual fund order/product cart workflows) and pinpointing potential process deadlocks or supervisor visibility gaps, along with necessary recovery actions, escalations, and governance controls?",\n  "business_entities": [\n    "Validations and Warning",\n    "Supervisor Approval screen",\n    "Performance Projection",\n    "Mutual Funds",\n    "product cart"\n  ],\n  "citations": [\n    {"id": "1", "source": "Handover and Delegation (v10) - Internal Product Document"},\n    {"id": "2", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Risk & Authorization (v11)"},\n    {"id": "3", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Supervisor Approval Process"},\n    {"id": "4", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Performance Projection Feature"},\n    {"id": "5", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Product Cart Validations"},\n    {"id": "6", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Documentation Requirements"},\n    {"id": "7", "source": "Journey from Order Placement to Settlement - Pending Orders Workflow"}\n  ],\n  "answer": "**Operational Continuity Strategy for Abrupt RM Handover**\\n\\nWhen a Relationship Manager exits unexpectedly, the system must seamlessly transfer all ongoing activities and client data to maintain service continuity. The first step is to immediately reassign the departing RM’s clients, prospects, and leads to an active RM (or a supervisor) using the platform’s handover functionality. This *Handover* process permanently remaps each customer record and pipeline item to the new owner, ensuring no client is left unmanaged and formally establishing who is responsible for day-to-day management going forward ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=1,nature%2C%20then%20Delegation%20is%20used)) ([file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1](file://file-35YkkRqiZAmfVJNhatPuk1#:~:text=4,from%20the%20Relationship%20Handover%20screen)). Alongside the reallocation of clients, a thorough review of in-flight workflows is necessary to avoid any stalled transactions or oversight lapses. Four critical concurrent workflows require special attention during the handover:\\n\\n1. **Validations & Warnings (Risk Controls)** – The wealth platform enforces both *soft stops* and *hard stops* to uphold compliance and suitability rules during order entry. Soft-stop validations trigger warning pop-ups (for example, if a chosen product’s risk level is slightly above the client’s risk profile) that the RM can acknowledge and override with justification ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=7,will%20go%20first%20to%20Circle)). In these cases, the system logs the deviation and, upon order submission, automatically escalates the order for higher approval – first to a senior manager (e.g. Circle or Zonal head) and then to the Supervisor for final sign-off ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=8,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). By contrast, hard-stop validations indicate a critical breach (such as a product far outside the client’s risk tolerance or missing mandatory details) and **block the transaction entirely**, preventing the RM from proceeding until the issue is resolved ([file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4](file://file-MdBP6kEH9N4aqQJdyjwJH4#:~:text=9,will%20not%20allow%20transactions%20in)). During an abrupt handover, any soft-stop warnings that were acknowledged by the outgoing RM become important flags for the incoming RM and supervisors. The system’s Product Cart interface highlights all such deviations in an order overlay – listing any hard-stop issues (e.g. “Guardian details required for minor nominee”) and soft-stop warnings associated with that transaction ([file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA](file://file-TYXBsCKEm553VNnW8SHNFA#:~:text=Product%20Cart%20,Not%20Applicabl%20e%20Example%3A%20Guardian)). As part of the continuity plan, the Supervisor should review these deviation lists for any pending orders the former RM was handling, to ensure that accepted risks or pending requirements won’t be overlooked. If a hard-stop condition was left unresolved by the time of handover, that order cannot move forward – creating a potential deadlock. The resolution would be to have the new RM or an operations user provide the required information or documentation to clear the hard stop, or else remove the non-compliant product from the order. In summary, the continuity strategy calls for **capturing and transferring all validation outcomes**: warnings need to be revalidated by the new RM and approved by the supervisor, and no order should remain blocked due to an unmet hard-stop condition.\\n\\n2. **Supervisor Approval Process** – Every investment order initiated by an RM must ultimately be authorized by a supervisor (or designated approver) before execution. When an RM submits an order, it enters a *“Pending Approval”* state and becomes visible in the Supervisor’s approval queue ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=SBI_Journey%20from%20Order%20Placement%20till,in%20the%20top%20panel)) ([file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF](file://file-4cicPP7UemwRK7RbBfT9YF#:~:text=Supervisor%20Approval%20screen%20Screen%3A%20Supervisor,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). The Supervisor uses the **Supervisor Approval screen** (accessible via a dedicated icon in the application) to view and process all pending orders. On this screen, orders awaiting approval are listed and can be searched by various criteria such as Order Number, Security/Scheme, or Customer Name ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=3,pending%20for%20approval%20is%20displayed)). Notably, the interface also allows filtering by *Transaction Type* and by *RM Name*, so a supervisor can display orders associated with a particular RM under their oversight ([file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU](file://file-VWuv4i6A5CU1yCaGXjRUxU#:~:text=5,Customer%20and%20Intellect%20Page%2050)). In an abrupt handover scenario, this filtering mechanism introduces a **visibility consideration**: if a departing RM’s orders are still pending approval, they may initially be indexed under that RM’s name. The continuity plan should ensure that supervisors actively search by client or order number if needed, rather than relying solely on the RM filter, especially if the outgoing RM’s profile is inactivated or removed from the reporting hierarchy. The system should not drop or hide pending approvals even if the RM who created them is no longer active; those orders remain in the queue until acted upon. To prevent any *process deadlock*, the organization can define an escalation timeline for approvals – for example, if an order sits in “Pending Approval” beyond a certain cutoff (perhaps due to an intermediate approver like a department head being unavailable), the next higher authority or the supervisor can intervene to approve or reroute it. This ensures that orders do not languish unapproved due to the absence of the originating RM or any approver in the chain. All approval decisions and any overrides (such as approving an order that had a risk warning) are logged for audit. As a governance control, the Supervisor taking over should run a report of all pending orders by that outgoing RM and verify their status. Any order that was submitted by the old RM will follow the normal authorization flow – meaning the new RM typically does *not* need to re-enter it, but the supervisor should communicate with the incoming RM about the context of that order (especially if there were risk deviations or special client instructions attached).\\n\\n3. **Performance Projection Tools** – The platform provides a *Performance Projection* feature that allows RMs to simulate and view the potential future performance of selected securities or portfolios under various scenarios (e.g. optimistic, current, and pessimistic market conditions) ([file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9](file://file-G4s1vqs2gpqzTtdnScmuB9#:~:text=7.%20Performance%20Projection%20,the%20calculator%20on%20Max%20Drawdown)). RMs often use this functionality during product selection to illustrate potential returns and risks to clients. While this workflow is more analytical (it doesn’t create a transaction by itself), it runs in parallel with the order-building process and can inform an RM’s recommendations. In the context of an RM handover, the continuity strategy should ensure that any insights or materials generated from these projections are not lost. Since the projections are based on underlying data (prices, model portfolios, etc.) and are reproducible, a new RM stepping in can re-run the same simulations on the client’s portfolio or proposed investments. However, if the departing RM had saved any specific projection reports or used them in a client proposal, those should be archived or made accessible to the new RM. There is minimal risk of system deadlock with the projection tool itself (as it doesn’t hold state that would block processes), but there is a *knowledge transfer aspect*: the incoming RM should be briefed on any performance analysis the client was shown or any strategy being pursued. Governance measures can include attaching any generated projection reports to the client’s record or notes. This way, the Supervisor and new RM have full visi	{"polled":true,"poll_status":"completed","domainResolution":{"domainId":"wealth_management","strategy":"conversation","confidence":1,"matchedKeywords":[]},"jobId":"job_1765953887233_4k0vth05f","status":"completed","responseId":"resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7","reportFormat":"Custom","mode":"deep","answeredAt":"2025-12-17T06:55:49.899Z"}	resp_0b60d6027530799e006942515e2a40819fb7ca0284f3e615d7	t	2025-12-17 06:55:51.497	2025-12-19 10:13:48.393	5	f	\N
