ned to be scorable, while others are non-scorable and used to gauge knowledge of wealth products; both inform the overall risk profile [1].\n  - In practice, the risk profile questionnaire is maintained and linked to the customer’s risk profile, with options to record timelines and history (e.g., risk score history, risk category history) for governance and audit purposes [1].\n  - The process often includes a formal risk profile questionnaire and validation steps, which can generate a “Recommended Risk Profile” and feed into the suitability framework (e.g., SAF) [2].\n\n- Inputs that shape the risk profile\n  - Common inputs include the client’s goals, time horizon, liquidity needs, and broader financial objectives, which feed into the risk assessment and asset-allocation decisions. Time horizon and risk appetite influence the chosen risk profile that governs asset allocation decisions [2].\n\n- How risk profiles map to risk categories\n  - Risk profiling yields a defined risk category or score that corresponds to an expected level of return and volatility, forming a basis for asset allocation decisions and performance expectations. Systems often maintain a history of risk scores and risk categories associated with each profile [1][3].\n  - The risk profile is linked to asset allocation rules (e.g., Asset Allocation details drive how investments are allocated according to the profile) and may be described in risk-profile questionnaires and related documentation [2].\n\n- How profiles drive portfolio construction, client segmentation, and regulatory/compliance\n  - Portfolio construction is guided by the risk profile; asset allocation is maintained for the selected risk profile, ensuring alignment with the client’s risk tolerance and objectives [2].\n  - Risk profiling supports client segmentation by grouping customers according to their profiles and risk appetite, enabling targeted strategies and communications consistent with risk tolerance levels [2].\n  - Regulatory/suitability compliance is embedded in the process through components like the Risk Profile Questionnaire and the Suitability Assessment Form, ensuring that recommendations match the client’s profile and regulatory requirements [2].\n\n- Practical governance aspects (examples across implementations)\n  - Some implementations document maintenance workflows for risk profiling, including risk appetite mapping, risk-profile maintenance, and knowledge checks, underscoring ongoing governance and auditability of risk profiles [1].\n  - The risk profile information is often referenced in downstream screens or journeys (e.g., risk profile prompts during product selection or asset allocation steps), illustrating how profiling interacts with the client journey and decision points [2].\n\nSources\n- 360One_Journey of Assesing Risk_V10_CCV15.pdf [1]\n- HSBC_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf [2]\n- SBI_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV12.pdf [3]	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["risk profiling","INVESTOR","RM","Order","customer","transaction","Product risk profile","CIF id","securities","warning message"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:customer","dataentity:cif_id","dataentity:securities","dataentity:rm","report:warning_message","compliance:risk_profiling","dataentity:risk_profiling","dataentity:product_risk_profile","aum:risk_profiling","system:rmws","dataentity:transaction","dataentity:order","dataentity:investor","dataentity:warning_message"],"expanded_nodes":48,"expanded_edges":78,"kg_guided_queries":["[Focused Response Directive]\\n\\nPlease follow these instructions when answering:\\n• Answer ONLY the specific question asked - be precise and direct\\n• Include ONLY information that is immediately relevant to this specific question\\n• Exclude tangential details, background context, or loosely related information\\n• Be concise while remaining comprehensive on the core topic\\n• Prioritize clarity and relevance over exhaustiv