informs frequency\n- Asset drift is monitored through deviation and exposure views that compare model allocations to actual holdings (model vs. actual vs. selected asset-class allocations). This drift information is used to determine when rebalancing should be considered, as deviations signal misalignment with the target allocation [2].\n\nFactors shaping the recommended frequency\n- Drift thresholds / deviation levels: The need to rebalance is driven by how far actual allocations have deviated from the model targets, as surfaced by deviation/exposure measurements [2].\n- Risk tolerance and client objectives: The chosen cadence and trigger thresholds reflect the client's risk appetite and stated goals, which influence how aggressively allocations are kept in line with targets [1].\n- Tax and transaction cost considerations: Frequency and trigger selection balance the desire to maintain target allocations with the potential tax consequences and costs of trading [1].\n- Asset-class behavior and platform governance: The behavior of underlying asset classes and the governance/workflow configuration of the platform (e.g., model order approval workflows) influence how and when rebalancing is executed [1], and how deviations are presented to users for decisioning [2].\n\nPractical takeaway\n- Most wealth-management implementations support both time-based cadences and deviation-driven triggers, with the exact frequency and trigger rules configurable in the model/portfolio setup. This allows tailoring to client objectives, risk tolerance, and cost/tax considerations while maintaining appropriate governance and control over rebalancing actions [1][2].\n\nSources\n- [1] EID031 - Model Portfolio_Basket Based Investments.docx\n- [2] SBI_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement - MF V10_SBI_CCV13.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Selected Portfolio - Asset Class","Asset Class wise Product Composition","Product Composition – A