ation approach is tailored to the individual client. [1]\n- Model portfolios provide a structured, repeatable framework for diversification. Model Portfolio Maintenance defines and maintains the diversified holdings, and the model is integrated with the portfolio management system to translate the allocation into executable orders. This enables consistent diversification across clients mapped to the same framework. [4]\n\nHow diversification is implemented in practice\n- Asset-class and sector exposure management\n  Diversification is operationalized by capturing and presenting asset-class wise and sector-wise composition for each security in the portfolio. This visibility ensures that the overall portfolio spreads risk across broad asset classes and industry exposures rather than concentrating in a narrow subset. [2]\n- Product selection and portfolio construction\n  The product selection process exposes multiple instruments within a consolidated framework (e.g., mutual funds or other eligible products) that are then combined into a model portfolio. The selection screen enables assembling a diversified basket that reflects the intended allocation across asset classes and sectors, which is subsequently executed through the PMS integration. [4]\n- Monitoring, governance, and rebalancing\n  Diversification is actively maintained through governance-enabled maintenance of model portfolios and automated alerts. Alert rules monitor portfolio performance and diversification integrity (e.g., portfolio rebalancing alerts), triggering reviews or rebalance actions as needed. This ensures that the portfolio remains aligned with the client’s risk profile and evolving market conditions. [5]\n\nEnd-to-end flow supporting diversification\n- Risk profiling feeds into asset allocation and diversification decisions, informing the target allocations and allowable concentration limits. This linkage ensures that diversification is not static but evolves with the client’s risk posture. [1]\n- The model portfolio construct, order placement, and PMS integration enable disciplined execution of a diversified allocation, with product overlays and exposure visibility guiding ongoing adjustments. [4]\n- Asset-class and sector exposure data are surfaced at the product/overlay level to ensure that diversification is measured and managed within the client’s holdings. [2]\n- Alerts and governance mechanisms provide continuous oversight and trigger diversification-related actions (e.g., rebalancing) when required by performance, risk, or policy deviations. [5]\n\nIn summary\nDiversification in wealth management is a systemic, risk-profile-driven discipline that combines risk assessment, model portfolio design, asset-class/sector exposure visibility, disciplined execution through PMS workflows, and continuous monitoring with governance-backed rebalancing. This integrated approach supports spreading risk across a broad set of assets and exposures while staying aligned with each client’s objectives and constraints. [1][2][3][4][5]\n\nSources\n- [1] JBR_Journey of Assesing Risk_V1_CCV1.pdf\n- [2] HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 1.pdf\n- [3] HSBC_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV10_Part 2.pdf\n- [4] 360ONE_Journey from Order Placement till Settlement_V11_CCV13_Part 1.pdf\n- [5] IIFL_Journey of Defining Maintenance_V10_CCV13_Part 3.pdf	\N	{"v2_workflow":true,"mode":"concise","model":"gpt-5-nano","seed_node_names":["Product Composition – Asset Class","Asset Class wise Product Composition","Selected Portfolio - Asset Class","Selected Portfolio - Sector","Mutual Fund – View Deviation & Exposure","Mutual Funds","Exposures","Risk Appetite Mapping","Model Portfolio – Order Placement","Model Portfolio Maintenance"],"seed_node_ids":["dataentity:product_composition_asset_class","system:model_pf_maintenance","dataentity:asset_class_wise_product_composition","report:selected_pf_sector","dataentity:model_pf_maintenance","report